const D_SKILLS = {

mud:[
  {t:"Mud Therapy — Principles & Physiological Effects",badge:"Foundation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Definition</div>Mud therapy (Mrittikapachanam) uses wet earth / clay as a therapeutic agent. Its cooling, absorptive, anti-inflammatory, and detoxifying properties make it a fundamental naturopathic modality.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Therapeutic Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Heat absorption</td><td>High specific heat capacity of wet clay draws heat from body</td><td>Reduces local inflammation, fever, headache</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mineral content</td><td>Silica, magnesium, calcium, iron absorbed transdermally</td><td>Skin nourishment, joint support</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Absorptive action</td><td>Clay draws toxins, excess sebum, and waste products</td><td>Skin detoxification, acne, psoriasis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mechanical pressure</td><td>Weight of mud pack applies gentle compression</td><td>Reduces oedema, improves lymphatic drainage</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Relaxant effect</td><td>Parasympathetic stimulation via skin receptors</td><td>Muscle relaxation, stress reduction</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Ideal mud for therapy</div><div class="pt">Best therapeutic mud: black cotton soil or fullers earth (multani mitti) — high mineral content, fine texture. Should be collected from 3–4 feet depth (free of contaminants, pesticides, worms). Sun-dry, powder, sieve, and store in earthen pot. Reconstitute with clean water to a paste consistency (like soft dough) before application. Never use mud from near chemical factories, cremation grounds, or stagnant water sources.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Mud Pack — Types & Application Technique",badge:"Technique",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Area</th><th>Mud thickness</th><th>Duration</th><th>Indication</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Mud pack — local</td><td>Abdomen, eyes, head, back</td><td>1.5–2 cm</td><td>20–30 min</td><td>Constipation, fever, headache, inflammation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mud bath — full body</td><td>Entire body (except head)</td><td>1 cm all over</td><td>20–45 min</td><td>Skin diseases, arthritis, obesity, stress</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mud bath — partial</td><td>Arms, legs, or trunk only</td><td>1 cm</td><td>20–30 min</td><td>Joint pain, varicose veins, local skin conditions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mud compress</td><td>Small local area</td><td>0.5–1 cm on cloth</td><td>15–20 min</td><td>Sprains, bruises, swelling, insect bites</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Preparation</span> — Wet mud to soft paste. Spread evenly on muslin cloth or directly on skin. Temperature: room temperature (cool) for inflammatory conditions; slightly warm for chronic stiffness.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Application</span> — Apply in smooth strokes in one direction. Cover with thin cloth or wet bandage to retain moisture. Patient should be comfortable and warm.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Duration & removal</span> — Remove before mud dries completely (retains heat once dry). Wipe with damp cloth, then warm water. Pat dry — do not rub.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Post-treatment</span> — Rest for 15–20 min. Avoid exposure to cold/wind. Offer warm herbal tea. Record skin response and patient feedback.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Abdominal mud pack</div><div class="pt">Most commonly prescribed mud application in BNYS. Indication: constipation, IBS, indigestion, hyperacidity, colitis, liver disorders, obesity. Apply cool mud pack from navel to pubic symphysis, width of palm on either side. 20–30 minutes, morning before breakfast or 3 hours after meals. The cooling effect reduces intestinal inflammation, improves peristalsis, and calms vagal tone. Course: daily × 14 days for chronic conditions.</pt></div>`},
  {t:"Eye Mud Pack",badge:"Technique",c:`
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Indication</div>Eye strain, conjunctivitis (non-infective), headache from eye strain, refractive errors (adjunct), dark circles, periorbital puffiness, early cataract (adjunct).</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Preparation</span> — Wet refined mud (no grit) to soft, smooth consistency. Shape into two oval pads (5×3 cm, 1 cm thick) on gauze strips.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Position</span> — Patient supine, eyes closed. Place mud pads gently over closed eyelids. No pressure on eyeball.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Duration</span> — 10–20 minutes. Monitor every 5 min for discomfort. Remove if patient feels pressure or irritation.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Removal</span> — Remove gently. Ask patient to keep eyes closed for 2 minutes. Splash cool clean water gently over closed eyes. Pat dry.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Contraindications</div>Acute conjunctivitis (infective), corneal ulcer, open wounds around eyes, skin infections, known eye allergies, recent eye surgery.</div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Course of treatment</div><div class="pt">For refractive errors and eye strain: daily morning application × 21 days, then alternate days × 1 month. Combine with netra tarpana (ghee eye bath in Ayurveda context), palming exercises, and screen time reduction. Never use mud with visible grit on eyes — filter through 3 layers of muslin before preparing eye packs. Refrigerated mud packs are more effective for conjunctivitis and headache.</pt></div>`},
  {t:"Mud Therapy — Contraindications & Precautions",badge:"Safety",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Absolute contraindications</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Reason</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Open wounds, cuts, ulcers</td><td>Infection risk — mud is not sterile</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Active skin infections (fungal, bacterial)</td><td>May spread infection</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Severe eczema / psoriasis (acute)</td><td>May irritate broken skin</td></tr>
      <tr><td>High fever (&gt;103°F / 39.4°C)</td><td>Full body mud bath may cause collapse</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Severe cardiac / renal failure</td><td>Circulatory stress from full body mud bath</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pregnancy (abdominal application)</td><td>Pressure contraindicated</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Precautions</div>Always check for clay/mineral allergies. Patch test 24hr before first application. Warm patient before and after in cold climates. Never apply over varicose veins with broken skin. Elderly and debilitated patients: shorter duration, constant monitoring.</div>`}
],

diet:[
  {t:"Naturopathic Diet Therapy — Principles",badge:"Foundation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Core BNYS principle</div>"Let food be thy medicine" — Hippocrates. Diet is the first and most fundamental therapeutic tool in naturopathy. All other treatments are secondary to correct nutrition.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Principle</th><th>Application</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Vitalism through whole foods</td><td>Unprocessed, unrefined, locally grown, seasonal foods carry highest vital energy (prana)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Eliminative diet</td><td>Reduce toxic load: avoid processed, preserved, refined, chemically treated foods</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Individualisation</td><td>Diet tailored to constitution (prakriti), current condition (vikriti), digestion, and climate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acid-alkaline balance</td><td>70% alkaline-forming : 30% acid-forming ratio for optimal tissue health</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Raw food emphasis</td><td>Raw fruits and vegetables retain enzymes, vitamins, and vital force — cook minimally</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mindful eating</td><td>Eat slowly, chew thoroughly (32 times per mouthful), in calm environment, with gratitude</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Alkaline vs acid forming foods</div><div class="pt">Alkaline-forming (eat freely): all fruits (even citrus — alkaline ASH), all vegetables, sprouts, millet, seeds, nuts (most), coconut water. Acid-forming (limit): meat, fish, eggs, dairy, refined grains, sugar, alcohol, coffee. Note: it is the ASH residue after metabolism — not the taste — that determines acid/alkaline effect. Lemon is alkaline-forming despite being acidic in taste.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Therapeutic Diet Types — Quick Reference",badge:"Reference",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Diet Type</th><th>Composition</th><th>Duration</th><th>Indication</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Eliminative / Detox diet</td><td>Fruits only, fruit juices, coconut water, raw vegetables</td><td>1–7 days</td><td>Detoxification, acute conditions, obesity start, skin diseases</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mono diet</td><td>Single food only (e.g., grapes, watermelon, papaya)</td><td>1–3 days</td><td>Digestive rest, specific organ support</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Alkaline / Anti-inflammatory diet</td><td>70% raw fruits + vegetables, sprouts, seeds</td><td>Ongoing</td><td>Arthritis, autoimmune, metabolic syndrome, cancer adjunct</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Raw food diet</td><td>Uncooked fruits, vegetables, nuts, seeds, sprouts only</td><td>1–4 weeks</td><td>Obesity, constipation, skin diseases, hypertension</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Satvic diet</td><td>Fresh, light, easily digestible; no meat, onion, garlic, alcohol</td><td>Lifelong ideal</td><td>Mental clarity, spiritual practice, chronic disease management</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Elimination diet</td><td>Remove top allergens: gluten, dairy, eggs, soy, corn, peanuts</td><td>4–6 weeks then reintroduce</td><td>Food intolerance, IBS, eczema, migraine, autoimmune</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Specific carbohydrate diet (SCD)</td><td>No grains, no dairy (except specific), no refined sugar</td><td>Minimum 1 year</td><td>IBD, SIBO, Crohn's, ulcerative colitis</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},
  {t:"Fasting Therapy — Types & Protocols",badge:"Core",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Fasting principle in naturopathy</div>Fasting is the most powerful natural tool for self-healing. It directs vital energy from digestion to elimination and repair. "The physician within" is activated by fasting.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Fasting Type</th><th>Duration</th><th>Intake allowed</th><th>Indication</th><th>Supervision</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Water fast</td><td>1–3 days (short); 7–21 days (therapeutic)</td><td>Water only (2–3L/day)</td><td>Obesity, hypertension, chronic toxicity, spiritual</td><td>Mandatory &gt;3 days</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Juice fast</td><td>3–21 days</td><td>Fresh fruit/vegetable juices, coconut water</td><td>Detox, weight loss, skin diseases, digestive disorders</td><td>Recommended</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fruit fast</td><td>3–7 days</td><td>Fresh fruits only (no bananas/dates initially)</td><td>Milder detox, good for beginners, diabetics (with care)</td><td>Self-supervised possible</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intermittent fast (16:8)</td><td>Ongoing</td><td>All food within 8-hour window</td><td>Metabolic syndrome, obesity, insulin resistance, longevity</td><td>Self-managed</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ekadashi fast</td><td>2 days/month (lunar 11th)</td><td>Fruits/water only</td><td>Digestive rest, spiritual, gut microbiome reset</td><td>Self-managed</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#92400e">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Preparation (3 days pre-fast)</span> — Gradually eliminate meat, dairy, cooked grains. Increase fruits and vegetables. Reduce portion size. Clear bowel with enema or laxative herbs.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#92400e">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">During fast</span> — Rest, light yoga/walking only. Plenty of water/juice. Daily enema or colonic irrigation for fasts &gt;3 days. Monitor BP, pulse, urine output, ketones.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#92400e">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Breaking the fast (most critical)</span> — Break with diluted fresh juice first, then small amount of fruit. Never break with solid food. Take same number of days as fasting to return to normal diet. Breaking wrongly can cause refeeding syndrome.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Healing crisis during fasting</div><div class="pt">Expect: headache (days 1–2), fatigue, irritability, bad breath, coated tongue, skin breakouts, body odour — these are signs of active detoxification, not side effects. Distinguish from dangerous symptoms: severe hypoglycaemia (trembling, confusion), cardiac palpitations, BP drop &gt;20mmHg, vomiting blood. Never fast patients with T1DM, active TB, severe anaemia (Hb &lt;8), eating disorders, or cachexia.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Fasting — Contraindications & Monitoring",badge:"Safety",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Absolute contraindications to therapeutic fasting</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Reason</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Type 1 Diabetes Mellitus</td><td>Rapid DKA risk without insulin</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Active tuberculosis</td><td>Caloric restriction worsens TB</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Severe anaemia (Hb &lt;8 g/dL)</td><td>Further depletion risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cachexia / severe underweight (BMI &lt;16)</td><td>Life-threatening further loss</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pregnancy / breastfeeding</td><td>Fetal/infant nutrition requirements</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Active eating disorders</td><td>Psychological harm, refeeding risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Recent surgery (&lt;4 weeks)</td><td>Healing requires adequate protein/calories</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Severe cardiac failure</td><td>Electrolyte imbalance risk</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Weight check</div><div class="nv-val">Daily (expect 0.5–1 kg/day)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">BP monitoring</div><div class="nv-val">Twice daily (orthostatic)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Urine output</div><div class="nv-val">Minimum 1L/day</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Blood glucose</div><div class="nv-val">If diabetic: 4× daily</div></div>
    </div>`}
],

yoga:[
  {t:"Yoga Therapy Assessment — Initial Evaluation",badge:"Framework",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">BNYS yoga assessment principle</div>Yoga therapy in BNYS is therapeutic yoga — not fitness yoga. The goal is to select the right practice for the right patient at the right time. Assessment must precede prescription.</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#7c3aed">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Structural assessment</span> — Posture (standing, sitting), spinal alignment (kyphosis, lordosis, scoliosis), joint ROM (shoulder, hip, spine), muscle tightness (hamstrings, hip flexors, thoracic), balance (single leg stand), gait.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#7c3aed">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Breath assessment</span> — Rate (normal 12–16/min), pattern (chest vs diaphragmatic), depth, smoothness, breath-holding capacity (BHT), any breathlessness at rest or exertion.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#7c3aed">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Energy / vitality</span> — Sleep quality, fatigue level (VAS), digestion, elimination pattern, stress levels (PSS score), mood (PHQ-9, GAD-7).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#7c3aed">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Contraindication screen</span> — Recent surgery, fractures, acute disc prolapse, severe HTN (&gt;180/110), advanced glaucoma, pregnancy stage, cardiac history, dizziness/vertigo.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#7c3aed">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Goal setting</span> — What does the patient want to achieve? Pain relief, stress reduction, weight management, spiritual practice, disease management? Set realistic, measurable goals.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Breath-holding time (BHT)</div><div class="pt">Simple clinical marker of respiratory and cardiovascular health. Normal: 25–40 seconds. &lt;20 seconds = significant dysfunction (poor parasympathetic tone, CO₂ sensitivity, anxiety). &gt;40 seconds = good cardiovascular fitness. Measure: normal exhale, then hold, time to first urge to breathe. Improves significantly with pranayama practice — a useful treatment outcome marker.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Yoga Prescription by Condition",badge:"Clinical",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Recommended Asanas</th><th>Pranayama</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Hypertension</td><td>Shavasana ★, Makarasana, seated forward bends, gentle inversions (Viparita Karani)</td><td>Nadi Shodhana ★, Bhramari, Ujjayi — slow rhythm</td><td>Kapalbhati, Bhastrika, strong inversions (Sirsasana), Surya Namaskar (vigorous)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Type 2 Diabetes</td><td>Pavanamuktasana, Mandukasana, Dhanurasana, Ardha Matsyendrasana, Surya Namaskar (slow)</td><td>Kapalbhati ★ (gentle), Bhastrika, Anulom-Vilom</td><td>None specific — adjust intensity to fitness</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Low back pain</td><td>Pawanmuktasana series, Cat-Cow, Balasana, Bhujangasana (gentle), Setu Bandhasana</td><td>Nadi Shodhana, Ujjayi</td><td>Halasana, Paschimottanasana (acute phase), deep twists (acute)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Anxiety / Depression</td><td>Surya Namaskar (slow ×5), Ustrasana, Matsyasana, Viparita Karani, Shavasana ★, Yoga Nidra ★</td><td>Bhramari ★, Nadi Shodhana, 4-7-8 breathing</td><td>Intense practices if highly anxious initially</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Obesity</td><td>Surya Namaskar ★ (build to 12 rounds), standing poses, Navasana, Ardha Chandrasana</td><td>Kapalbhati ★, Bhastrika, Agni Sara</td><td>None if no joint problems — modify for knees</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Asthma / COPD</td><td>Makarasana, chest-opening asanas (Bhujangasana, Matsyasana), Shavasana</td><td>Pursed lip breathing, Ujjayi ★, Anulom-Vilom — NEVER Kapalbhati in acute</td><td>Kapalbhati (acute), Bhastrika, forceful breathing</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypothyroidism</td><td>Sarvangasana (Shoulderstand) ★, Halasana, Matsyasana, Ujjayi, Simhasana</td><td>Ujjayi ★, Bhramari</td><td>None specific</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Yoga Nidra — therapeutic goldmine</div><div class="pt">Yoga Nidra (yogic sleep) is the single most powerful stress-reduction tool in BNYS — 30 minutes = 2–3 hours of deep sleep physiologically. Induces theta brainwave state (4–8 Hz). Clinical evidence: ↓ cortisol, ↓ sympathetic tone, ↑ DHEA, ↓ PTSD symptoms, ↓ chronic pain scores, ↓ diabetes-related distress. Prescription: 30 min daily, same time, supine. Start with guided recording (Bihar School of Yoga format). No contraindications except severe psychosis.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Pranayama — Clinical Guide",badge:"Core",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Pranayama</th><th>Technique</th><th>Effect</th><th>Dose</th><th>Contraindication</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Anulom-Vilom (Nadi Shodhana)</td><td>Alternate nostril: 4 in left, 8 hold, 8 out right; reverse</td><td>↑ HRV, ANS balance, ↓ anxiety, ↑ cognitive function</td><td>5–10 min daily</td><td>None</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kapalbhati</td><td>Passive inhalation, active sharp exhalation; 1/sec</td><td>↑ Metabolism, ↓ blood sugar, abdominal toning, expectorant</td><td>3–5 min; build slowly</td><td>HTN (severe), epilepsy, pregnancy, hernia, acute asthma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bhramari</td><td>Hum on exhale with fingers on face (Shanmukhi mudra)</td><td>↑ Nitric oxide, ↓ BP, vagal stimulation, calming</td><td>5–7 rounds, 2× daily</td><td>Severe ear infection</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bhastrika</td><td>Forceful inhalation AND exhalation equally</td><td>↑ O₂, energising, clears nadis, ↑ metabolic rate</td><td>3 rounds × 10 breaths</td><td>HTN, cardiac disease, epilepsy, pregnancy, hernia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ujjayi</td><td>Constrict throat slightly, ocean-sound breath; 6–8/min</td><td>Calming, ↑ HRV, ↑ endurance, thyroid stimulation</td><td>Throughout yoga practice or 10 min</td><td>None</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sheetali / Sheetkari</td><td>Inhale through curled tongue/teeth; exhale nose</td><td>Cooling, ↓ BP, ↓ pitta, thirst, hunger management</td><td>5–10 rounds</td><td>Low BP, cold/asthma, excess kapha</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Sequence of practice</div><div class="pt">Correct order: Asanas → Pranayama → Meditation/Yoga Nidra → Shavasana. Never reverse. Reason: asanas prepare the body and nervous system for pranayama; pranayama prepares the mind for meditation. Pranayama on an unprepared body (without asanas) can cause hyperventilation, dizziness, and emotional release. Minimum gap of 4 hours after meals for vigorous asanas; 2 hours for pranayama only.</div></div>`}
],

acup:[
  {t:"Acupressure — Principles & Theory",badge:"Foundation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Principle</div>Acupressure stimulates specific points (acupoints) on the body along energy channels (meridians) to restore the free flow of vital energy (Qi/Prana), correct imbalances, and activate the body's self-healing mechanisms.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Concept</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Meridians (Nadis)</td><td>14 main energy channels (12 organ meridians + 2 extraordinary). Each linked to specific organ systems.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acupoints</td><td>365 classical points + extra points. Located at energy junctions with measurable electrical resistance differences.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tonification vs Sedation</td><td>Clockwise pressure = tonifies (strengthens). Anticlockwise = sedates (calms). Sustained pressure = balancing.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Zone therapy (reflexology)</td><td>Hands, feet, and ears contain reflex maps of entire body. Stimulation affects corresponding organs.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mechanism (modern)</td><td>Endorphin release, gate control pain theory, autonomic modulation, local micro-circulation improvement</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Deqi sensation</div><div class="pt">The therapeutic sensation at a correctly stimulated acupoint: dull ache, heaviness, tingling, warmth, or electric-like sensation radiating along the meridian. This is "Deqi" — means the Qi has arrived. It indicates correct point location and adequate stimulation. Absence of Deqi = incorrect location, insufficient pressure, or depleted Qi (chronic illness). Teach patients to recognise Deqi so they can do self-acupressure correctly.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Key Acupressure Points — Clinical Reference",badge:"Reference",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Point</th><th>Location</th><th>Indication</th><th>Method</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>P6 (Neiguan)</td><td>3 finger-widths above wrist crease, between tendons — inner forearm</td><td>Nausea ★ (CINV, morning sickness, travel), anxiety, palpitations, insomnia</td><td>Firm circular pressure, 1–3 min</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ST36 (Zusanli)</td><td>4 finger-widths below kneecap, 1 finger lateral to tibial crest</td><td>Digestive disorders ★, fatigue, immune boost, knee pain, overall vitality tonic</td><td>Deep pressure + circular, 2–3 min</td></tr>
      <tr><td>LI4 (Hegu)</td><td>Web between thumb and index finger — highest point of muscle belly</td><td>Headache ★, toothache, cold/flu, constipation, facial disorders, pain</td><td>Deep pinch pressure, 1–2 min each side</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GB20 (Fengchi)</td><td>Base of skull, in hollow between SCM and trapezius muscles</td><td>Headache ★, neck pain, hypertension, cold/flu, dizziness, eye disorders</td><td>Firm upward pressure both sides simultaneously</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SP6 (Sanyinjiao)</td><td>4 finger-widths above medial malleolus, posterior to tibial border</td><td>Gynaecological disorders ★, insomnia, digestive issues, urinary problems</td><td>Firm pressure, 1–2 min. CONTRAINDICATED in pregnancy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>KD1 (Yongquan)</td><td>Centre of sole, in depression when toes curl — junction of anterior ⅓</td><td>Hypertension ★, insomnia, anxiety, grounding, kidney tonic</td><td>Firm pressure or rolling with thumb</td></tr>
      <tr><td>CV6 (Qihai)</td><td>1.5 cun below umbilicus, midline</td><td>Fatigue ★, digestive weakness, reproductive disorders, Qi deficiency</td><td>Gentle circular clockwise pressure</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GV20 (Baihui)</td><td>Top of head — midline, apex of skull</td><td>Headache, dizziness, mental clarity, prolapse conditions, depression</td><td>Gentle circular pressure — avoid vigorous in HTN</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Marma points (Ayurvedic)</div><div class="pt">107 Marma points are vital energy junctions in Ayurveda — anatomically correspond to junctions of muscle, bone, ligament, vessel, and joint. Key clinical Marma points: Sthapani (between eyebrows — headache, stress), Talahridaya (palm/sole centre — cardiac, grounding), Brahmarandhra (crown — mental health), Kakshadhara (armpit — shoulder, lymph). Marma stimulation uses gentle pressure, rotation, and warm sesame/medicated oil. Contraindicated over open wounds, scars, or known tumours.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Foot Reflexology — Zone Map & Protocol",badge:"Technique",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Theory</div>The feet contain a complete reflex map of the body. Pressure on specific reflex zones sends neurological signals to corresponding organs via spinal reflexes and autonomic pathways.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Foot Zone</th><th>Corresponding Organ/Area</th><th>Clinical use</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Big toe / toes 2–5</td><td>Head, brain, sinuses, teeth</td><td>Headache, sinusitis, eye/ear disorders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ball of foot</td><td>Heart, lungs, chest</td><td>Respiratory conditions, palpitations, anxiety</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Upper arch</td><td>Stomach, liver, gallbladder, pancreas, spleen</td><td>Digestive disorders, diabetes, jaundice</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lower arch</td><td>Small intestine, colon, kidneys</td><td>IBS, constipation, UTI, kidney stones</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Heel</td><td>Pelvis, sciatic nerve, reproductive organs</td><td>Sciatica, menstrual disorders, low back pain</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Inner (medial) edge</td><td>Entire spine (cervical at toe to lumbar at heel)</td><td>Spinal disorders, posture, back pain</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Outer (lateral) edge</td><td>Shoulder, elbow, knee, hip (down heel)</td><td>Limb joint disorders</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Preparation</span> — Warm foot bath 5 min. Pat dry. Apply sesame oil or reflexology cream. Patient supine or in reclining chair.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">General relaxation</span> — 5 min: effleurage whole foot, ankle rotations, toe stretches, heel squeeze.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Systematic pressure</span> — Use thumb-walking technique on all zones. Note tender points (indicate congestion/dysfunction). Hold sensitive points with sustained pressure × 30 sec.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Closing</span> — General relaxation strokes. Solar plexus point (centre of ball) bilaterally with deep breath × 3. Duration: 30–45 min total.</div></div>
    </div>`}
],

mass:[
  {t:"Massage Therapy in Naturopathy — Principles",badge:"Foundation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">BNYS massage principle</div>Naturopathic massage aims to restore circulation, lymphatic flow, nervous system balance, and tissue health — not merely relaxation. Oil selection is therapeutic, not aesthetic.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Stroke Type</th><th>Technique</th><th>Effect</th><th>When used</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Effleurage</td><td>Long gliding strokes, towards heart, full palm contact</td><td>↑ Venous/lymphatic return, relaxation, warm-up</td><td>Opening and closing strokes</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Petrissage</td><td>Kneading, wringing, rolling of muscle tissue</td><td>↑ Local circulation, breaks adhesions, reduces muscle tension</td><td>Main body of massage</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tapotement</td><td>Percussion: hacking, cupping, tapping</td><td>Stimulates, loosens secretions (chest), energises</td><td>Stimulating massage; chest therapy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Friction</td><td>Deep circular pressure on specific points/areas</td><td>Breaks scar tissue, resolves local adhesions</td><td>Specific tight areas, tendons</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vibration</td><td>Fine trembling of hands on body part</td><td>Loosens secretions, nerve stimulation, relaxation</td><td>Chest, nerve pathways</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Therapeutic oils in BNYS</div><div class="pt">Sesame oil (tila taila): warming, anti-Vata, best for dry skin, joint disorders, neurological conditions — most universally used. Coconut oil: cooling, anti-inflammatory, best for Pitta, skin conditions, headaches. Mustard oil: deeply warming and stimulating — cold/flu, arthritis, cold constitutions. Neem oil: antimicrobial, antifungal — skin infections, psoriasis, eczema. Castor oil: deeply penetrating, anti-inflammatory — abdominal application, joint swelling. Always warm oil to body temperature before application.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Abhyanga — Full Body Oil Massage",badge:"Core",c:`
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Abhyanga (Ayurvedic oil massage)</div>Traditional whole-body massage with warm medicated oil. One of the most powerful rejuvenative (rasayana) therapies. 60–90 minute protocol.</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Patient position & preparation</span> — Warm room (no draught). Disrobe to underwear. Massage table with towels. Warm oil to 40–42°C. Begin supine.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Head & scalp (10 min)</span> — Circular pressure on scalp with fingertips. Stroke temples, occiput, forehead. Stimulates marma points: Adhipati (crown), Sthapani (forehead), Krikatika (nape).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Face & neck (5 min)</span> — Upward strokes on face. Long effleurage down neck towards clavicle (lymphatic drainage). Circular on jaw muscles.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Chest & abdomen (10 min)</span> — Effleurage chest outward. Abdomen: clockwise circular strokes following colon (ascending right → transverse → descending left).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Arms & hands (10 min)</span> — Long strokes from hand to shoulder. Circular at joints. Palm and finger massage. Reflex points on palm.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Legs & feet (15 min)</span> — Long effleurage from foot to hip. Circular at knee and ankle. Foot massage including heel and toe joints. Reflexology zones as indicated.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">7</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Back (15 min)</span> — Prone position. Long strokes from sacrum to neck. Circular on erector spinae. Shoulder blade region. Gluteal kneading.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#b45309">8</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Steam bath (Svedana)</span> — Follow with steam cabinet or wet sheet pack × 10–15 min to drive oil into tissues. Remove excess oil with dry towel or warm bath.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Self-abhyanga prescription</div><div class="pt">Daily self-abhyanga is one of the most powerful preventive health practices. Prescription: warm sesame oil, 10–15 min before morning shower. Start at crown, work down. Let oil absorb 5 min then shower with warm (not hot) water — do not use soap on oiled skin. Weekly self-abhyanga reduces Vata, improves sleep, ↓ cortisol, ↑ skin barrier function. Teach every chronically stressed patient this practice.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Massage Contraindications & Precautions",badge:"Safety",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Absolute contraindications</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Reason</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Deep vein thrombosis (DVT)</td><td>Risk of embolism from dislodging clot</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Active infections (skin, systemic fever)</td><td>Spreads infection; increases systemic load</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Open wounds, burns, unhealed scars</td><td>Direct tissue damage risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Active malignancy (over tumour site)</td><td>Risk of local spread (theoretical but cautious)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bleeding disorders / anticoagulants</td><td>Bruising, haematoma risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acute fractures</td><td>Movement of fracture site</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acute inflammatory joint disease (gout attack, RA flare)</td><td>Pain, worsens inflammation</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Precautions (modify, not contraindicate)</div>Varicose veins (massage above, not directly over). Pregnancy (avoid deep abdominal and lower back in 1st trimester; all massage after 1st trimester with appropriate positioning). Osteoporosis (gentle only — no deep pressure). Hypertension (avoid heavy tapotement). Diabetes (check skin integrity before and after, reduced sensation).</div>`}
],

coun:[
  {t:"Counselling in Naturopathy — Core Principles",badge:"Foundation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Role of counselling in BNYS</div>Health is physical, mental, social, and spiritual. A naturopathic physician must be able to identify psychological contributors to illness, provide basic supportive counselling, and refer appropriately. You cannot treat the body and ignore the mind.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Skill</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Active listening</td><td>Full attention, no interruption, non-verbal engagement (nodding, eye contact, open posture)</td><td>Allow patient to complete their story before asking questions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reflection</td><td>Mirror back what was said in slightly different words</td><td>"So it sounds like you feel the stress at work is making your symptoms worse?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Open questions</td><td>Cannot be answered with yes/no — invite elaboration</td><td>"How has this been affecting your daily life?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Empathy statements</td><td>Acknowledge the emotional experience without judgment</td><td>"That sounds like it's been really difficult to manage alongside work."</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Summarising</td><td>Periodically recap to show understanding and check accuracy</td><td>"Let me just check I've understood correctly — you've had this for 3 months, worse with stress, better on weekends?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Motivational interviewing</td><td>Explore ambivalence; elicit patient's own motivation for change</td><td>"What would a healthier version of you look like in 6 months?"</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 BATHE technique — 5 min psychosocial screen</div><div class="pt">B — Background: "What is going on in your life?" A — Affect: "How do you feel about that?" T — Trouble: "What troubles you most about it?" H — Handling: "How are you handling it?" E — Empathy: "That must be very difficult for you." This 5-question structure provides a complete psychosocial history in under 5 minutes and is proven to improve patient satisfaction and clinical outcomes. Use at every consultation.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Communication Skills — The Therapeutic Consultation",badge:"Practice",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#065f46">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Opening (2 min)</span> — Warm greeting by name. Introduce yourself clearly. Check how patient wishes to be addressed. "How can I help you today?" — then LISTEN without interrupting for at least 90 seconds.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#065f46">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Exploration (10–15 min)</span> — ICE framework: Ideas ("What do you think might be causing this?"), Concerns ("What worries you most about it?"), Expectations ("What were you hoping I could do for you today?").</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#065f46">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Examination & assessment (5–10 min)</span> — Explain what you're going to do before each step. Maintain dignity. Invite questions during examination.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#065f46">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Shared decision-making (5 min)</span> — Explain findings in lay language. Offer options, not prescriptions. "This is what I recommend, but ultimately you decide." Involve the patient in the treatment plan.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#065f46">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Safety-netting & closing (2 min)</span> — "If things don't improve in 2 weeks / if you experience X, please come back or seek urgent care." Written plan. Confirm understanding: "Is there anything you're unsure about?"</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 The 90-second rule</div><div class="pt">Studies show doctors interrupt patients on average within 18 seconds of them beginning to speak. If allowed to speak uninterrupted, 80% of patients finish in under 90 seconds — and they reveal the real reason for the consultation. The first 90 seconds of a consultation should be the patient's time. Put down your pen. Look up from the screen. Just listen. This single change improves diagnosis accuracy, patient satisfaction, and adherence to treatment.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Mental Health Screening in Naturopathic Practice",badge:"Essential",c:`
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Why screen in BNYS?</div>70% of patients in naturopathic practice have a significant psychological component to their illness. PHQ-9 and GAD-7 take 2 minutes and are mandatory tools.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>What it measures</th><th>Score interpretation</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>PHQ-9</td><td>Depression (9 items, 0–27)</td><td>0–4 minimal; 5–9 mild; 10–14 moderate; 15–19 mod-severe; 20–27 severe</td><td>PHQ-9 ≥10 = discuss; ≥20 = REFER URGENTLY. Always ask Q9 (self-harm)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GAD-7</td><td>Generalised anxiety (7 items, 0–21)</td><td>0–4 minimal; 5–9 mild; 10–14 moderate; 15–21 severe</td><td>≥10 = moderate anxiety — consider referral if not improving</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PSQI</td><td>Sleep quality (7 domains)</td><td>Score &gt;5 = poor sleep quality</td><td>Intervene with sleep hygiene + yoga nidra + magnesium</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PSS-10</td><td>Perceived Stress Scale</td><td>0–13 low; 14–26 moderate; 27–40 high</td><td>High PSS → stress management programme priority</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Mandatory referral indicators</div>PHQ-9 ≥20 or active suicidal ideation (Q9 score &gt;0). Active psychosis or mania. Severe eating disorder (BMI &lt;17.5 or rapid weight loss). Substance dependence. Any immediate safety concern. Always document referral and safety-netting in case notes.</div>`}
],

soap:[
  {t:"BNYS Casesheet — Structure & Format",badge:"Template",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Purpose of the casesheet</div>The BNYS casesheet is a comprehensive naturopathic history document. It integrates conventional biomedical history with naturopathic constitutional assessment — serving as both diagnostic and treatment planning tool.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Section</th><th>Content</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Patient identification</td><td>Name, age, sex, occupation, marital status, address, date, registration number</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chief complaint (CC)</td><td>Patient's presenting problem in their own words + duration</td></tr>
      <tr><td>History of present illness (HPI)</td><td>SOCRATES: Site, Onset, Character, Radiation, Associations, Time/duration, Exacerbating/relieving factors, Severity (NRS 0–10)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Past medical history (PMH)</td><td>Previous illnesses, hospitalisations, surgeries, accidents, chronic diseases, childhood illnesses</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Family history (FH)</td><td>Hereditary conditions: diabetes, HTN, cancer, heart disease, thyroid, mental illness — in parents, siblings, children</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Personal history</td><td>Diet (type, habits, times, raw/cooked ratio), sleep (hours, quality, timing), bowel habits, urine output, exercise, occupation stress, habits (tobacco, alcohol)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Menstrual/obstetric history</td><td>Cycle regularity, flow, LMP, pregnancies, deliveries, contraception (female patients)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Drug history</td><td>Current medications + dose + duration. Allergies. Previous naturopathic treatments.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Naturopathic constitutional assessment</td><td>Prakriti (Vata/Pitta/Kapha dominance), tongue examination, pulse (Nadi pariksha basics), iris/sclera observation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Systems review</td><td>Systematic questioning: CVS, respiratory, GI, GU, MSK, neurological, skin, endocrine, mental health</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},
  {t:"BNYS Physical Examination — Naturopathic Approach",badge:"Template",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#1d4ed8">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">General appearance</span> — Nutritional status (obese/thin/normal), body type (ectomorph/mesomorph/endomorph), pallor, jaundice, cyanosis, clubbing, oedema, lymphadenopathy, hydration status</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#1d4ed8">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Vital signs</span> — BP (both arms), Pulse (rate, rhythm, volume, character), RR, Temperature (oral), SpO₂, Weight (kg), Height (cm), BMI, Waist circumference</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#1d4ed8">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Tongue examination (naturopathic)</span> — Colour (pale=deficiency, red=heat, purple=stasis), coating (white=cold/dampness, yellow=heat, thick=excess), shape (swollen=dampness, thin=deficiency), moisture, cracks, teeth marks</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#1d4ed8">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Skin & nails</span> — Texture (dry/oily), turgor, elasticity, rashes, discolouration, nail changes (koilonychia=iron def, leukonychia, Beau's lines, clubbing)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#1d4ed8">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Abdominal examination</span> — Inspection (distension, visible peristalsis), palpation (tenderness, guarding, organomegaly), percussion (tympany, dullness), auscultation (bowel sounds)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#1d4ed8">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Naturopathic-specific assessment</span> — Spinal palpation (vertebral tenderness, kyphosis/lordosis/scoliosis), reflex zone tenderness (feet/hands), muscle tension patterns, breathing pattern (chest vs diaphragmatic)</div></div>
    </div>`},
  {t:"SOAP Note — BNYS Format",badge:"Template",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">S</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Subjective</span><br>
        <b>CC:</b> [Chief complaint] × [duration]<br>
        <b>HPI:</b> [SOCRATES summary]<br>
        <b>PMH / FH / DH / SH:</b> [Relevant positives and negatives]<br>
        <b>Diet:</b> [Type, times, habits, water intake, raw/cooked]<br>
        <b>Sleep:</b> [Hours, quality, timing]<br>
        <b>Bowels:</b> [Frequency, consistency, colour]<br>
        <b>Stress:</b> [Level 0–10, sources]<br>
        <b>Exercise:</b> [Type, frequency, duration]</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">O</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Objective</span><br>
        <b>Vitals:</b> BP _/_ mmHg · PR __ bpm · RR __ /min · T __ °C · SpO₂ __%<br>
        <b>Anthropometry:</b> Wt __kg · Ht __cm · BMI __ · WC __cm<br>
        <b>Tongue:</b> [Colour/coating/shape]<br>
        <b>Examination findings:</b> [System-specific positives and negatives]<br>
        <b>Investigations:</b> [Recent reports with date]<br>
        <b>Outcome scores:</b> PHQ-9: __ / GAD-7: __ / PSQI: __ / Pain NRS: __</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">A</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Assessment</span><br>
        <b>Diagnosis:</b> [Conventional diagnosis + naturopathic terrain]<br>
        <b>Root cause analysis:</b> [Dietary, lifestyle, structural, emotional, environmental factors]<br>
        <b>Naturopathic constitution:</b> [Prakriti / body type]<br>
        <b>Therapeutic order level:</b> [1–6 — see therapeutic order framework]<br>
        <b>Risk factors / red flags:</b> [Any requiring referral?]</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#064E3B">P</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Plan</span><br>
        <b>1. Investigations:</b> [Ordered — with clinical indication]<br>
        <b>2. Diet:</b> [Specific dietary prescription]<br>
        <b>3. Naturopathic treatments:</b> [Mud, hydro, massage, acupressure — with frequency/duration]<br>
        <b>4. Yoga/pranayama:</b> [Specific prescription — asanas, pranayama, duration]<br>
        <b>5. Supplements/herbs:</b> [Name, dose, form, duration, timing]<br>
        <b>6. Lifestyle:</b> [Sleep, stress, exercise modifications]<br>
        <b>7. Patient education:</b> [Topics covered]<br>
        <b>8. Safety-netting:</b> [When to return / seek urgent care]<br>
        <b>9. Review:</b> [Date + objectives to reassess]</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Documentation principle</div><div class="pt">"If it isn't written, it didn't happen." Good documentation protects the patient (continuity of care), protects you (medico-legal), and improves outcomes (structured thinking leads to better plans). Write legibly in black ink. Date and sign every entry. Never use correction fluid — draw a single line through errors and initial. Document patient consent for all treatments. BNYS case notes should be kept for minimum 7 years.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Treatment Progress Notes & Discharge Summary",badge:"Template",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Progress note format (each visit)</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Date & visit number</span> — e.g., "Day 7 of 21-day residential programme"</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Interval history</span> — "Since last visit: [symptom change, treatment response, adherence, any adverse reactions, new complaints]"</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Repeat objective measures</span> — Vitals, weight, relevant exam findings, outcome score changes</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Assessment update</span> — "Responding well / partial response / no response / worsening — possible reasons:"</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Plan modification</span> — Continue / escalate / modify / refer</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Discharge summary must include</div>
      <div class="plist">
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>Admission and discharge dates</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>Diagnosis at admission and discharge</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>All treatments given (with dates, duration, response)</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>Outcome measures at admission vs discharge</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>Home programme prescribed (diet, yoga, self-care)</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>Follow-up plan and date</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>When to seek emergency care (safety-netting)</div></div>
        <div class="pi"><div class="pd" style="background:#064E3B"></div><div>Referring/treating doctor signature + date</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>`}
]

};


const D_EXAM = {

cv:[
  {t:"General Inspection",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Position & environment</span> — Patient at 45°, chest exposed, adequate lighting. Look from the end of the bed before touching.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Face & peripheries</span> — Malar flush (mitral stenosis), pallor, central cyanosis (lips/tongue), jaundice (right heart failure), corneal arcus, xanthelasma</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Hands</span> — Clubbing, koilonychia, splinter haemorrhages (IE), Osler's nodes (painful, pulp, IE), Janeway lesions (painless, palms, IE), pallor (anaemia)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Chest</span> — Sternotomy scar (CABG/valve replacement), thoracotomy scar, pacemaker/ICD device, chest deformity (pectus excavatum → MVP)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Legs</span> — Pitting oedema (bilateral = cardiac/hypoalbuminaemia, unilateral = DVT/venous), varicosities, peripheral cyanosis</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Clinical Pearl</div><div class="pt">Inspection before palpation — always. The end-of-bed assessment gives you the gestalt of how sick the patient is. A patient who looks well despite abnormal observations is different from one who looks unwell with normal observations.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Pulse Assessment",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal rate</div><div class="nv-val">60–100 bpm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal rhythm</div><div class="nv-val">Regular sinus</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Pulse volume</div><div class="nv-val">Normal / High / Low</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Pulsus paradoxus</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;10 mmHg drop in SBP on inspiration</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Pulse character</th><th>Description</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Collapsing (water hammer)</td><td>Rapid rise and fall — best felt with arm raised</td><td>Aortic regurgitation, PDA, AV fistula</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Slow-rising (anacrotic)</td><td>Slow upstroke, sustained peak</td><td>Aortic stenosis (severe)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bounding</td><td>Large amplitude, forceful</td><td>CO₂ retention, sepsis, thyrotoxicosis, anaemia, pregnancy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bisferiens</td><td>Double peak</td><td>HOCM, mixed AS/AR</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Alternans</td><td>Alternating strong/weak beats (regular)</td><td>Severe LV dysfunction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Irregularly irregular</td><td>No pattern to rhythm</td><td>Atrial fibrillation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pulsus paradoxus</td><td>&gt;10mmHg SBP drop on inspiration</td><td>Cardiac tamponade ★, severe asthma, COPD</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">Radio-radial &amp; radio-femoral delay</div>Simultaneous palpation: delay between right and left radial = subclavian artery stenosis or aortic coarctation. Radio-femoral delay = coarctation of aorta.</div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always check the pulse for a full 30 seconds in suspected AF — feel for the irregularity. A regularly irregular pulse (missed beats) = ectopics or Wenckebach. An irregularly irregular pulse = AF until proven otherwise.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Blood Pressure",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Correct technique</span> — Patient seated or supine, 5 minutes rest, arm supported at heart level, correct cuff size (bladder should encircle 80% of arm circumference)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Estimate systolic first</span> — Inflate until radial pulse disappears, note pressure, deflate, re-inflate 20–30 mmHg above this estimate</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Deflate slowly</span> — 2–3 mmHg/sec. Korotkoff Phase I (first sound) = systolic. Phase V (disappearance) = diastolic</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Both arms</span> — &gt;20 mmHg difference = subclavian stenosis or aortic dissection (use the higher reading)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Lying and standing</span> — Postural hypotension = &gt;20 mmHg SBP drop or &gt;10 mmHg DBP drop after 3 minutes standing → autonomic failure, dehydration, medications</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Classification</th><th>Systolic</th><th>Diastolic</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Normal</td><td>&lt;130</td><td>&lt;85</td></tr>
      <tr><td>High normal</td><td>130–139</td><td>85–89</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage 1 hypertension</td><td>140–159</td><td>90–99</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage 2 hypertension</td><td>160–179</td><td>100–109</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage 3 / severe</td><td>≥180</td><td>≥110</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypertensive urgency</td><td>≥180</td><td>≥120 (no organ damage)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypertensive emergency</td><td>≥180</td><td>≥120 + end-organ damage (papilloedema, AKI, encephalopathy)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"JVP Assessment",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">Technique</div>Patient at 45°, head rotated slightly left. Look for the double waveform (a-c-x-v-y) in the right internal jugular vein. Do NOT confuse with carotid pulse (JVP is non-pulsatile with light pressure, has double waveform, rises on abdominal pressure).</div>
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal JVP height</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;3 cm above sternal angle</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">JVP waveform</div><div class="nv-val">a wave (atrial contraction), v wave (venous filling)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Raised JVP</td><td>Right heart failure ★, tamponade, constrictive pericarditis, SVC obstruction, fluid overload</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Absent JVP</td><td>Dehydration, hypovolaemia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cannon a waves</td><td>Atrial contraction against closed tricuspid valve → CHB, VT, junctional rhythm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Giant v waves</td><td>Tricuspid regurgitation (systolic pulsation)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Absent a wave</td><td>Atrial fibrillation (no coordinated atrial contraction)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kussmaul's sign</td><td>JVP RISES on inspiration → constrictive pericarditis, RV infarction, cardiac tamponade</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hepatojugular reflux</td><td>Firm RUQ pressure → sustained JVP rise &gt;3cm → right heart failure</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The JVP is a window into the right atrium. A raised JVP is one of the earliest signs of right heart failure. In cardiac tamponade, remember Beck's triad: raised JVP + hypotension + muffled heart sounds. Pulsus paradoxus also present.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Precordial Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Apex beat — location</span> — Normally 5th ICS, midclavicular line. Displaced laterally/inferiorly = cardiomegaly (LV dilatation). Non-palpable = COPD, obesity, pericardial effusion, dextrocardia</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Apex beat — character</span> — Heaving (pressure overload: AS, hypertension) / Thrusting (volume overload: AR, MR) / Tapping (palpable S1: MS) / Dyskinetic (LV aneurysm)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Parasternal heave</span> — Left hand flat on sternum: sustained outward lift = right ventricular hypertrophy (cor pulmonale, pulmonary hypertension)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cv)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Thrills</span> — Palpable murmur (grade ≥4). Systolic thrill at base = AS. At apex = MR. At LLSE = VSD. Continuous = PDA.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always use the flat of the hand for thrills (more sensitive than fingertips). A thrill means the murmur is at least grade 4/6. The absence of a thrill does NOT mean the murmur is not significant.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Cardiac Auscultation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">Auscultation areas</div>Aortic: 2nd right ICS · Pulmonary: 2nd left ICS · Tricuspid: lower left sternal edge · Mitral: apex (5th ICS midclavicular line)</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Heart sound</th><th>Timing</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>S1</td><td>Start of systole</td><td>Mitral + tricuspid closure. Loud in MS, soft in MR. Split S1 = RBBB or Ebstein's</td></tr>
      <tr><td>S2</td><td>End of systole</td><td>Aortic + pulmonary closure. Fixed split = ASD. Paradoxical split = LBBB, AS. Loud P2 = pulmonary hypertension</td></tr>
      <tr><td>S3 (ventricular gallop)</td><td>Early diastole</td><td>Normal in young/pregnancy. Pathological in adults = heart failure (ventricular dilatation), MR, VSD</td></tr>
      <tr><td>S4 (atrial gallop)</td><td>Late diastole (pre-systole)</td><td>Always abnormal. Stiff ventricle: LVH, hypertension, HOCM, AS, ischaemia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Opening snap</td><td>Early diastole after S2</td><td>Mitral stenosis. Closer snap to S2 = more severe MS</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ejection click</td><td>Early systole after S1</td><td>Bicuspid aortic valve, pulmonary stenosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mid-systolic click</td><td>Mid-systole</td><td>Mitral valve prolapse (may be followed by a late systolic murmur)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pericardial friction rub</td><td>Systole + diastole</td><td>Pericarditis — scratchy, leathery. Best heard end-expiration with patient leaning forward.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Auscultate in multiple positions: sitting forward (aortic regurgitation murmur louder), left lateral decubitus (mitral murmurs louder), standing/squatting (HOCM: murmur louder on standing, softer on squatting). Always listen at the carotids for AR radiation and in the axilla for MR.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Cardiac Murmurs — Full Guide",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Lesion</th><th>Timing</th><th>Best heard</th><th>Radiation</th><th>Character</th><th>Key features</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Aortic stenosis</td><td>Ejection systolic</td><td>Aortic area</td><td>Carotids ★</td><td>Harsh, crescendo-decrescendo</td><td>Slow-rising pulse, narrow pulse pressure, heaving apex, ejection click (if bicuspid)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Aortic regurgitation</td><td>Early diastolic</td><td>LLSE (lean forward, held expiration)</td><td>None</td><td>Soft, blowing, decrescendo</td><td>Collapsing pulse, wide pulse pressure, displaced apex, many eponymous signs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mitral regurgitation</td><td>Pansystolic (whole systole)</td><td>Apex</td><td>Axilla ★</td><td>Blowing, uniform intensity</td><td>Soft S1, S3, thrusting apex, AF common</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mitral stenosis</td><td>Mid-diastolic (rumble)</td><td>Apex — left lateral position</td><td>None</td><td>Low-pitched rumble, presystolic accentuation</td><td>Tapping apex, loud S1, opening snap, malar flush, AF, raised JVP</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tricuspid regurgitation</td><td>Pansystolic</td><td>LLSE</td><td>None</td><td>Blowing</td><td>Louder on inspiration (Carvallo's sign), raised JVP with giant v waves, pulsatile liver</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pulmonary stenosis</td><td>Ejection systolic</td><td>Pulmonary area (2nd LICS)</td><td>None</td><td>Harsh</td><td>Ejection click, right-sided S4, parasternal heave</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VSD</td><td>Pansystolic</td><td>LLSE</td><td>All over precordium</td><td>Harsh, loud</td><td>Thrill at LLSE. If small VSD = loud murmur (maladie de Roger)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HOCM</td><td>Ejection systolic</td><td>LLSE / apex</td><td>None</td><td>Harsh</td><td>Louder on standing/Valsalva, softer on squatting/hand grip. Jerky pulse.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">Grading murmurs (Levine scale)</div>1 = barely audible · 2 = soft but easily heard · 3 = moderately loud · 4 = loud + palpable thrill · 5 = very loud, heard with stethoscope partially off chest · 6 = heard without stethoscope</div>`}
],

rs:[
  {t:"Respiratory Inspection",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">General</span> — Patient at 45°, chest exposed. Count RR for 30 seconds (normal 12–20/min). Note work of breathing: accessory muscle use, intercostal recession, nasal flaring, pursed lip breathing</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Breathing pattern</span> — Kussmaul (deep, sighing = metabolic acidosis), Cheyne-Stokes (waxing/waning + apnoea = bilateral cortical lesion, CCF), Biot's (irregular with apnoea = brainstem lesion)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Hands</span> — Clubbing (fibrosis, lung ca, bronchiectasis, empyema), peripheral cyanosis, nicotine staining, CO₂ retention flap (asterixis — outstretched hands)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Face</span> — Central cyanosis (tongue/lips — SpO₂ &lt;85%), Horner's syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis — Pancoast tumour), plethoric face (polycythaemia, SVC obstruction)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Chest shape</span> — Barrel chest (COPD — AP diameter increased), pectus excavatum/carinatum, Harrison's sulcus (childhood respiratory disease), kyphoscoliosis (restrictive lung disease)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Trachea</span> — Central? Deviation toward collapse/fibrosis. Away from tension pneumothorax/large effusion. Note use of SCM (accessory muscle) = respiratory distress.</div></div>
    </div>`},

  {t:"Chest Expansion & Percussion",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Expansion</span> — Hands around lower chest, thumbs meet at midline. Normal expansion = 5+ cm. Reduced unilaterally = pleural effusion, pneumonia, collapse, pneumothorax on that side</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Tactile vocal fremitus</span> — Ulnar edge of hand. "99". Increased = consolidation. Reduced = effusion, pneumothorax, collapse</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--rs)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Percussion technique</span> — Middle finger of non-dominant hand flat on chest (hyperextended). Strike with tip of dominant middle finger. Compare sides systematically.</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Percussion note</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Causes</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Resonant</td><td>Normal air-filled lung</td><td>Normal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dull</td><td>Solid or fluid replacing air</td><td>Consolidation ★, collapse, pleural effusion (stony dull), haemothorax</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stony dull</td><td>Fluid above lung</td><td>Pleural effusion ★, empyema, haemothorax</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hyper-resonant</td><td>Increased air</td><td>Pneumothorax ★, COPD (bullae), asthma (during attack)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tympanic</td><td>Air-filled hollow structure</td><td>Over stomach bubble (lower left)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">In pleural effusion: stony dull percussion + decreased breath sounds + decreased vocal resonance + decreased expansion on that side. In consolidation: dull percussion + bronchial breathing + increased vocal resonance/tactile fremitus + aegophony. The combination tells the story.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Auscultation — Breath Sounds",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">Technique</div>Ask patient to breathe through mouth. Compare side-to-side. Start at apex, work systematically to bases. Note quality, added sounds, and vocal resonance.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Breath sound</th><th>Character</th><th>Normal/Abnormal location</th><th>Cause when abnormal</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Vesicular</td><td>Soft, rustling, inspiration &gt; expiration</td><td>Normal throughout lung fields</td><td>—</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bronchial</td><td>Loud, hollow, expiration = inspiration, pause between</td><td>Normal over trachea only</td><td>Consolidation ★, collapse, lung abscess, fibrous tissue</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reduced/absent</td><td>Quieter or absent sounds</td><td>Abnormal when unilateral</td><td>Pleural effusion, pneumothorax, collapse, COPD, obesity</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Crackles (coarse)</td><td>Low-pitched, bubbling, inspiratory ± expiratory</td><td>Bases</td><td>Pulmonary oedema ★, pneumonia, bronchiectasis, early CCF</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Crackles (fine)</td><td>High-pitched, velcro-like, late inspiratory</td><td>Bases + upper zones</td><td>Pulmonary fibrosis ★ (IPF), asbestosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wheeze (expiratory)</td><td>Musical, high-pitched, diffuse</td><td>Diffuse expiratory wheeze</td><td>Asthma ★, COPD, anaphylaxis, cardiac asthma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wheeze (inspiratory = stridor)</td><td>High-pitched, monophonic, inspiration</td><td>Best heard over trachea</td><td>Upper airway obstruction: epiglottitis, croup, tumour, foreign body</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pleural rub</td><td>Creaking/leathery, inspiration + expiration</td><td>Localised</td><td>Pleuritis, pulmonary embolism (infarction), pleural tumour</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Vocal resonance: ask patient to say "ninety-nine" while auscultating. Increased = consolidation (sound conducted through solid tissue). Decreased = effusion/pneumothorax (fluid/air blocks transmission). Whispering pectoriloquy (whispered sounds heard clearly) = consolidation. Aegophony (E→A sound change) = effusion.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Respiratory Pattern Recognition",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Inspection</th><th>Expansion</th><th>Percussion</th><th>Breath sounds</th><th>Vocal resonance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Consolidation (pneumonia)</td><td>Reduced movement</td><td>Reduced on affected side</td><td>Dull</td><td>Bronchial breathing ★</td><td>Increased (whisp. pectoriloquy)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pleural effusion</td><td>Reduced movement, trachea deviated away if large</td><td>Reduced on affected side</td><td>Stony dull</td><td>Reduced/absent (bronchial at top)</td><td>Decreased (aegophony above effusion)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pneumothorax</td><td>Reduced movement, trachea deviates away if tension</td><td>Reduced on affected side</td><td>Hyper-resonant</td><td>Absent</td><td>Absent</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lobar collapse</td><td>Reduced movement, trachea toward</td><td>Reduced on affected side</td><td>Dull</td><td>Reduced/absent</td><td>Decreased</td></tr>
      <tr><td>COPD</td><td>Barrel chest, pursed lip, accessory muscles, poor expansion bilaterally</td><td>Globally reduced</td><td>Hyper-resonant bilaterally</td><td>Prolonged expiration, quiet, wheeze</td><td>Globally reduced</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pulmonary fibrosis</td><td>Cyanosis, clubbing, fine end-inspiratory crackles at bases</td><td>Globally reduced</td><td>Dull bilaterally at bases</td><td>Fine velcro crackles ★ (bases)</td><td>Reduced at bases</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Asthma (attack)</td><td>Accessory muscles, tachypnoea, unable to complete sentences</td><td>Poor bilaterally</td><td>Resonant/hyper-resonant</td><td>Diffuse expiratory wheeze</td><td>Normal</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`}
],

ab:[
  {t:"Abdominal Inspection",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Position</span> — Patient supine, pillow under head, arms by sides, abdomen exposed from xiphisternum to groin. Ask about pain before palpating.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Contour</span> — Distension? (5 Fs: Fat, Fluid, Flatus, Foetus, Faeces). Scaphoid (sunken) = cachexia. Visible peristalsis = bowel obstruction.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Scars</span> — Midline (laparotomy/bowel surgery), RIF (appendicectomy), RUQ (cholecystectomy), LIF (stoma reversal), Kocher's (open cholecystectomy), Rooftop (whipple/liver transplant), Mercedes-Benz (liver transplant)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Other signs</span> — Caput medusae (dilated periumbilical veins = portal hypertension), Sister Mary Joseph nodule (periumbilical node = intra-abdominal malignancy), Cullen's sign (periumbilical bruising = haemoperitoneum), Grey Turner's sign (flank bruising = retroperitoneal haemorrhage)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Hands/peripheral signs</span> — Clubbing, leukonychia, dupuytren's, palmar erythema, liver flap (asterixis), spider naevi (≥5 on trunk = portal hypertension), gynaecomastia, testicular atrophy</div></div>
    </div>`},

  {t:"Abdominal Palpation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">Always ask about pain before palpating — start away from the painful area</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Light palpation (9 regions)</span> — Superficial tenderness, guarding (voluntary/involuntary), rebound tenderness (peritoneal irritation — press then release), rigidity (board-like = peritonitis)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Deep palpation</span> — Masses: site, size, shape, surface (smooth/irregular), consistency, mobility, pulsatility, movement with respiration. Note tenderness with deep palpation.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Liver</span> — Start at RIF, move up with expiration. Normal upper border at 5th ICS (percussion). Measure in cm below costal margin (normal &lt;2cm). Character: smooth (hepatitis/CCF), nodular (cirrhosis/metastases), tender (hepatitis/CCF), pulsatile (TR).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Spleen</span> — Start at RIF, palpate diagonally toward left costal margin. Cannot get above it. Has a notch on medial border. Ask patient to take deep breath. If not palpable: roll patient to right lateral and try again.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Kidneys</span> — Bimanual: posterior hand in renal angle, anterior hand below costal margin. Ballottable (moveable up between hands). Can get above it (vs spleen/liver). Resonant to percussion (bowel in front).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Aorta</span> — Midline pulsation above umbilicus. Expansile pulsation (width &gt;3 fingers) = AAA. Normal aorta pulsates but does not expand laterally.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Splenomegaly causes: mnemonic CHINA — Chronic liver disease (portal HTN), Haematological (lymphoma/leukaemia/haemolytic anaemia), Infection (EBV, malaria, TB, IE), Neoplasm, Autoimmune (SLE, RA-Felty's). Spleen must be 2–3× normal size before palpable.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Special Abdominal Signs",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Sign</th><th>Technique</th><th>Positive finding</th><th>Indicates</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Murphy's sign</td><td>Two fingers below right costal margin, ask patient to breathe in</td><td>Arrest of inspiration due to pain</td><td>Acute cholecystitis ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rovsing's sign</td><td>Press firmly in LIF</td><td>Pain felt in RIF</td><td>Peritoneal irritation (appendicitis)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Psoas sign</td><td>Extend right hip with knee straight (patient on left side)</td><td>RIF pain on extension</td><td>Retrocaecal appendicitis, psoas abscess</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Obturator sign</td><td>Flex + internally rotate right hip</td><td>Hypogastric pain</td><td>Pelvic appendicitis, obturator hernia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Shifting dullness</td><td>Percuss from tympanic umbilicus to flank dullness. Mark boundary. Roll patient to side. Percussion note changes.</td><td>Boundary shifts toward new dependent side</td><td>Ascites (&gt;500mL)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fluid thrill</td><td>One hand on flank, flick opposite flank, third person's hand on midline</td><td>Impulse felt across abdomen</td><td>Large ascites (&gt;1L)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Courvoisier's law</td><td>Palpate RUQ below liver</td><td>Non-tender, palpable gallbladder + jaundice</td><td>Malignant biliary obstruction (Ca head pancreas) — NOT gallstones (chronic inflammation prevents distension)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Carnett's sign</td><td>Palpate tender area, ask patient to tense abdominal muscles</td><td>Pain WORSE on tensing = abdominal wall pain. Pain LESS on tensing = intra-abdominal</td><td>Differentiates abdominal wall vs visceral pain</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Never forget PR (digital rectal examination) in abdominal examination — especially in GI bleeding, constipation, suspected rectal cancer, and prostatic disease. "The finger you don't use will be pointed at you later."</div></div>`},

  {t:"Abdominal Percussion & Auscultation",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Liver percussion</span> — Upper border: start at 2nd ICS MCL, percuss down. Lower border: start at RIF, percuss up. Normal span 6–12 cm. Liver dullness: disappears in pneumoperitoneum (air over liver).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Splenic percussion</span> — Traube's space (left lower anterior thorax, bounded by liver, stomach, costal margin). Normally tympanic. Dull = splenomegaly or pleural effusion/consolidation.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ab)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Bowel sounds</span> — Auscultate for 30 seconds minimum. Normal = intermittent gurgles every few seconds.</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Bowel sounds</th><th>Description</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Normal</td><td>Intermittent gurgles 5–30 per minute</td><td>Intact peristalsis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>High-pitched, tinkling</td><td>Musical, frequent, rushing</td><td>Early/partial bowel obstruction ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Absent (&gt;3 minutes)</td><td>No sounds</td><td>Paralytic ileus, peritonitis, late obstruction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Borborygmi</td><td>Loud, prolonged gurgling</td><td>Hyperperistalsis: gastroenteritis, early obstruction, diarrhoea</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Succussion splash</td><td>Splashing sound on shaking upper abdomen (≥3 hrs post-meal)</td><td>Gastric outlet obstruction, pyloric stenosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Renal/hepatic bruit</td><td>Auscultate over renal arteries/liver</td><td>Renal artery stenosis, hepatocellular carcinoma, AV malformation</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`}
],

nr:[
  {t:"Cranial Nerve Examination",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>CN</th><th>Name</th><th>How to test</th><th>Abnormal finding</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>I</td><td>Olfactory</td><td>Identify familiar smell (coffee/mint) each nostril</td><td>Anosmia: head injury, frontal meningioma, COVID-19</td></tr>
      <tr><td>II</td><td>Optic</td><td>Snellen chart (VA), visual fields (confrontation), colour vision, pupil reflexes, fundoscopy</td><td>Reduced VA, field defects, RAPD, optic disc swelling/pallor</td></tr>
      <tr><td>III</td><td>Oculomotor</td><td>EOM: H-pattern. Look for ptosis, pupil size</td><td>CN III palsy: down-and-out pupil, dilated pupil (posterior communicating artery aneurysm = SURGICAL emergency)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>IV</td><td>Trochlear</td><td>Look downward and inward (superior oblique)</td><td>Head tilt, diplopia going down stairs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>V</td><td>Trigeminal</td><td>Light touch 3 divisions (forehead/cheek/chin), jaw clench (masseter), corneal reflex (sensory limb)</td><td>Facial numbness, loss of corneal reflex</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VI</td><td>Abducens</td><td>Lateral gaze</td><td>Medial deviation of eye at rest, cannot abduct. Long intracranial course → false localising sign in raised ICP</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VII</td><td>Facial</td><td>Raise eyebrows, close eyes tight, show teeth, puff cheeks. Note nasolabial fold asymmetry.</td><td>UMN: lower face weakness only (forehead spared). LMN (Bell's): entire face including forehead = Bell's palsy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VIII</td><td>Vestibulocochlear</td><td>Whisper test, Rinne & Weber tuning fork tests</td><td>Conductive vs sensorineural hearing loss. Vestibular: nystagmus, Dix-Hallpike</td></tr>
      <tr><td>IX/X</td><td>Glossopharyngeal / Vagus</td><td>Say "aah" — palate rises symmetrically. Gag reflex (IX = afferent, X = efferent). Hoarse voice = X</td><td>Uvula deviation away from lesion, absent gag, dysphonia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>XI</td><td>Accessory</td><td>Shrug shoulders (trapezius) and turn head against resistance (SCM)</td><td>Weakness: neck dissection, posterior fossa lesion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>XII</td><td>Hypoglossal</td><td>Tongue: protrude, move side to side. Look for wasting/fasciculations.</td><td>Deviation toward side of lesion (LMN), wasting + fasciculations</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">CN III palsy with a DILATED pupil = posterior communicating artery aneurysm until proven otherwise. Emergency CT angiography. A CN III palsy with a SPARED pupil = usually ischaemic (DM, hypertension) — pupillomotor fibres are peripheral and spared by ischaemia but compressed by aneurysm.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Upper Limb Neurological Exam",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspection</span> — Wasting (thenar/hypothenar/intrinsic), fasciculations, involuntary movements, posture, drift test (outstretched arms, eyes closed — 30 seconds)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Tone</span> — Flex/extend at wrist and elbow. Increased (spasticity = UMN, clasp-knife; rigidity = cogwheel/lead-pipe = Parkinson's), decreased = LMN/cerebellar</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Power (MRC 0–5)</span> — 0=none, 1=flicker, 2=gravity eliminated, 3=against gravity, 4-=slight resistance, 4=moderate resistance, 4+=strong resistance, 5=normal. Test: shoulder abduction (C5), elbow flexion (C5/6), elbow extension (C7), wrist extension (C7), finger extension (C7/8), finger flexion (C8), finger abduction (T1)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Reflexes</span> — Biceps C5/6 (musculocutaneous), Brachioradialis C5/6 (radial), Triceps C7 (radial). Grade 0 (absent) to 4+ (clonus). Compare sides.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Sensation</span> — Light touch, pin-prick (spinothalamic: pain/temp), vibration (posterior columns), proprioception. Test dermatomes C5-T1. Document level.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Coordination</span> — Finger-nose test (intention tremor = cerebellar), dysdiadochokinesia (rapid alternating movements)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Drift test: upward drift of one arm = cerebellar pathology. Pronator drift (arm pronates and drifts down) = contralateral UMN lesion. Pseudoathetosis (writhing movements) = proprioceptive loss. Perform this test for a full 30 seconds with eyes closed.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Lower Limb Neurological Exam",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspection</span> — Wasting (quadriceps, calf, foot), fasciculations, pes cavus (hereditary motor neuropathy), foot drop</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Tone</span> — Roll leg on bed (observe foot rotation), then passive flex/extend knee. Spasticity = legs may scissor or catch. Clonus at ankle: rapid dorsiflexion, sustained &gt;3 beats = UMN.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Power</span> — Hip flexion (L1/2), hip extension (L5/S1), knee flexion (L5/S1), knee extension (L3/4), ankle dorsiflexion (L4/5), ankle plantarflexion (S1), big toe extension (L5)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Reflexes</span> — Knee (L3/4 femoral), ankle (S1 sciatic), plantar (Babinski): stroke lateral sole with orange stick. Upgoing = Babinski positive = UMN (or normal in infants &lt;2yrs)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Sensation</span> — Test L1–S1 dermatomes. Saddle anaesthesia (S2/3/4) = cauda equina emergency.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nr)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Coordination</span> — Heel-shin test: slide heel from opposite knee down tibia. Ataxia = cerebellar.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Cauda equina syndrome: saddle anaesthesia + bowel/bladder dysfunction + bilateral leg weakness/numbness = neurosurgical emergency. MRI spine within 4 hours. Missing this diagnosis = medicolegal catastrophe.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Cerebellar & Gait Examination",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">DANISH mnemonic for cerebellar signs</div>Dysdiadochokinesia · Ataxia (gait/truncal) · Nystagmus · Intention tremor · Slurred speech (dysarthria/scanning) · Hypotonia</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Gait type</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Hemiplegic</td><td>Arm flexed/adducted, leg extended, circumduction of affected leg</td><td>Contralateral UMN lesion (stroke, tumour)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spastic (scissoring)</td><td>Both legs stiff, crossing over (scissoring), walks on toes</td><td>Bilateral UMN: cerebral palsy, cord compression, MS</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Parkinsonian</td><td>Stooped, shuffling, festinating (accelerating), reduced arm swing, en-bloc turning, freezing</td><td>Parkinson's disease, drug-induced</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cerebellar (ataxic)</td><td>Wide-based, staggering, falls to side of lesion, cannot tandem walk</td><td>Cerebellar lesion, alcohol, MS, drugs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sensory ataxic</td><td>Wide-based, high-stepping, foot slapping, worse with eyes closed (Romberg +ve)</td><td>Posterior column disease: subacute combined degeneration, tabes dorsalis, diabetic neuropathy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Foot drop (steppage)</td><td>Exaggerated hip/knee flexion to clear foot, foot slaps</td><td>Common peroneal nerve palsy, L4/5 root, CMT</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Antalgic</td><td>Short stance phase on painful side</td><td>Hip/knee/foot pathology</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trendelenburg</td><td>Pelvis drops to unaffected side during stance on affected leg</td><td>Weak hip abductors (gluteus medius): OA hip, hip fracture, Paget's</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apraxic</td><td>Magnetic gait — feet seem glued to floor, takes small shuffles, trunk/arms normal</td><td>Normal pressure hydrocephalus, frontal lobe lesion</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Romberg's test: stand feet together, eyes open (tests cerebellar function), then close eyes. Falls with eyes closed = positive Romberg = posterior column/proprioceptive problem (NOT cerebellar — cerebellar patients fall with eyes open too).</div></div>`},

  {t:"Mini Mental State & Cognitive Testing",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">MMSE (Folstein) — 30 points</div>Mild impairment: 21–24 · Moderate: 10–20 · Severe: &lt;10. Adjust for education/age.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Domain</th><th>Test</th><th>Max score</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Orientation in time</td><td>Year, season, month, date, day</td><td>5</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Orientation in place</td><td>Country, county, town, hospital, ward</td><td>5</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Registration</td><td>Name 3 objects, repeat immediately</td><td>3</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Attention &amp; calculation</td><td>Serial 7s (100-7-7...) or WORLD backwards</td><td>5</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Recall</td><td>Recall 3 objects from registration</td><td>3</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Language</td><td>Name 2 objects, repeat phrase, 3-step command, read/write sentence, copy pentagon</td><td>9</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">4AT — Rapid delirium screening (preferred at bedside)</div>Alertness + AMT4 (age, DOB, place, year) + Attention (months backward) + Acute change: Score 0 = unlikely delirium. ≥4 = possible delirium. Takes &lt;2 minutes. More sensitive than MMSE for delirium.</div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The clock drawing test is a quick screen: ask patient to draw a clock face showing 10 past 11. Tests visuospatial, executive function, and semantic memory. Any error is significant. Also assess: frontal lobe (verbal fluency — say as many animals as possible in 1 minute — &lt;12 suggests frontal impairment).</div></div>`}
],

ms:[
  {t:"GALS Screen (Gait, Arms, Legs, Spine)",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">GALS is a 3-minute screening tool — if ANY abnormality found, go to detailed regional examination</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">G</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Gait</span> — Ask patient to walk to end of room and back. Normal? Any limp, asymmetry, antalgic gait, difficulty turning?</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">A</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Arms</span> — "Hands behind head" (shoulder abduction/external rotation). "Hands out in front" (wrist extension). "Turn hands over" (supination). "Make a fist" (grip). Squeeze MCPJs (tenderness). Touch each finger to thumb (fine motor). Inspect hands (swelling, deformity).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">L</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Legs</span> — Patient supine. Feel for knee effusion (patellar tap, bulge sign). Passive hip flexion/internal rotation. Passive knee flexion. Squeeze MTPs (tenderness). Inspect feet (deformity, callosities).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">S</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Spine</span> — "Look at the wall, look at the floor" (cervical flex/extend). "Look over shoulder" (rotation). "Run hand down leg" (lumbar lateral flexion). Thoracolumbar extension. Schober's test if ankylosing spondylitis suspected.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always ask screening questions before GALS: "Do you have any pain or stiffness in muscles, joints, or back?" "Can you dress yourself without difficulty?" "Can you walk up and down stairs?" Positive screening = detailed examination needed.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Hand & Wrist Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspect dorsum and palm</span> — Swelling (MCPJs, PIPJs, DIPJs, wrists), deformity (ulnar deviation, swan neck, boutonnière, Z-deformity of thumb), muscle wasting (thenar, hypothenar, intrinsic), skin changes (psoriatic plaques, vasculitis, tophi)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Palpate</span> — Squeeze MCPJs (metacarpophalangeal tenderness = RA). Feel each joint individually. Temperature (warm = active synovitis). Subcutaneous nodules (extensor surfaces = RA). Tophi (helix of ear, olecranon = gout).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Move</span> — Wrist: flex/extend/deviation. Fingers: flex/extend/abduct/adduct. Opposition of thumb. Grip strength (compare sides).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Function</span> — "Do up a button / pick up a coin / write your name" — functional tests.</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Deformity</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Swan neck</td><td>PIPJ hyperextension + DIPJ flexion</td><td>Rheumatoid arthritis ★, joint hypermobility</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Boutonnière</td><td>PIPJ flexion + DIPJ hyperextension</td><td>Rheumatoid arthritis, trauma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Z-deformity (thumb)</td><td>MCP flexion + IP hyperextension</td><td>Rheumatoid arthritis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Heberden's nodes</td><td>Bony swelling at DIPJs</td><td>Osteoarthritis ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bouchard's nodes</td><td>Bony swelling at PIPJs</td><td>Osteoarthritis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ulnar deviation</td><td>Fingers deviated toward ulna at MCPJs</td><td>Rheumatoid arthritis ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trigger finger</td><td>Finger locks in flexion, snaps with extension</td><td>Flexor tendon sheath thickening: DM, RA, idiopathic</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Knee Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspect standing</span> — Valgus (knock-knee), varus (bow-leg), genu recurvatum, swelling, quadriceps wasting, skin changes</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Patellar tap</span> — Empty suprapatellar pouch by stroking medial/lateral to patella, press patella down — tap = effusion (&gt;30mL)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Bulge sign</span> — Milk fluid from medial compartment to lateral, then press lateral — bulge reappears medially. Small effusions (&lt;30mL).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Range of motion</span> — Normal: 0° extension to 135° flexion. Loss of full extension = locked knee (meniscal tear/loose body), flexion contracture (OA)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Ligament tests</span> — MCL: valgus stress at 30°. LCL: varus stress at 30°. ACL: anterior draw (Lachman at 30°, most sensitive). PCL: posterior draw test.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Meniscal tests</span> — McMurray's: external rotation + extension (medial meniscus), internal rotation + extension (lateral). Click or pain = positive.</div></div>
    </div>`},

  {t:"Hip & Spine Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Hip inspection</span> — Trendelenburg test: stand on one leg, pelvis should not drop on opposite side. Positive = weak ipsilateral hip abductors (OA, fracture, Paget's)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Hip ROM (FABER)</span> — Flexion (120°), ABduction (45°), External Rotation (45°). Thomas test: flex both hips maximally, extend one — fixed flexion deformity. FABER/FABERE pain = hip pathology or SI joint.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Spine inspection</span> — Scoliosis (Adam's forward bend test), kyphosis, lordosis, muscle spasm, skin overlying spine</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Cervical spine</span> — Flex/extend (chin to chest / look up), rotation (chin to shoulder), lateral flexion. Spurling test: compress neck + rotate — radiculopathy if reproduces arm pain</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ms)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Lumbar spine</span> — Schober's test (ankylosing spondylitis): mark 5cm below and 10cm above L5/S1, bend forward — should increase &gt;5cm (total &gt;20cm). SLR: raise straight leg — &lt;60° + sciatic radiation = L4/5/S1 disc herniation</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Schober's test &lt;20cm at maximal forward flexion = restricted lumbar movement. Combined with morning stiffness &gt;45min, buttock pain, improved with exercise = ankylosing spondylitis until proven otherwise. Check HLA-B27 and MRI sacroiliac joints.</div></div>`}
],

th:[
  {t:"Thyroid Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspect from front</span> — Neck swelling? Visible goitre? Ask patient to swallow (sip of water) — thyroid moves up on swallowing (distinguishes from other neck masses)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Palpate from behind</span> — Both hands around neck, thumbs at back. Feel isthmus (over trachea), lobes (lateral). Size, consistency (soft = colloid goitre, firm = Hashimoto's, hard/irregular = malignancy), tenderness (thyroiditis), nodules (single vs multinodular)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Palpate on swallowing</span> — Feel movement with swallow. Does it move? (Should = thyroid/thyroglossal cyst). Fixed mass = malignancy.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Percuss</span> — Over sternum for retrosternal extension. Dull = retrosternal goitre</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Auscultate</span> — Thyroid bruit (thyrotoxicosis: Graves' disease — increased vascularity)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Eyes</span> — Exophthalmos, lid lag, lid retraction, chemosis, ophthalmoplegia (Graves' ophthalmopathy)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--th)">7</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Other signs</span> — Pretibial myxoedema (Graves'), thyroid acropachy (periosteal new bone — rare)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Pemberton's sign: raise arms above head for 1 minute — facial plethora, JVP rise, or stridor = superior vena caval obstruction from retrosternal goitre. Always check for tracheal deviation and dysphagia in large goitres.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Hyperthyroidism vs Hypothyroidism Signs",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Hyperthyroidism</th><th>Hypothyroidism</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>General</td><td>Weight loss, sweating, heat intolerance, agitation</td><td>Weight gain, cold intolerance, fatigue, lethargy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pulse</td><td>Tachycardia, AF, palpitations</td><td>Bradycardia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Skin/Hair</td><td>Warm, moist, fine hair, onycholysis, spider naevi</td><td>Dry, coarse skin, coarse hair, hair loss (outer 1/3 eyebrow)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reflexes</td><td>Brisk (hyperreflexia)</td><td>Slow relaxing (hung-up reflexes) ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tremor</td><td>Fine tremor (outstretched hands)</td><td>None (may have coarse ataxia)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Eyes (Graves' only)</td><td>Exophthalmos, lid lag, lid retraction, ophthalmoplegia</td><td>Periorbital oedema</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Voice</td><td>Normal or anxious</td><td>Husky, deep, hoarse voice (myxoedema)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Goitre</td><td>Diffuse (Graves'), nodular (MNG, toxic adenoma)</td><td>Hashimoto's (initially enlarged, then atrophic)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Neurology</td><td>Anxiety, irritability, proximal myopathy</td><td>Carpal tunnel syndrome, cerebellar ataxia, cognitive impairment</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Cushing's Syndrome Examination",c:`
    <div class="slist">
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Central obesity</span><span class="sdesc">Truncal fat with thin limbs (buffalo hump, moon face, supraclavicular fat pads)</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Purple striae</span><span class="sdesc">Wide (&gt;1cm), purple/red stretch marks on abdomen, thighs, breasts. White striae = normal.</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Thin skin &amp; bruising</span><span class="sdesc">Skin easily bruised, paper-thin, poor wound healing</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Hypertension</span><span class="sdesc">Often significant, secondary to cortisol mineralocorticoid effects</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Proximal myopathy</span><span class="sdesc">Difficulty rising from chair, climbing stairs — test: stand from seated without arms</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Acne &amp; hirsutism</span><span class="sdesc">Androgen excess — facial hair in women, acne</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--th)"></span><div><span class="sname">Glucose intolerance</span><span class="sdesc">Cortisol → insulin resistance → secondary diabetes</span></div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always ask about steroid medication — iatrogenic Cushing's is far more common than endogenous. Investigate if suspected: 24-hr urine cortisol, midnight salivary cortisol, or 1mg overnight dexamethasone suppression test. Then localise: ACTH-dependent (pituitary = Cushing's disease, ectopic) vs ACTH-independent (adrenal tumour).</div></div>`}
],

ey:[
  {t:"Visual Acuity & Visual Fields",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Snellen chart</span> — 6 metres from chart, one eye covered, with glasses/contact lenses. Record as 6/6 (normal) to 6/60 (counts fingers). &lt;6/60: count fingers, hand movements, light perception.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Pinhole test</span> — Reduced VA through pinhole = refractive error (correctable). No improvement = other pathology (cataract, macular, neural).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Visual fields by confrontation</span> — Examiner and patient at eye level, 1 metre apart, cover opposite eyes. Wiggle finger in each quadrant. Compare patient's response to examiner's (who has normal fields).</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Field defect</th><th>Location of lesion</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Monocular blindness (one eye)</td><td>Optic nerve or retina (anterior to chiasm)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bitemporal hemianopia</td><td>Optic chiasm: pituitary adenoma ★, craniopharyngioma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Homonymous hemianopia</td><td>Optic tract, radiation, or visual cortex (posterior to chiasm) — contralateral side</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Superior quadrantanopia</td><td>Inferior temporal lobe (Meyer's loop) — contralateral superior temporal field lost</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Inferior quadrantanopia</td><td>Parietal lobe</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Central scotoma</td><td>Macula, optic nerve (optic neuritis: MS, temporal arteritis)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Bitemporal hemianopia: the patient cannot see things to the left with the left eye OR to the right with the right eye — they bump into things on both sides. Classic presentation of pituitary macroadenoma. First test: Snellen (VA often preserved early). Always check visual fields in headache + visual symptoms.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Pupil Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspect both pupils</span> — Size (normal 2–6mm), shape (round, regular), symmetry. Anisocoria = unequal pupils</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Direct light reflex</span> — Shine light from temporal side into one eye — that pupil constricts (direct reflex)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Consensual light reflex</span> — Light in one eye — opposite pupil also constricts</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Swinging flashlight test (RAPD)</span> — Swing light rapidly between eyes. Relative afferent pupillary defect (Marcus Gunn): the affected eye's pupil DILATES when light shone on it (optic nerve problem)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ey)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Accommodation reflex</span> — Ask patient to look at distant object, then near finger — both pupils constrict</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Pupil finding</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Dilated, fixed (unilateral)</td><td>CN III palsy (surgical: posterior communicating artery aneurysm ★, herniation). Atropine drops.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Constricted (unilateral)</td><td>Horner's syndrome: ptosis + miosis + anhidrosis (Pancoast tumour, carotid dissection, lateral medullary syndrome)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Both fixed and dilated</td><td>Brain death, severe hypoxia, atropine, cocaine, sympathomimetics</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Both constricted (pinpoint)</td><td>Opioid overdose ★, pontine lesion, cholinergic (organophosphate)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>RAPD</td><td>Optic neuritis (MS ★), optic nerve compression, severe retinal disease, amblyopia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Argyll Robertson</td><td>Reacts to accommodation but NOT to light = neurosyphilis ("prostitute's pupil — accommodates but doesn't react")</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Fundoscopy",c:`
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">Technique</div>Dilate pupils (tropicamide 1%) if possible. Dark room. Set ophthalmoscope to +2 lens initially. Approach from temporal side at 15°. Focus on optic disc first, then vessels, macula (ask patient to look directly at light).</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Description</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Papilloedema</td><td>Disc swelling, blurred margins, haemorrhages, engorged veins. Absent venous pulsation earliest sign.</td><td>Raised ICP ★ (tumour, hydrocephalus, hypertensive emergency, IIH)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Optic atrophy</td><td>Pale white disc, sharp margins</td><td>Optic neuritis (MS), glaucoma, compression, ischaemia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Diabetic retinopathy</td><td>Dot/blot haemorrhages (deep), flame haemorrhages (superficial), microaneurysms (earliest), exudates, new vessels (proliferative)</td><td>Diabetes mellitus</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypertensive retinopathy</td><td>Silver/copper wiring (AV ratio &lt;2/3), AV nipping, flame haemorrhages, cotton-wool spots, papilloedema (grade 4)</td><td>Hypertension (Keith-Wagener grade 1–4)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Retinal vein occlusion</td><td>"Stormy sunset" — flame haemorrhages in all quadrants (CRVO) or one quadrant (BRVO)</td><td>Hypertension, DM, thrombophilia, glaucoma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Retinal artery occlusion</td><td>Pale retina, cherry-red spot at macula</td><td>Emboli (carotid atheroma, cardiac), giant cell arteritis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cupped disc</td><td>Cup:disc ratio &gt;0.5, nasal shift of vessels</td><td>Glaucoma ★</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Papilloedema is a bilateral finding — unilateral disc swelling = usually optic neuritis or ischaemic optic neuropathy. In papilloedema, the earliest sign is loss of venous pulsation (only visible in 80% of normals). Always examine the fundus in headache, visual symptoms, hypertensive emergency, and suspected raised ICP.</div></div>`}
],

er:[
  {t:"Ear Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">External inspection</span> — Auricle shape, size, position (low-set = chromosomal syndromes), pre-auricular pits/tags, discharge, scars (mastoidectomy). Behind ear: swelling over mastoid = mastoiditis (Bezold abscess)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Otoscopy</span> — Pull pinna up and back (adults) or down and back (children). Insert speculum. Examine: canal (wax, discharge, foreign body, swelling), tympanic membrane (normal = pearl-grey, cone of light at 5 o'clock)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Tympanic membrane</span> — Perforation (central = safe, marginal = cholesteatoma risk), retraction pockets, fluid level/bubbles (OME), haemotympanum (basal skull fracture), chalk patches (tympanosclerosis)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Hearing test</th><th>Technique</th><th>Result interpretation</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Whisper test</td><td>Stand behind patient at 60cm. Exhaled whisper of 3 numbers. Repeat other ear.</td><td>Failure to repeat = significant hearing loss</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rinne test (512Hz)</td><td>Fork on mastoid (BC) — when sound gone, move to external ear (AC)</td><td>Rinne +ve (AC &gt; BC) = normal OR sensorineural. Rinne –ve (BC &gt; AC) = conductive hearing loss ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Weber test (512Hz)</td><td>Fork on centre of forehead</td><td>Lateralises to WORSE ear = conductive. Lateralises to BETTER ear = sensorineural on other side.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Rinne negative (BC > AC) + Weber lateralises to SAME ear = CONDUCTIVE hearing loss on that side (e.g. glue ear, wax, otosclerosis). Rinne positive + Weber lateralises to OPPOSITE ear = SENSORINEURAL hearing loss on Weber side (e.g. acoustic neuroma, noise damage).</div></div>`},

  {t:"Nose & Throat Examination",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Nose inspection</span> — External: shape, deviation, swelling, trauma. Occlude each nostril: patent? Nasal speculum: mucosa (pale/boggy = allergic rhinitis, red = infective), septum (deviation, perforation — cocaine, Wegener's, sarcoid), turbinates, polyps</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Throat (oropharynx)</span> — Adequate lighting + tongue depressor. Lips, teeth, gums, tongue (movement, atrophy, fasciculations), buccal mucosa (aphthae, white patches = leukoplakia/candida), palate (high arched = Marfan's), tonsils, posterior pharyngeal wall, uvula</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Tonsils grading</span> — 1 = within tonsillar pillars. 2 = at pillar level. 3 = beyond pillars. 4 = "kissing tonsils" (touching midline)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Voice</span> — Hoarse = recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy (left: aortic arch pathology, lung/mediastinal ca; right: thyroid ca, right-sided lesions) or laryngeal pathology. Muffled "hot potato" voice = peritonsillar abscess.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">A unilateral tonsil larger than the other = malignancy until proven otherwise (tonsillar lymphoma). Quinsy (peritonsillar abscess): uvula deviates away from affected side + unilateral swelling + trismus. Emergency I&D needed. Epiglottitis: tripod position + stridor + drooling + toxic — do NOT examine throat (can precipitate complete obstruction).</div></div>`},

  {t:"Neck Examination & Lymph Nodes",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspect</span> — Swelling, asymmetry, scars, skin changes, pulsations (carotid), distended veins (SVC obstruction)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Palpate lymph nodes systematically</span> — Submental → submandibular → pre-auricular → post-auricular → occipital → anterior cervical → posterior cervical → supraclavicular (Virchow's) → axillary</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--er)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Lymph node character</span> — Size, consistency (soft/firm/hard/rubbery), tenderness, fixation to skin or deep tissues, overlying skin changes</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Character</th><th>Likely diagnosis</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Tender, soft, mobile</td><td>Reactive lymphadenopathy (infection ★): URTI, dental, EBV, CMV</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hard, irregular, fixed, non-tender</td><td>Malignant lymphadenopathy: metastatic cancer ★, lymphoma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rubbery, non-tender, mobile</td><td>Lymphoma ★ (Hodgkin's — usually cervical)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fluctuant, tender</td><td>Abscess (TB cold abscess — fluctuant but NOT hot)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Left supraclavicular (Virchow's = Troisier's)</td><td>Intra-abdominal malignancy (gastric, pancreatic, colorectal) — via thoracic duct</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Right supraclavicular</td><td>Lung, oesophageal, mediastinal malignancy</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always examine ALL lymph node groups, not just where the patient complains. A cervical lump in an adult &gt;40 is malignant until proven otherwise. "Never biopsy a lymph node unless you have excluded a primary source." — look for primaries in head, neck, mouth, lungs, abdomen first.</div></div>`}
],

gn:[
  {t:"Breast Examination",c:`
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">Always ensure a chaperone is present and explain each step beforehand</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Inspect — 4 positions</span> — Arms at side, hands on hips (tenses pectorals), hands behind head, lean forward. Look: symmetry, skin changes (peau d'orange, erythema, ulceration), nipple changes (inversion — new vs old, discharge, eczematous = Paget's), contour changes, visible lumps.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Palpate (supine, arm behind head)</span> — Systematic: 4 quadrants + tail of Spence (axillary tail) + areola/subareolar. Use flat of fingers in circular motion. Any lump: site, size (cm), shape, surface, consistency, mobility, tenderness, skin tethering, deep fixation.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Nipple</span> — Squeeze gently from the periphery toward nipple. Note discharge (serous/sanguineous/purulent). Single duct vs multiple duct discharge.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Lymph nodes</span> — Axillary (4 groups: anterior, posterior, medial, apical), supraclavicular, cervical. Support patient's arm with your hand to relax pectorals.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Triple assessment for breast lumps: clinical examination + imaging (USS if &lt;35, mammogram if &gt;35) + core needle biopsy. Do not discharge a patient with a breast lump on the basis of clinical examination alone. Paget's disease of nipple (eczematous change) = underlying DCIS or invasive cancer until proven otherwise.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Per Speculum & Bimanual Examination",c:`
    <div class="alert a-danger"><div class="a-label">⚠️ Always ensure consent, chaperone, privacy, and patient positioning (lithotomy or left lateral) before examination</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">External inspection</span> — Vulva: skin (erythema, leukoplakia, lesions, ulceration, warts), Bartholin's glands, urethral meatus, vaginal introitus</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Speculum examination</span> — Warm speculum, insert obliquely then rotate. Open to visualise cervix. Note: discharge (colour, odour), erosion (ectropion), polyps, nabothian cysts, contact bleeding. Take smear/swabs if indicated.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Bimanual examination</span> — Two fingers (index + middle) vaginally, one hand abdominally. Assess: cervical excitation (cervical motion tenderness = PID/ectopic), uterine size/position/mobility/tenderness, adnexal masses/tenderness (ovaries)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Cervical excitation (chandelier sign)</td><td>Pain on moving cervix = PID, ectopic pregnancy ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Uterus enlarged</td><td>Pregnancy ★, fibroids, adenomyosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Retroverted uterus</td><td>Normal variant (20%), or fixed = endometriosis, PID</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Adnexal mass</td><td>Ovarian cyst/tumour, ectopic, tubo-ovarian abscess, hydrosalpinx</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cervical lesion (firm, irregular)</td><td>Cervical cancer until proven otherwise — refer under 2-week wait</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Male Genitourinary Examination",c:`
    <div class="alert a-warn"><div class="a-label">Always ensure chaperone and consent before examination</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Penis inspection</span> — Phimosis (non-retractile foreskin), paraphimosis (retracted, constricting), hypospadias, epispadias, discharge (urethritis), lesions (warts, ulcers = STI, SCC)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Scrotal inspection</span> — Oedema (local vs referred), skin changes, position of testes</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Palpate each testis</span> — Size (normal 4×3cm), consistency, tenderness. Lie finger and thumb along testis. Separate epididymis (posterior). Get above swelling — can you get above it? (Cannot = inguinoscrotal hernia)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gn)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Transillumination</span> — Apply light — transilluminates = fluid (hydrocele, epididymal cyst). Does NOT transilluminate = solid (hernia, tumour, haematocele)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Painless testicular mass</td><td>Testicular cancer ★ until proven otherwise — urgent USS</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Painful, high-riding testis + absent cremasteric reflex</td><td>Testicular torsion ★★★ — surgical emergency. Do NOT wait for Doppler if high suspicion.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tender epididymis, normal testis</td><td>Epididymo-orchitis (STI: chlamydia in young; UTI organism in older men)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bag of worms (standing, disappears lying)</td><td>Varicocele — left-sided ★. Right-sided = possible retroperitoneal mass (renal ca compressing IVC)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Transilluminates, cystic</td><td>Hydrocele (surrounds testis) or epididymal cyst (separate from testis)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Testicular torsion: "if in doubt, take them out." Any patient with acute scrotal pain under 35 is torsion until proven otherwise. Torsion most common 12–18 years (bimodal peak in neonates). Window for testicular salvage: 6 hours (100%) → 12 hours (50%) → 24 hours (&lt;10%). Never delay for investigations if clinical suspicion is high.</div></div>`}
],

sk:[
  {t:"Skin Lesion Description",c:`
    <div class="alert a-info"><div class="a-label">Systematic description of any skin lesion — use this framework always</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Description options</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Site &amp; distribution</td><td>Localised / generalised / dermatomal / extensor / flexural / photosensitive / intertriginous</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Number</td><td>Solitary / multiple / confluent</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Size</td><td>Measure in cm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Shape</td><td>Round / oval / irregular / linear / annular (ring) / serpiginous (snake-like) / discoid</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Border</td><td>Well-defined / poorly defined / raised / rolled / everted</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Colour</td><td>Red / brown / black / white / yellow / violaceous / hyperpigmented / hypopigmented</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Surface</td><td>Smooth / rough / scaly / crusted / verrucous / keratotic</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Secondary changes</td><td>Excoriation / lichenification / fissuring / atrophy / scarring / ulceration</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px"><thead><tr><th>Primary lesion</th><th>Definition</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Macule</td><td>Flat colour change &lt;1cm</td><td>Freckle, café-au-lait spot, vitiligo</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Patch</td><td>Flat colour change &gt;1cm</td><td>Port-wine stain, vitiligo patch</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Papule</td><td>Raised solid lesion &lt;1cm</td><td>Acne, wart, DLE</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Plaque</td><td>Raised solid lesion &gt;1cm</td><td>Psoriasis ★, lichen planus</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nodule</td><td>Raised solid &gt;1cm, deeper than papule</td><td>Dermoid cyst, lipoma, melanoma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vesicle</td><td>Fluid-filled blister &lt;1cm</td><td>Chickenpox ★, dermatitis herpetiformis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bulla</td><td>Fluid-filled blister &gt;1cm</td><td>Pemphigus ★, pemphigoid, burns</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pustule</td><td>Pus-filled raised lesion</td><td>Acne, folliculitis, impetigo</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wheal (urticaria)</td><td>Transient raised oedematous lesion</td><td>Urticaria / hives</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Common Rash Patterns",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Distribution</th><th>Lesion type</th><th>Key features</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Psoriasis</td><td>Extensor surfaces ★, scalp, nails, flexures (inverse)</td><td>Well-defined red plaques + silvery scale</td><td>Auspitz sign (bleeding on removing scale), nail pitting, onycholysis, koebnerisation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Eczema (atopic)</td><td>Flexures ★ (antecubital, popliteal), face in infants</td><td>Ill-defined erythema, vesicles, weeping, lichenification</td><td>Pruritic, personal/family atopy, Dennie-Morgan fold, keratosis pilaris</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lichen planus</td><td>Wrists, ankles, oral mucosa</td><td>Flat-topped violaceous papules + Wickham's striae (white lacy surface)</td><td>Pruritic, koebnerisation, 4 Ps: Purple, Polygonal, Pruritic, Papules</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tinea (ringworm)</td><td>Any body site (corporis), groin (cruris), feet (pedis)</td><td>Annular plaque with raised scaly border, central clearing</td><td>KOH prep shows hyphae, Wood's lamp</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Herpes zoster (shingles)</td><td>Dermatomal — unilateral, does NOT cross midline</td><td>Grouped vesicles on erythematous base, follows dermatome</td><td>Prodromal pain before rash. Ramsay Hunt (VII): ear + face. PHN risk in elderly.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SLE butterfly rash</td><td>Malar rash — cheeks + nose bridge, spares nasolabial folds</td><td>Erythematous, sometimes oedematous</td><td>Spares nasolabial folds (vs rosacea which involves them). Photosensitive. ANA positive.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Erythema nodosum</td><td>Anterior shins ★ (rarely thighs/arms)</td><td>Tender, raised, red nodules</td><td>Causes: Sarcoidosis ★, IBD, streptococcal, TB, drugs (OCP, sulphonamides), pregnancy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Erythema multiforme</td><td>Extremities (dorsum hands) → centripetal spread</td><td>Target lesions (3 zones: pale centre, dark ring, red halo)</td><td>Causes: HSV ★ (most common), Mycoplasma, drugs. Stevens-Johnson if mucous membranes (&gt;30% BSA = TEN)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Skin Signs of Systemic Disease",c:`
    <div class="slist">
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Acanthosis nigricans</span><span class="sdesc">Velvety hyperpigmentation in axillae/neck/groin — Insulin resistance ★, T2DM, GI malignancy (sudden onset in adult)</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Pyoderma gangrenosum</span><span class="sdesc">Painful ulcer with undermined purple border — IBD ★ (Crohn's/UC), RA, haematological malignancy</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Dermatitis herpetiformis</span><span class="sdesc">Intensely itchy vesicles on extensor surfaces — Coeliac disease ★ (IgA deposits in dermis)</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Necrobiosis lipoidica</span><span class="sdesc">Shiny yellow-brown plaques with telangiectasia on shins — Diabetes mellitus ★</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Xanthomata</span><span class="sdesc">Tuberous (over joints), tendon (Achilles/extensor tendons), xanthelasma (eyelids) — Hyperlipidaemia ★, FH</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Spider naevi</span><span class="sdesc">Central arteriole + radiating vessels, blanch with pressure — ≥5 on trunk = liver disease ★ (portal hypertension)</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Gottron's papules</span><span class="sdesc">Purple papules over MCPJs/PIPJs — Dermatomyositis ★ (also heliotrope rash around eyes)</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Café-au-lait spots</span><span class="sdesc">Light brown macules — Neurofibromatosis type 1 ★ (≥6 spots &gt;1.5cm = NF1 diagnostic criterion)</span></div></div>
      <div class="sitem"><span class="sdot" style="background:var(--sk)"></span><div><span class="sname">Osler-Weber-Rendu (HHT)</span><span class="sdesc">Telangiectasia on lips/tongue/fingers — Hereditary haemorrhagic telangiectasia (recurrent epistaxis)</span></div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">ABCDE for melanoma: Asymmetry, Border (irregular), Colour (variable), Diameter (&gt;6mm), Evolution (change over time). Any pigmented lesion that is changing, itching, or bleeding = dermatology referral. Never biopsy a suspicious melanoma in primary care — refer for excisional biopsy by specialist.</div></div>`}
],

gp:[
  {t:"General Peripheral Signs — Hands",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Sign</th><th>Description</th><th>Association</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Clubbing</td><td>Loss of nail angle, drumstick appearance, fluctuant nail bed (Schamroth window test)</td><td>Respiratory: lung ca ★, fibrosis, empyema, bronchiectasis, cystic fibrosis. Cardiac: cyanotic CHD, IE. GI: cirrhosis, IBD, coeliac. Thyroid: thyroid acropachy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Koilonychia</td><td>Spoon-shaped nails (concave)</td><td>Iron deficiency anaemia ★, idiopathic</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Leukonychia (white nails)</td><td>White discolouration — transverse lines (Mees' lines) or diffuse (Terry's nails)</td><td>Hypoalbuminaemia (liver disease, nephrotic syndrome). Mees' lines = arsenic poisoning, chemotherapy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Onycholysis</td><td>Nail separates from nail bed</td><td>Thyrotoxicosis, psoriasis, trauma, fungal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nail pitting</td><td>Small depressions in nail surface</td><td>Psoriasis ★, alopecia areata, eczema</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Splinter haemorrhages</td><td>Linear red-brown streaks under nail</td><td>Infective endocarditis ★, trauma (most common), vasculitis, sepsis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Palmar erythema</td><td>Red palms, sparing central palm</td><td>Liver disease ★, pregnancy, thyrotoxicosis, RA, polycythaemia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dupuytren's contracture</td><td>Palmar fibrosis, ring finger flexion</td><td>Alcohol ★, idiopathic, DM, epilepsy, manual labour</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Asterixis (liver flap)</td><td>Coarse irregular tremor with outstretched wrists — flapping</td><td>Hepatic encephalopathy ★, CO₂ retention (type 2 RF), renal failure, Wilson's disease</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"General Peripheral Signs — Face & Eyes",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Sign</th><th>Association</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Malar flush</td><td>Butterfly rash over cheeks — mitral stenosis (pulmonary hypertension), SLE</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Central cyanosis (lips/tongue)</td><td>SpO₂ &lt;85%. Respiratory failure, cyanotic heart disease, severe cardiac failure, haemoglobinopathy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Jaundice (sclerae)</td><td>Earliest visible sign (when serum bilirubin &gt;35 µmol/L). Scleral icterus precedes skin jaundice.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Corneal arcus</td><td>White/grey ring around corneal periphery. Under 45 = hyperlipidaemia. Over 60 = normal ageing (arcus senilis)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Xanthelasma</td><td>Yellow plaques on eyelids. Hyperlipidaemia — but 50% have normal lipids. FH screen warranted.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Facial telangiectasia</td><td>Rosacea, liver disease, SLE (not crossing nasolabial folds), systemic sclerosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Periorbital oedema</td><td>Hypothyroidism ★, nephrotic syndrome, SVC obstruction, anaphylaxis, angioedema</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kayser-Fleischer rings</td><td>Golden-brown ring at corneal periphery (slit lamp needed if subtle). Wilson's disease ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cushingoid facies</td><td>Moon face, plethora, acne, hirsutism — Cushing's syndrome, steroid therapy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acromegaly facies</td><td>Prognathism (enlarged jaw), prominent supraorbital ridge, macroglossia, wide nose, oily skin</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Vital Signs — Normal Values & Interpretation",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Temperature</div><div class="nv-val">36.1–37.2°C</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Heart rate</div><div class="nv-val">60–100 bpm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Respiratory rate</div><div class="nv-val">12–20 /min</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Blood pressure</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;130/85 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SpO₂ (room air)</div><div class="nv-val">95–100%</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SpO₂ (COPD target)</div><div class="nv-val">88–92%</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Capillary glucose</div><div class="nv-val">4–7 mmol/L fasting</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">GCS</div><div class="nv-val">15/15 (normal)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Vital sign abnormality</th><th>Threshold</th><th>Think about</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Fever</td><td>&gt;38.0°C</td><td>Infection ★, inflammatory conditions, malignancy (lymphoma), drugs, DVT/PE, transfusion reaction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hyperthermia</td><td>&gt;40°C</td><td>Heat stroke, malignant hyperthermia, serotonin syndrome, NMS (antipsychotics)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypothermia</td><td>&lt;35.0°C</td><td>Exposure, hypothyroidism, Addison's, hypoglycaemia, alcohol, sepsis (in elderly)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bradycardia</td><td>&lt;60 bpm</td><td>Athletic, beta-blockers, complete heart block, hypothyroidism, raised ICP, inferior MI, vasovagal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tachycardia</td><td>&gt;100 bpm</td><td>Sepsis, pain, anxiety, AF, thyrotoxicosis, anaemia, PE, hypovolaemia, drugs (salbutamol)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypotension</td><td>SBP &lt;90 mmHg</td><td>Septic shock, cardiogenic shock, hypovolaemia, anaphylaxis, Addisonian crisis, PE (massive)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tachypnoea</td><td>&gt;20 /min</td><td>Earliest sign of deterioration. Sepsis, pneumonia, PE, metabolic acidosis, pain, anxiety</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Tachypnoea is the most sensitive early sign of physiological deterioration — more sensitive than tachycardia or hypotension. A patient with RR of 25 who looks well deserves as much attention as one with a blood pressure of 90. Never dismiss an isolated elevated respiratory rate.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Nutritional & Fluid Assessment",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gp)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Nutritional assessment</span> — BMI = weight(kg)/height²(m). Under 18.5 = underweight. 18.5–24.9 = normal. 25–29.9 = overweight. ≥30 = obese. Waist circumference: &gt;94cm (M) / &gt;80cm (F) = metabolic risk.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gp)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Signs of dehydration</span> — Dry mucous membranes, sunken eyes, reduced skin turgor (pinch test — slow recoil), reduced urine output, tachycardia, orthostatic hypotension, confusion (late sign)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gp)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Signs of fluid overload</span> — Peripheral pitting oedema, elevated JVP, S3 gallop, bibasal crackles, ascites, pleural effusions, pulmonary oedema on CXR</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--gp)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Malnutrition signs</span> — Bitot's spots (Vit A deficiency), angular cheilitis (B2, iron, folate), glossitis (B2, B3, B6, B12, iron), koilonychia (iron), peripheral neuropathy (B1/B12), pellagra skin (B3)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">MUST score (Malnutrition Universal Screening Tool): BMI + weight loss + acute disease effect. Use on all inpatient admissions. Malnutrition prolongs hospital stay, increases infection risk, delays wound healing, and independently predicts mortality. Always check MUST on admission and refer to dietitian if score ≥2.</div></div>`}
]

};
const D_BNYS = {

ca:[
  {t:"BNYS History Taking — Naturopathic Framework",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Naturopathic perspective</div>The aim is to understand the WHOLE person — physical, mental, emotional, social, and spiritual dimensions — not just the disease. Always ask: what is obstructing the body's innate healing force (Vis Medicatrix Naturae)?</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Chief complaint (CC)</span> — In patient's own words. Duration, onset, progression. Previous episodes. Previous treatments (allopathic + naturopathic).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Dietary history</span> — Meal frequency, types of food (raw/cooked/processed/non-veg), eating habits (rushed/mindful), water intake (L/day), tea/coffee/alcohol intake, fasting history, appetite, digestion, bowel habits</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Sleep history</span> — Hours, quality (restful/disturbed), dreams, sleep time, position, snoring, daytime drowsiness</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Physical activity</span> — Type, frequency, duration. Occupation (sedentary/active). Exercise tolerance. Any yoga/meditation practice?</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Mental & emotional status</span> — Stress levels (work/personal), anxiety, depression, anger, emotional triggers, relationships, recent life events</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Elimination history</span> — Bowel frequency (ideal = once daily, morning), consistency, colour. Urinary frequency, colour, odour. Sweating pattern.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">7</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Sunlight & fresh air exposure</span> — Time outdoors, sunlight access, ventilation at home/work</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">8</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Social & environmental history</span> — Occupation, pollution exposure, smoking/alcohol/tobacco, economic stress, social support</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">9</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">ICE — Ideas, Concerns, Expectations</span> — What does the patient think is causing this? What are they most worried about? What do they expect from naturopathic treatment?</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Clinical Pearl</div><div class="pt">The naturopathic history is often more revealing than lab tests. A patient with chronic fatigue who sleeps 5 hours, eats processed food, never exercises, and has high stress doesn't need a diagnosis — they need a lifestyle prescription. The history IS the diagnosis in naturopathy.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Vitality Assessment — The Naturopathic Lens",c:`
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ca)"></span><div><strong>Vital force (Vis Medicatrix Naturae)</strong> — Assess overall energy, resilience, and healing capacity. High vitality = brisk healing response. Low vitality = slow, poor response, tendency to chronicity.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ca)"></span><div><strong>Tongue assessment</strong> — Coated (white = toxin accumulation, digestive sluggishness), pale (anaemia, cold constitution), red/dry (heat, dehydration), geographic (stress, nutritional deficiency)</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ca)"></span><div><strong>Iris (iridology — supplementary)</strong> — Zone assessment. Note as supplementary finding, not primary diagnosis. Always correlate with clinical findings.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ca)"></span><div><strong>Pulse quality</strong> — Rate, rhythm, strength, volume. In naturopathy, also note: tense/relaxed, superficial/deep, fast/slow — reflects nervous system state.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ca)"></span><div><strong>Skin quality</strong> — Lustre, moisture, turgor, temperature, colour. Skin is a mirror of internal health. Dry skin = dehydration/poor fat intake. Sallow = liver sluggishness.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ca)"></span><div><strong>Elimination efficiency</strong> — Bowel (ideal: once daily, Bristol type 3–4), urine (pale yellow = well hydrated), sweating (natural detox). Poor elimination = toxin accumulation = disease tendency.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Clinical Pearl</div><div class="pt">In naturopathy, symptoms are not the enemy — they are the body's healing attempts. Fever, acute inflammation, mucus discharge, diarrhoea = body trying to eliminate. Support the process, don't suppress it (unless the patient is in danger). This is the fundamental philosophical difference from allopathy.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Naturopathic Clinical Examination",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>System</th><th>What to assess</th><th>Naturopathic significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Anthropometry</td><td>Height, weight, BMI, waist circumference, waist-hip ratio</td><td>Obesity: WHR &gt;0.9(M)/&gt;0.8(F) = central obesity → metabolic risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vital signs</td><td>BP, HR, RR, temperature, SpO₂</td><td>Baseline for monitoring treatment response. Hypertension management target.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Skin & hair</td><td>Texture, moisture, colour, lesions, nail quality, hair lustre</td><td>Reflects nutritional status, toxin load, hormonal balance</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Abdomen</td><td>Distension, tenderness, bowel sounds, organomegaly, constipation assessment</td><td>Gut health is central to naturopathy — most disease begins in poor digestion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spine & posture</td><td>Spinal curves (kyphosis/lordosis/scoliosis), posture, joint mobility, muscle tone</td><td>Spinal health affects nerve flow to all organs in naturopathic theory</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Respiratory</td><td>Breathing pattern, chest expansion, diaphragmatic vs thoracic breathing</td><td>Most people breathe shallowly — pranayama targets this directly</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mental state</td><td>Eye contact, affect, speech, mood, cognitive clarity, emotional state</td><td>Mind-body unity — mental state is ALWAYS part of the naturopathic assessment</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Clinical Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always assess the patient's READINESS for change. A patient who isn't ready to modify their diet will not benefit from a perfect naturopathic prescription. The Stages of Change model (precontemplation → contemplation → preparation → action → maintenance) guides how you frame your advice.</div></div>`},

  {t:"BNYS Treatment Planning Framework",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn style='display:none'"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Remove obstacles to cure</span> — Identify and eliminate factors obstructing healing: poor diet, sedentary behaviour, stress, toxic exposures, bad sleep</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Support natural healing</span> — Use the least invasive intervention first: diet → lifestyle → exercise → yoga → hydrotherapy → massage → acupressure → other modalities</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Treat the whole person</span> — Address physical, mental, emotional, social, and spiritual dimensions simultaneously</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Identify and treat root cause</span> — Not just symptoms. Ask: WHY has this person developed this condition at this time?</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Prevention and education</span> — Every consultation is a teaching opportunity. Empower patients to maintain health independently.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--ca)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Doctor as teacher (Docere)</span> — Educate patient about health principles. The best outcome is a patient who no longer needs you.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">BNYS treatment prescription components</div>
      Diet plan (individualised) · Fasting schedule · Daily yoga protocol · Pranayama routine · Hydrotherapy prescriptions · Massage schedule · Acupressure points to self-apply · Sleep hygiene · Sunlight prescription · Stress management · Exercise protocol · Follow-up interval
    </div>`}
],

yk:[
  {t:"Yoga Asanas — Therapeutic Indications",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Key principle</div>Asanas are prescribed based on pathology, not aesthetics. Always modify for the patient's current capacity. Teach correctly before prescribing for home practice.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Asana</th><th>Type</th><th>Therapeutic indications</th><th>Contraindications</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Tadasana (Mountain pose)</td><td>Standing</td><td>Posture correction, flat feet, poor body awareness, anxiety (grounding)</td><td>Severe dizziness, acute vertigo</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trikonasana</td><td>Standing</td><td>Back pain (chronic), scoliosis, hip stiffness, stress, leg strengthening</td><td>Neck injury (don't look up), recent hip replacement</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Virabhadrasana I, II, III</td><td>Standing</td><td>Knee/hip strengthening, balance, low back pain, circulation</td><td>Acute knee injury, severe hypertension (I, III)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Paschimottanasana</td><td>Forward bend</td><td>Constipation ★, diabetes (abdominal organs), anxiety, hamstring tightness, mild depression</td><td>Acute disc herniation, sciatica (aggravates), osteoporosis of spine</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bhujangasana</td><td>Backbend</td><td>Back pain (muscle), kyphosis correction, asthma (chest opening), mild depression, constipation</td><td>Acute lumbar disc prolapse, pregnancy, abdominal hernia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Shalabhasana</td><td>Backbend</td><td>Lumbar muscle strengthening, sciatica (mild), constipation</td><td>Acute disc disease, hernia, cardiac conditions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dhanurasana</td><td>Backbend</td><td>Constipation ★, abdominal organ toning, back stiffness, menstrual disorders, obesity</td><td>Peptic ulcer, hypertension, pregnancy, hernia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Halasana</td><td>Inversion</td><td>Constipation, thyroid stimulation, back pain, headache</td><td>Cervical spondylosis ★, hypertension, glaucoma, menstruation, pregnancy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sarvangasana</td><td>Inversion</td><td>Thyroid disorders, varicose veins, constipation, insomnia, mild hypertension (initially)</td><td>Cervical spondylosis, glaucoma, hypertension (established), menstruation, pregnancy, disc disease</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Shirshasana</td><td>Inversion</td><td>Cognitive enhancement, varicose veins, insomnia (advanced practitioners only)</td><td>Hypertension, glaucoma, cervical issues, cardiac disorders, vertigo. NOT for beginners.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Matsyasana</td><td>Backbend</td><td>Thyroid stimulation, asthma (chest expansion), cervical stiffness, depression</td><td>Peptic ulcer, acute cervical spondylosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ardha Matsyendrasana</td><td>Twist</td><td>Diabetes ★ (pancreatic stimulation), constipation, back pain, liver/spleen toning</td><td>Pregnancy, abdominal surgery (recent), severe spine disorders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mayurasana</td><td>Balance</td><td>Digestive disorders, diabetes, constipation — powerful abdominal blood redistribution</td><td>Pregnancy, wrist injury, hernia, abdominal inflammation, cardiac disorders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Shavasana</td><td>Relaxation</td><td>Stress ★, hypertension ★, anxiety, insomnia, post-session integration. ALWAYS end with 10 min Shavasana.</td><td>None (always indicated)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Surya Namaskar (12 steps)</td><td>Sequence</td><td>Obesity ★, diabetes, cardiovascular health, full-body conditioning, metabolic disorders</td><td>Acute fever, inflammatory conditions (active), pregnancy (modified), severe hypertension</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Inversions (Sarvangasana, Halasana, Shirshasana) are absolutely contraindicated in cervical spondylosis — can cause spinal cord compression. This is one of the most common missed contraindications in yoga prescriptions. Always screen neck mobility before prescribing inversions.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Yoga for Specific Conditions — Protocols",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Recommended asanas</th><th>Avoid</th><th>Duration</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Diabetes Type 2</td><td>Surya Namaskar, Ardha Matsyendrasana, Dhanurasana, Paschimottanasana, Mayurasana, Sarvangasana, Pranayama (Kapalbhati, Anulom Vilom)</td><td>Strenuous poses if blood sugar uncontrolled (&gt;300 mg/dL)</td><td>45–60 min/day, 5–6 days/week</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypertension</td><td>Shavasana ★, Surya Namaskar (slow), Bhramari, Anulom Vilom, Paschimottanasana, Yoga Nidra</td><td>Inversions (Shirshasana, Sarvangasana), Kapalbhati (forceful), Bhastrika, Kumbhaka (breath holding)</td><td>30–45 min/day, no breath holding</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Obesity</td><td>Surya Namaskar (fast, 6–12 rounds), Trikonasana, Virabhadrasana, Dhanurasana, Naukasana, Pavanmuktasana series</td><td>None specifically, but monitor capacity</td><td>60 min/day with aerobic component</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Asthma/COPD</td><td>Bhujangasana, Matsyasana, Gomukhasana, Ardha Chandrasana, Pranayama (Anulom Vilom, Bhramari), Yoga Nidra. Gradual pranayama build-up.</td><td>Kapalbhati forceful exhalation (initially), Kumbhaka, cold exposure</td><td>30 min asana + 20 min pranayama</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Low back pain</td><td>Bhujangasana, Shalabhasana, Marjariasana (cat-cow), Balasana, Supta Pawanmuktasana, Trikonasana</td><td>Paschimottanasana (acute disc), Halasana, Sarvangasana (acute phase)</td><td>20–30 min focused protocol</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Constipation</td><td>Pavanmuktasana series ★, Ardha Matsyendrasana, Dhanurasana, Halasana, Baddha Konasana, Malasana (garland pose)</td><td>None specifically</td><td>30 min morning, with warm water before practice</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Anxiety/Stress</td><td>Yoga Nidra ★★, Shavasana, Balasana, Viparita Karani (legs-up-wall), Bhramari, Nadi Shodhana</td><td>Kapalbhati, Bhastrika (stimulating pranayamas)</td><td>45 min/day with emphasis on relaxation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Thyroid disorders</td><td>Sarvangasana ★ (hypothyroid), Matsyasana, Halasana, Uttanpadasana, Ujjayi pranayama</td><td>Inversions in uncontrolled hyperthyroid, cervical issues</td><td>30–40 min, include counter-poses</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Yoga Nidra — Systematic Relaxation",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="display:none"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--yk)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Setup (5 min)</span> — Shavasana position, warm blanket, eye pillow. Set Sankalpa (short positive intention, repeated 3 times at start and end). Room slightly darkened, no distractions.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--yk)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Physical relaxation (10 min)</span> — Systematic rotation of consciousness through body parts (61-point relaxation). Instructor speaks slowly, 3–5 seconds per body part.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--yk)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Breath awareness (5 min)</span> — Count breaths backwards from 54 to 1. If mind wanders, restart from 54.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--yk)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Opposites (5 min)</span> — Experience pairs: heavy/light, warm/cold, pain/pleasure, joy/sadness. Rapidly alternating to develop equanimity.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--yk)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Visualisation (10 min)</span> — Rapid image sequences. Then a stable, pleasant scene (personalised). Activates REM-like brainwave states.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--yk)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Conclusion (5 min)</span> — Repeat Sankalpa. Slowly bring awareness back. Roll to right side. Sit up slowly.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Evidence base</div>Yoga Nidra has the strongest evidence of any relaxation technique: reduces cortisol, improves HbA1c in T2DM (Amita et al 2009), reduces anxiety scores (HAMA scale), improves sleep quality. 1 hour of Yoga Nidra = equivalent deep rest to 4 hours of sleep (EEG studies show theta/delta wave induction).</div>`}
],

ms:[
  {t:"Massage Techniques — BNYS Fundamentals",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Technique</th><th>Description</th><th>Effect</th><th>Indications</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Effleurage</td><td>Long, gliding strokes with palmar surface, toward heart. Light to moderate pressure. Used to begin and end session.</td><td>Increases venous/lymphatic return, warms tissue, relaxation, reduces oedema</td><td>Oedema ★, anxiety, fatigue, post-exercise recovery, introduction to session</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Petrissage</td><td>Kneading, wringing, rolling of muscles between hands. Lifts and compresses tissue.</td><td>Breaks adhesions, improves circulation, reduces muscle tension, removes metabolic waste</td><td>Muscle tightness ★, chronic pain, fibromyalgia, trigger points</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tapotement (percussion)</td><td>Rhythmic hacking, cupping, clapping, tapping. Brisk, stimulating movements.</td><td>Stimulates nerve endings, increases circulation, loosens mucus (chest), muscle tone</td><td>Chest physiotherapy ★ (bronchiectasis, COPD), sports warm-up, muscle atrophy, low energy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Friction</td><td>Deep circular or transverse movements on specific areas. Thumb/fingertip pressure.</td><td>Breaks down adhesions, scar tissue, chronic muscle knots (trigger points)</td><td>Frozen shoulder ★, tendinopathy, chronic muscle strain, myofascial pain</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vibration</td><td>Fine trembling movements transmitted through hands to patient's tissue.</td><td>Relaxes spasm, stimulates nerve endings, loosens secretions</td><td>Nervous system conditions, chest (secretion loosening), muscle spasm</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stroking (light)</td><td>Very light superficial touch, slow speed. Over-clothing or on skin.</td><td>Calms nervous system, reduces pain perception, sedative effect</td><td>Anxiety ★, hyperalgesia, chronic pain, nervous exhaustion</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always start with effleurage (warms tissue, builds trust, assesses tone) and end with effleurage (closes the session, promotes venous return). The session arc: effleurage → petrissage → friction (specific areas) → tapotement (if indicated) → effleurage to close. Total duration: 45–60 minutes for full body.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Oil Selection for Massage",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Oil</th><th>Properties</th><th>Best for</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Sesame oil</td><td>Warming, penetrating, heavy. High in vitamin E and antioxidants.</td><td>Vata conditions, dry skin, cold constitution, joint pain, low back pain, elderly</td><td>Oily skin, pitta conditions (heat)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Coconut oil</td><td>Cooling, light, antimicrobial. Solid below 24°C.</td><td>Pitta conditions, hair massage, scalp, hot climate, skin inflammation, fever massage</td><td>Cold/damp constitution (Kapha), fungal conditions (paradoxically — use sparingly)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mustard oil</td><td>Strongly warming, penetrating. Pungent smell.</td><td>Chronic arthritis ★, rheumatic pain, cold/damp conditions, muscle stiffness</td><td>Skin sensitivity, inflammatory arthritis (acute), open wounds</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Castor oil</td><td>Very viscous, strongly penetrating. Ricinoleic acid content.</td><td>Constipation (abdominal massage), fibrocystic conditions, chronic inflammation, lymphatic drainage</td><td>Pregnancy (can stimulate contractions)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Neem oil</td><td>Bitter, cooling, strongly antimicrobial/antifungal.</td><td>Skin conditions (psoriasis, eczema, scabies), dandruff, fungal infections</td><td>Undiluted on sensitive skin, pregnancy</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Olive oil</td><td>Medium viscosity, neutral. Rich in oleic acid, antioxidants.</td><td>General massage, dry skin, children's massage</td><td>Oily skin</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always warm the oil before application (test on inner wrist — comfortable warmth). Cold oil on skin causes vasoconstriction and reduces penetration. A small bowl in warm water for 5 minutes is sufficient. Never microwave oils as it destroys therapeutic compounds.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Contraindications to Massage",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">⚠️ ABSOLUTE contraindications — do NOT massage</div></div>
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Deep vein thrombosis (DVT)</strong> — Risk of dislodging clot → pulmonary embolism. Any unilateral leg swelling, calf pain, redness = DVT until proven otherwise. DO NOT MASSAGE.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Active infection / fever</strong> — Massage increases circulation and can spread local infection systemically. Viral fever: absolute rest, not massage.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Acute inflammation</strong> — Active arthritis flare, acute injury (RICE protocol instead), acute appendicitis, active phlebitis</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Malignancy (over tumour site)</strong> — Risk of promoting metastasis via lymphatic stimulation. Generalised massage with caution only in palliative care after oncology consultation.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Open wounds, burns, skin conditions</strong> — Eczema (acute weeping), infected wounds, third-degree burns, contagious skin conditions</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Recent fractures or surgery</strong> — Until cleared by treating physician</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Severe cardiac conditions</strong> — Acute MI, severe heart failure, acute arrhythmia</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Bleeding disorders / anticoagulants</strong> — Deep petrissage/friction can cause bruising and haematoma</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Relative contraindications — proceed with caution and modified technique</div>Pregnancy (avoid abdomen, avoid deep pressure, avoid certain positions) · Osteoporosis (avoid heavy tapotement) · Varicose veins (light effleurage only, avoid direct pressure) · Uncontrolled hypertension · Medications: anticoagulants (bruising risk)</div>`}
],

ac:[
  {t:"Acupressure — Key Points & Applications",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Point</th><th>Location</th><th>Therapeutic use</th><th>Technique</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>LI4 (Hegu)</td><td>Dorsum of hand, between 1st and 2nd metacarpals (highest point of web when adducted)</td><td>Headache ★, toothache, facial pain, common cold, constipation, labour pain</td><td>Firm thumb pressure, 1–3 min each side. <strong>Avoid in pregnancy</strong> (can induce labour)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ST36 (Zusanli)</td><td>4 finger-widths below patella, 1 finger-width lateral to tibial crest</td><td>Digestive disorders ★, fatigue, immunity, nausea, leg pain, diabetes management</td><td>1–3 min sustained pressure or circular friction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PC6 (Neiguan)</td><td>3 finger-widths above wrist crease, between the two tendons</td><td>Nausea ★ (morning sickness, motion sickness, post-anaesthesia), anxiety, palpitations, chest pain</td><td>Firm pressure, elastic wristband (Sea-Band) works here. 2–3 min.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SP6 (Sanyinjiao)</td><td>3 finger-widths above medial malleolus, posterior border of tibia</td><td>Menstrual disorders ★, insomnia, digestive issues, urinary problems, gynaecological conditions</td><td>1–3 min. <strong>Absolutely avoid in pregnancy</strong> (strong uterine stimulant)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GB20 (Fengchi)</td><td>Base of skull, in hollow between the SCM and trapezius tendons</td><td>Headache ★, neck pain, migraine, eye strain, cold/flu, dizziness, hypertension</td><td>Bilateral simultaneous pressure with thumbs, head tilted back slightly. 1–2 min.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>BL40 (Weizhong)</td><td>Centre of popliteal crease (back of knee)</td><td>Low back pain ★, sciatica, knee pain, hip pain</td><td>Moderate pressure with thumb, leg relaxed. 1–2 min each side.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>KD1 (Yongquan)</td><td>First third of sole of foot, in hollow made when toes flex</td><td>Insomnia ★, anxiety, hypertension, fainting, hot flushes, grounding</td><td>Firm circular massage, 2–3 min. Can self-apply before bed.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GV20 (Baihui)</td><td>Crown of head, at intersection of line from ears and line from nose to occiput</td><td>Headache, mental clarity, memory, depression, dizziness, prolapse conditions</td><td>Light circular pressure or tapping. 1 min.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HT7 (Shenmen)</td><td>Wrist crease, on ulnar side, radial to pisiform bone</td><td>Anxiety ★, insomnia, palpitations, emotional distress, heart conditions</td><td>Gentle circular pressure, 1–2 min. Self-applicable.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>LV3 (Taichong)</td><td>Dorsum of foot, between 1st and 2nd metatarsals, 1.5 cun proximal to web margin</td><td>Stress ★, headache, menstrual cramps, hypertension, liver disorders, eye problems</td><td>Firm pressure, can be sensitive. 1–2 min.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Acupressure works on the same meridian system as acupuncture but uses sustained manual pressure instead of needles. Most important points for a BNYS physician to know: LI4 (pain/head), ST36 (digestion/energy), PC6 (nausea), GB20 (headache/BP), KD1 (insomnia). Teach patients to self-apply for daily use.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Reflexology — Foot Zones",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Principle</div>The feet contain reflex zones that correspond to all organs and body systems. Precise thumb-walking technique on specific zones stimulates corresponding organs through nerve pathways and energy meridians.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Foot zone / area</th><th>Corresponding organ</th><th>Therapeutic application</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Toes (all)</td><td>Head, brain, sinuses</td><td>Headache, sinusitis, dental pain, cognitive issues</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Big toe</td><td>Brain, pituitary, pineal</td><td>Hormonal regulation, insomnia, endocrine disorders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ball of foot (left)</td><td>Heart, lungs</td><td>Cardiovascular and respiratory conditions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ball of foot (right)</td><td>Liver, gallbladder</td><td>Liver disorders, cholesterol, digestive issues</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Arch (medial)</td><td>Spine</td><td>Back pain, spinal problems, posture issues</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Arch (central)</td><td>Stomach, pancreas, small intestine</td><td>Digestive disorders, diabetes, IBS</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Heel</td><td>Pelvic organs, sciatic nerve, large intestine</td><td>Constipation, sciatica, reproductive disorders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Inner ankle</td><td>Uterus/prostate, bladder</td><td>Urinary conditions, reproductive health, prostate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Outer ankle</td><td>Ovaries/testes, lymphatics</td><td>Hormonal issues, oedema, immune conditions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dorsum of foot</td><td>Lymphatic drainage zones, breast/chest</td><td>Lymphoedema, immune support, respiratory</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Reflexology sessions: 30–45 minutes. Begin with relaxation movements (foot rotation, effleurage), then systematic thumb-walking through all zones, ending with relaxation. A tender reflex zone indicates possible dysfunction in corresponding organ — correlate with clinical findings. Not diagnostic, but guides further assessment.</div></div>`}
],

pr:[
  {t:"Pranayama — Full Guide with Therapeutic Ratios",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Pranayama</th><th>Technique</th><th>Ratio (I:H:E:H)</th><th>Therapeutic indications</th><th>Contraindications</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Nadi Shodhana (Anulom Vilom)</td><td>Alternate nostril breathing: close right nostril with thumb, inhale left; close left with ring finger, exhale right; inhale right; close right, exhale left = 1 cycle</td><td>1:4:2 (advanced) or 1:1:2 (beginners). 10–20 min.</td><td>Anxiety ★, hypertension ★, stress, asthma, balancing autonomic NS, pre-meditation, insomnia</td><td>Acute respiratory infection, nasal blockage (use gentle ratio)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kapalbhati</td><td>Forced exhalation with passive inhalation. Rapid pumping of abdomen. 60–120 strokes/min.</td><td>No ratio. 3–5 rounds of 30–60 strokes with rest.</td><td>Obesity ★, constipation ★, diabetes, sluggish metabolism, mucus clearing, mental clarity</td><td>Hypertension ★, cardiac disorders, pregnancy, menstruation, hernia, acute abdominal conditions, epilepsy. DO NOT FORCE in beginners.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bhastrika</td><td>Forceful inhalation AND exhalation (bellows breath). More intense than Kapalbhati.</td><td>No ratio. Start 10 strokes, increase slowly.</td><td>Low energy, cold constitution, weight loss, lung capacity, clearing mucus</td><td>Hypertension ★★ (contraindicated), cardiac disease, pregnancy, epilepsy, nasal bleeding, anxiety disorders</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bhramari (Humming bee)</td><td>Inhale through nose, exhale with humming sound (lips closed). Fingers may cover ears (Shanmukhi mudra).</td><td>I:E = 1:2. 5–10 rounds.</td><td>Anxiety ★★, hypertension ★, insomnia, stuttering, sinus, thyroid, pregnancy preparation, anger management</td><td>Ear infection. Safe in most conditions.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ujjayi (Victorious/Ocean breath)</td><td>Partial constriction of glottis during breathing — produces ocean/snoring sound. Through nose only.</td><td>1:1 to 1:2 (I:E). 5–15 min.</td><td>Thyroid disorders ★, hypertension, anxiety, during yoga asana practice, sleep disorders</td><td>Low blood pressure (can further lower BP), hyperthyroid (initially)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sheetali</td><td>Curl tongue lengthwise, inhale through curled tongue (cool air), close mouth, exhale through nose. (Sheetkari if can't curl tongue: inhale through clenched teeth)</td><td>I:E = 1:2. 5–10 rounds.</td><td>Hypertension ★, excess body heat, fever (moderate), hyperacidity, hot flushes, anger, pitta conditions</td><td>Asthma, respiratory disorders, very cold climate, low BP, excess mucus production</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Surya Bhedana</td><td>Inhale through RIGHT nostril only, close right, exhale through LEFT nostril only. Opposite of Nadi Shodhana.</td><td>1:1:2. 10–15 rounds.</td><td>Low energy, cold/damp constitution (Kapha excess), depression, low metabolism, hypothyroidism</td><td>Hypertension ★, pitta conditions, fever, right-sided migraine</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chandra Bhedana</td><td>Inhale through LEFT nostril only, exhale through RIGHT. Activates parasympathetic/cooling.</td><td>1:1:2. 10–15 rounds.</td><td>Hypertension, excess heat, anxiety, insomnia, evening practice</td><td>Low BP, depression, hypothyroidism, cold constitution</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Never teach Kumbhaka (breath retention) to beginners, hypertensives, or cardiac patients. The ratio 1:4:2 (inhale:hold:exhale) is only for advanced healthy practitioners. For clinical therapeutic use, always start with 1:1:2 or even just deep diaphragmatic breathing. The foundation of all pranayama is diaphragmatic breathing — teach this first.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Diaphragmatic Breathing — Foundation Technique",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Why this matters</div>90% of patients breathe thoracically (chest only), using only 1/3 of lung capacity. Diaphragmatic breathing activates the vagus nerve → parasympathetic response → reduces cortisol, HR, and BP. It is the single most powerful naturopathic intervention that takes &lt;2 minutes to teach.</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn style='display:none'"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--pr)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Position</span> — Supine or seated. One hand on chest, one on abdomen (navel level).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--pr)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Teach the movement</span> — "Breathe in so that ONLY the hand on the abdomen rises. The chest hand should barely move."</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--pr)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Ratio</span> — Inhale 4 counts, exhale 6–8 counts. Extended exhale activates parasympathetic system most effectively.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--pr)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Practice</span> — 5–10 minutes morning + evening. Can be done in any position, any time (before meals, before sleep, during stress).</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Immediate effect</div><div class="nv-val">HR ↓ 5–10 bpm within 3 min</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">BP effect</div><div class="nv-val">SBP ↓ 5–10 mmHg acute</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Cortisol</div><div class="nv-val">↓ after 10 min practice</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">HRV improvement</div><div class="nv-val">Measurable after 4 weeks</div></div>
    </div>`}
],

dt:[
  {t:"Naturopathic Dietary Principles",c:`
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--dt)"></span><div><strong>Whole foods, predominantly plant-based</strong> — Fruits, vegetables, legumes, nuts, seeds, whole grains as the foundation. Raw-to-cooked ratio ideally 40:60 (raw foods retain enzymes, vitamins, phytonutrients).</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--dt)"></span><div><strong>Elimination diet approach</strong> — Remove common irritants first: refined sugar, processed foods, trans fats, excessive dairy, alcohol, excess caffeine. Assess response before adding back.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--dt)"></span><div><strong>Food combining principles</strong> — Proteins + starches = poor digestion (avoid eating meat + rice together). Fruits eaten alone or 30 min before meals. Avoid cold water/drinks with meals (impairs digestive enzymes).</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--dt)"></span><div><strong>Meal timing</strong> — Breakfast = moderate, Lunch = largest meal (digestive fire peak), Dinner = light, early (by 7 pm ideally). No eating within 3 hours of sleep.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--dt)"></span><div><strong>Water therapy</strong> — 6–8 glasses/day. 2 glasses warm water first thing morning (stimulates peristalsis, flushes kidneys). Water 30 min before or 90 min after meals (not during — dilutes digestive enzymes).</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--dt)"></span><div><strong>Mindful eating</strong> — Eat slowly (20 min per meal). Chew each bite 20–30 times. No screens/phone during meals. Gratitude before eating. Eat only when genuinely hungry.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The most powerful single dietary change for most patients: replace white rice/bread/sugar with whole grains and increase vegetables to 50% of every plate. For Indian patients: reduce oil quantity (from 5 tbsp/day to 2), eliminate packaged snacks, and shift to brown rice or millets. These three changes alone address &gt;70% of common metabolic disorders.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Therapeutic Diets — Condition-Specific",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Diet type</th><th>Key components</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Type 2 Diabetes</td><td>Low GI diet + high fibre</td><td>Bitter gourd ★ (karela), fenugreek seeds (methi), cinnamon water, whole grains, legumes, green vegetables, fibre 25–35g/day</td><td>White rice, refined flour (maida), sugar, fruit juices, processed carbohydrates, alcohol</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypertension</td><td>DASH diet (Naturopathic)</td><td>Fruits (especially citrus, banana, amla), vegetables, low-fat dairy, nuts, seeds. Reduce sodium to &lt;2g/day. Garlic ★ (1 raw clove/day)</td><td>Salt (table + hidden in pickles, papads, processed food), alcohol, caffeine excess, red meat</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Obesity</td><td>Sattvic + calorie-modified</td><td>High volume low calorie foods, salads before meals, warm lemon water morning, millets, high fibre, protein at every meal, no refined carbs</td><td>Deep fried foods, sweets, aerated drinks ★, packaged foods, excess oil, late-night eating</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Constipation</td><td>High fibre + hydration</td><td>2L water/day ★, prunes/figs (2 soaked at night), psyllium husk (isabgol), warm water morning, papaya, fruits with skin, leafy greens</td><td>Dairy excess, refined carbohydrates, insufficient water, sedentary lifestyle, iron supplements (cause constipation)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acidity/GERD</td><td>Alkaline diet</td><td>Coconut water, banana, cucumber, aloe vera juice, cold milk (buffer), small frequent meals, alkaline foods (most fruits/vegetables)</td><td>Tea/coffee on empty stomach ★, spicy food, citrus (acute), tomatoes, chocolate, lying down after meals, large meals</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Arthritis</td><td>Anti-inflammatory diet</td><td>Turmeric (curcumin) ★, ginger, omega-3 rich foods (flaxseeds, walnuts), green vegetables, cherries (anti-inflammatory), alkaline diet</td><td>Red meat, processed foods, refined sugar, alcohol, fried foods, nightshade vegetables (tomato, brinjal, capsicum — avoid in RA)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Liver disease / fatty liver</td><td>Liver-supportive diet</td><td>Beetroot juice, carrot juice, papaya, garlic, green tea, bitter foods (karela, methi), high fibre</td><td>Alcohol ★★★, processed foods, excess sugar (especially fructose), red meat, saturated fats, excess salt</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Therapeutic Foods & Their Actions",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Food</th><th>Active component</th><th>Evidence-based action</th><th>How to use</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Bitter gourd (Karela)</td><td>Charantin, polypeptide-p, vicine</td><td>Reduces blood glucose (insulin-mimetic), improves insulin sensitivity. RCTs show 5–10% FBG reduction.</td><td>200mL juice morning empty stomach, or 2 karela/day cooked, or capsules</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fenugreek (Methi)</td><td>4-hydroxyisoleucine, galactomannan fibre</td><td>Slows glucose absorption, reduces FBG and HbA1c. Reduces LDL cholesterol.</td><td>1 tsp seeds soaked overnight, drink water + eat seeds in morning. OR 2 tsp powder in food.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Turmeric (Haldi)</td><td>Curcumin</td><td>Anti-inflammatory (inhibits COX-2), antioxidant, improves insulin sensitivity, liver protective. 500–1000mg curcumin/day = anti-inflammatory equivalent of low-dose ibuprofen in some studies.</td><td>Golden milk (turmeric + black pepper + warm milk), 1 tsp in cooking. Black pepper increases bioavailability by 2000%.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Garlic (Lahsun)</td><td>Allicin</td><td>Reduces SBP 8–10mmHg (meta-analysis), lowers LDL, antimicrobial, anti-thrombotic</td><td>1–2 raw cloves morning on empty stomach (crush, wait 10 min, then eat). Heat destroys allicin.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Amla (Indian gooseberry)</td><td>Vitamin C, tannins, gallic acid</td><td>Highest natural Vit C content. Antidiabetic, liver protective, immune stimulant, anti-ageing</td><td>1 fresh amla/day or 1 tsp amla powder in water</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Flaxseeds (Alsi)</td><td>Alpha-linolenic acid (ALA), lignans, fibre</td><td>Reduces LDL, lowers BP, reduces menopausal symptoms, improves bowel regularity</td><td>1–2 tbsp ground (not whole — passes through undigested) daily. Add to food or take with water.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wheatgrass juice</td><td>Chlorophyll, vitamins, enzymes</td><td>Alkalises body, improves haemoglobin in anaemia, antioxidant, detoxifying</td><td>30–60mL fresh juice on empty stomach, morning. Avoid metal containers.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Neem leaves</td><td>Nimbin, nimbidin, quercetin</td><td>Antidiabetic, antimicrobial, blood purifying, liver protective</td><td>5–10 leaves chewed on empty stomach morning, OR neem leaf juice 30mL</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`}
],

fa:[
  {t:"Types of Therapeutic Fasting",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Description</th><th>Duration</th><th>Best for</th><th>Supervision required</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Water fasting</td><td>Only plain water (2–3L/day). Complete rest from all food.</td><td>1–3 days (short), 7–21 days (extended — supervised inpatient)</td><td>Acute conditions, toxin elimination, weight loss, metabolic reset</td><td>Mandatory beyond 3 days</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Juice fasting</td><td>Fresh fruit/vegetable juices (500mL–2L/day) + water. No solid food.</td><td>3–14 days</td><td>Chronic conditions, first fast for beginners, liver detox, hypertension</td><td>Required beyond 7 days</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fruit fasting</td><td>Whole fresh seasonal fruits only + water. No cooked food.</td><td>3–7 days</td><td>Digestive rest, constipation, skin conditions, mild detox</td><td>Recommended</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mono diet fast</td><td>Single food only — usually fruit (grape, watermelon, apple) or khichdi. Simplifies digestion.</td><td>3–10 days</td><td>Digestive disorders, IBS, weight loss, initial chronic disease management</td><td>Recommended</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intermittent fasting (16:8)</td><td>16 hours fasting window, 8 hours eating window. Daily practice.</td><td>Ongoing lifestyle</td><td>Obesity ★, T2DM, metabolic syndrome, insulin resistance, NAFLD</td><td>Not required (healthy adults)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intermittent fasting (5:2)</td><td>5 days normal eating, 2 non-consecutive days very low calorie (500 kcal).</td><td>Ongoing lifestyle</td><td>Weight loss, metabolic health, longevity</td><td>Not required (healthy adults)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ekadashi fasting</td><td>Traditional: twice monthly (lunar calendar). Usually fruit/water only.</td><td>24 hrs, twice monthly</td><td>Spiritual + physical — digestive rest, mental clarity</td><td>Not required</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The most powerful and evidence-based fasting approach for BNYS practice is 16:8 intermittent fasting — backed by strong modern research AND aligned with traditional naturopathic principles. It is sustainable, safe for most patients, requires no supervision, and produces measurable results in 4–8 weeks. Start here before prescribing longer fasts.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Fasting Monitoring Protocol",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">⚠️ Absolute contraindications to fasting</div>Type 1 diabetes (risk of DKA) · Pregnancy/lactation · Severe underweight (BMI &lt;17) · Active eating disorder · Recent major surgery · Active TB or severe infection · Severe cardiac failure · Children &lt;14 years · Patients on insulin (require medical supervision and dose adjustment)</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="display:none"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--fa)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Pre-fast assessment</span> — BP, HR, weight, blood glucose (capillary), urine ketones baseline. Review medications (especially insulin, antidiabetics, antihypertensives — all may need dose reduction during fasting).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--fa)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Daily monitoring during fast</span> — BP morning and evening (hypotension is the most common complication), capillary glucose (if diabetic — check BD), urine output (should be 1.5–2L/day), ketone level (urine strips), weight (daily), sleep, mental state</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--fa)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Expected fasting symptoms (normal)</span> — Headache (day 1–2: glucose withdrawal), hunger (peaks day 2, reduces day 3), mild weakness, light-headedness on standing (orthostatic hypotension — managed with adequate water), slight bad breath (ketosis)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--fa)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Stop fasting immediately if:</span> BP &lt;90/60, blood glucose &lt;3.5 mmol/L, persistent vomiting, fainting, severe cardiac symptoms, altered consciousness, signs of dehydration despite water intake</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Refeeding after fasting is as important as the fast itself. NEVER break a fast with a heavy meal. Rule: number of days fasted = number of days of gradual refeeding. Break with diluted fruit juice (50:50 water) → whole fruit → cooked vegetables → normal food. Refeeding syndrome (hypophosphataemia) risk exists after extended fasting.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Refeeding Protocol After Fasting",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Fast duration</th><th>Day 1 (break fast)</th><th>Day 2</th><th>Day 3</th><th>Day 4+</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>1–3 day fast</td><td>Diluted fruit juice → fresh fruits</td><td>Fruits + vegetable soup</td><td>Add cooked vegetables, khichdi</td><td>Normal naturopathic diet</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4–7 day fast</td><td>Small amounts diluted juice only (200mL every 2–3 hrs)</td><td>Fresh fruits, coconut water</td><td>Raw vegetables, light soup</td><td>Gradually add cooked vegetables, grains by day 5–7</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7–14 day fast</td><td>100–200mL diluted juice every 2–3 hrs</td><td>Diluted juices and coconut water</td><td>Full juices and fruits</td><td>Progressive solid foods over 7–10 days of refeeding</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Refeeding electrolyte monitoring</div>For fasts &gt;5 days: check serum phosphate, potassium, magnesium on day 1–2 of refeeding. Hypophosphataemia is the key risk. Symptoms: weakness, confusion, arrhythmia, respiratory failure. If developing — slow refeeding further, increase phosphate-rich foods (dairy, legumes), refer if severe.</div>`}
],

lf:[
  {t:"Type 2 Diabetes — Naturopathic Management",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Evidence base</div>Lifestyle intervention (diet + exercise + yoga) can reduce HbA1c by 1–2% — equivalent to metformin — in T2DM (DPPOS, DPP trials). Intensive lifestyle can achieve remission in early T2DM.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Modality</th><th>Prescription</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Diet</td><td>Low GI diet, 25–35g fibre/day, bitter gourd juice morning, fenugreek seeds, reduce refined carbs by 80%, no sugar-sweetened drinks</td><td>Strong — ADA supports lifestyle first</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Exercise</td><td>Brisk walking 150 min/week minimum + 2× resistance training. Post-meal walks (15 min after meals — reduces post-prandial glucose spike ★)</td><td>Strong — reduces insulin resistance</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yoga</td><td>Surya Namaskar (12 rounds/day), Ardha Matsyendrasana, Dhanurasana, Paschimottanasana, Mayurasana. Daily 45 min.</td><td>Moderate — reduces FBG, HbA1c</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pranayama</td><td>Kapalbhati 5 min + Anulom Vilom 10 min + Bhramari 5 min. Daily.</td><td>Moderate — reduces cortisol, improves insulin sensitivity</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stress management</td><td>Yoga Nidra 30 min daily. Cortisol ↑ → insulin resistance ↑. Stress management is metabolic therapy.</td><td>Moderate — reduces cortisol, improves glycaemic control</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intermittent fasting</td><td>16:8 fasting — skip breakfast or delay first meal to noon. Improves insulin sensitivity, reduces FBG.</td><td>Growing — reduces FBG 5–10 mmol/L in some studies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sleep</td><td>7–8 hrs/night. Poor sleep ↑ insulin resistance by 25% (Spiegel et al). Sleep deprivation = metabolic disease accelerator.</td><td>Strong — independent predictor</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">When to refer to allopathic physician</div>HbA1c &gt;9%, FBG &gt;250 mg/dL consistently, symptoms of hyperglycaemia (polydipsia, polyuria, weight loss), ketones in urine, T1DM, DKA symptoms, feet complications (neuropathy, ulcers), any patient on insulin (collaborative management needed)</div>`},

  {t:"Hypertension — Naturopathic Management",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Target BP (general)</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;130/80 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Target BP (&gt;65 yrs)</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;140/90 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Lifestyle can reduce SBP</div><div class="nv-val">10–20 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Before referring to drugs</div><div class="nv-val">3–6 month lifestyle trial</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Intervention</th><th>Expected SBP reduction</th><th>Prescription</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Salt restriction</td><td>↓ 5–10 mmHg</td><td>&lt;2g sodium/day. Avoid pickles, papads, processed food, adding salt at table. Check labels for hidden sodium.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Weight loss</td><td>↓ 1 mmHg per kg lost</td><td>Target 5–10% body weight reduction in 3–6 months through diet + exercise</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Exercise</td><td>↓ 5–8 mmHg</td><td>Moderate aerobic exercise 30–45 min, 5 days/week. Walking, swimming, cycling. Avoid heavy isometric exercise (weight lifting raises BP acutely).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>DASH diet</td><td>↓ 8–14 mmHg</td><td>Fruits, vegetables, low-fat dairy, reduced sodium, increased potassium (banana, coconut water, sweet potato)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yoga + pranayama</td><td>↓ 5–12 mmHg</td><td>Shavasana ★, Yoga Nidra, Anulom Vilom, Bhramari, slow deep breathing. AVOID Kapalbhati, Bhastrika, Shirshasana.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Garlic</td><td>↓ 8–10 mmHg</td><td>1–2 raw crushed cloves daily, empty stomach</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hibiscus tea</td><td>↓ 7 mmHg</td><td>2 cups/day of hibiscus (roselle) tea. ACE-inhibitory properties shown in trials.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Alcohol cessation</td><td>↓ 4–5 mmHg</td><td>Complete cessation if &gt;2 units/day</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">⚠️ When to refer immediately (hypertensive emergency)</div>BP ≥180/120 + headache, visual changes, chest pain, shortness of breath, or neurological symptoms = HYPERTENSIVE EMERGENCY → emergency referral. Naturopathy CANNOT manage this.</div>`},

  {t:"Obesity — Naturopathic Management",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Naturopathic approach to obesity</div>Obesity is not a willpower problem — it is a hormonal, metabolic, and behavioural disorder with strong environmental drivers. The naturopathic approach addresses ALL root causes simultaneously, not just calorie counting.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Prescription</th><th>Target</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Diet</td><td>Reduce daily calories by 500–750 kcal deficit. Increase protein (preserve muscle), high fibre (satiety), reduce refined carbs + sugar + liquid calories (biggest impact). No ultra-processed foods.</td><td>0.5–1 kg/week weight loss (safe rate)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Exercise</td><td>150–300 min/week aerobic + 2× resistance training. Start where the patient is — even 10 min walks count. Increase gradually. NEAT (Non-exercise activity thermogenesis) — standing, walking, stairs.</td><td>300+ min/week for weight loss maintenance</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Yoga</td><td>Surya Namaskar (10–12 rounds/day = 350–400 kcal), Kapalbhati (boosts metabolism), dynamic sequences</td><td>60 min/day, 6 days/week</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Meal timing</td><td>Largest meal = lunch. No eating after 7pm. 16:8 intermittent fasting. Eat slowly (brain takes 20 min to register fullness).</td><td>Reduce evening calorie intake by 40%</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sleep optimisation</td><td>7–8 hrs/night. Sleep deprivation → ghrelin ↑ (hunger hormone) + leptin ↓ (satiety hormone) → increased appetite by 300 kcal/day</td><td>Consistent sleep/wake time</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stress management</td><td>Cortisol drives central obesity specifically (belly fat). Yoga Nidra, meditation, CBT approaches</td><td>Stress score reduction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Water therapy</td><td">500mL water before each meal reduces calorie intake by 13% (RCT). 2L/day minimum. Replace all sweetened drinks with water.</td><td>2–2.5L/day</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Measure waist circumference, not just weight. Waist &gt;90cm (M) / &gt;80cm (F) in Indians = central obesity = high metabolic risk (Indian-specific cut-offs lower than international). A patient may be normal BMI but have metabolic obesity (TOFI — thin outside, fat inside). Visceral fat is the dangerous fat, not subcutaneous fat.</div></div>`}
],

nt:[
  {t:"Chronic Constipation Protocol",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="display:none"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Diet</span> — 2.5L water/day (most important) + fibre 25–35g/day (fruits, vegetables, whole grains, isabgol 1 tsp with warm water at night), soaked prunes (2–4 at bedtime), papaya (daily)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Morning routine</span> — Drink 2 glasses warm water immediately on waking → stimulates gastrocolic reflex → natural urge within 20–30 min. Never suppress the urge.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Yoga</span> — Pavanmuktasana series (10 rounds), Ardha Matsyendrasana, Dhanurasana, Malasana (squat pose — best physiological position for defecation)</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Abdominal massage</span> — Castor oil massage clockwise (in direction of colon), 5–10 min, morning. Stimulates peristalsis.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Hydrotherapy</span> — Cold hip bath 15–20 min daily, or cold compress on abdomen — stimulates intestinal activity</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Pranayama</span> — Kapalbhati 5–10 min daily (powerful abdominal pump — natural peristalsis stimulator)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The squatting position for defecation (Malasana) is physiologically superior to sitting on a Western toilet — it straightens the anorectal angle and reduces straining. Recommend a toilet stool (Squatty Potty) or teach Malasana. This alone resolves many cases of chronic constipation and straining.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Chronic Back Pain Protocol",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Modality</th><th>Prescription</th><th>Frequency</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Yoga (specific)</td><td>Bhujangasana, Shalabhasana, Marjariasana (cat-cow) ★, Balasana, Trikonasana, Supta Baddha Konasana</td><td>Daily, 30 min, morning</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Massage</td><td>Deep tissue (petrissage + friction) to paraspinal muscles + gluteals. Mustard/sesame oil. Avoid deep friction in acute phase.</td><td>3× week (chronic), rest (acute)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acupressure</td><td>BL40 (popliteal fossa), BL23 (paravertebral L2 level), GV4 (between L2–L3 spinous processes). Teach self-application.</td><td>Daily, 1–2 min each point</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hot compress</td><td>Moist heat to lumbar region (15–20 min). Relaxes muscle spasm. NOT in acute inflammatory phase (use cold first 48 hrs).</td><td>2× daily in chronic phase</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Posture correction</td><td>Ergonomic assessment. Lumbar support while sitting. No prolonged sitting &gt;45 min. Standing desk if possible.</td><td>Ongoing — lifestyle modification</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Diet</td><td>Anti-inflammatory diet, weight loss if overweight (each kg reduces spinal load by 4kg), adequate Vit D + Calcium</td><td>Ongoing</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Red flags — STOP naturopathic treatment and refer urgently</div>Bilateral leg weakness or numbness · Saddle anaesthesia (numbness around perineum) · Bladder/bowel incontinence or retention · Severe progressive neurological deficit → Cauda equina syndrome = SURGICAL EMERGENCY</div>`},

  {t:"Insomnia Protocol",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="display:none"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Sleep hygiene (most important)</span> — Fixed sleep/wake time (even weekends). Bedroom = only sleep + sex (no screens). Temperature 18–20°C. Dark room. No screen 1 hour before bed. No caffeine after 2pm.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Yoga Nidra</span> — 30 min before bed. Most effective single naturopathic intervention for insomnia. Can use recorded guided practice.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Pranayama</span> — 4-7-8 breathing (inhale 4, hold 7, exhale 8) OR Anulom Vilom 10 min before bed. Activates parasympathetic system.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Acupressure</span> — KD1 (sole of foot), HT7 (wrist), SP6 (above medial ankle) — 2 min each before sleep. Self-applicable.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Diet</span> — Warm milk (tryptophan) + 1/4 tsp nutmeg (natural sedative) at bedtime. Light dinner. Banana (magnesium + tryptophan). Avoid heavy meals within 3 hours of sleep.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--nt)">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Warm bath/foot soak</span> — 20 min warm bath 1–2 hours before bed. The subsequent drop in core body temperature triggers sleep onset.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">CBT-I (Cognitive Behavioural Therapy for Insomnia) has more evidence than any sleeping medication for chronic insomnia (AASM guidelines). BNYS physicians can implement the behavioural components (sleep restriction therapy, stimulus control, sleep hygiene) — this is within scope and highly effective.</div></div>`}
],

dr:[
  {t:"Yoga & Exercise Interactions with Medications",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">⚠️ Critical interactions — always check medications before prescribing yoga/exercise</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Drug/Drug class</th><th>Interaction with yoga/exercise</th><th>What to do</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Antihypertensives (all)</td><td>Exercise + yoga (especially inversions) can lower BP further → hypotension, dizziness, syncope</td><td>Monitor BP before and after sessions. Avoid Shirshasana, prolonged inversions. Check for orthostatic hypotension on standing.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Beta-blockers (propranolol, atenolol)</td><td>Blunt tachycardia response to exercise — HR won't rise normally. Can't use HR to guide exercise intensity.</td><td>Use RPE (Rating of Perceived Exertion) scale 1–10 instead of heart rate. Target RPE 5–7.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Insulin / Sulphonylureas (glibenclamide, glipizide)</td><td>Exercise lowers blood glucose — risk of hypoglycaemia during or after session</td><td>Check glucose before yoga. If &lt;5.5 mmol/L: small snack first. Carry glucose tablets/juice. Never practice on empty stomach if on insulin.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Diuretics (furosemide, hydrochlorothiazide)</td><td>Dehydration risk during exercise + hot yoga. Electrolyte imbalance (K+, Mg) causes cramps, arrhythmia.</td><td>Extra hydration before/during. Check electrolytes if on loop diuretics. Avoid hot yoga.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Anticoagulants (warfarin, DOACs)</td><td>Contact-type massage contraindicated (bruising, haematoma). Hot wax treatments increase absorption of topical drugs.</td><td>Use light effleurage only. No deep friction/petrissage. No cupping therapy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Corticosteroids (long-term)</td><td>Osteoporosis risk — avoid forceful spinal twists, extreme ranges of motion. Muscle weakness (steroid myopathy).</td><td>Gentle yoga only. No weight-bearing inversions. Screen BMD before intensive yoga.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ACE inhibitors + ARBs</td><td>Synergistic BP lowering with exercise. Risk of hypotension especially in hot conditions.</td><td>Monitor BP. Ensure adequate hydration. Avoid hot yoga or hot rooms.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Dietary Interventions & Drug Interactions",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Food/Supplement</th><th>Drug</th><th>Interaction</th><th>Clinical significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Karela (bitter gourd), Methi</td><td>Metformin, Insulin, Sulphonylureas</td><td>Additive blood glucose lowering → hypoglycaemia</td><td>HIGH ★★★. Monitor glucose closely. May need drug dose reduction. Inform treating physician.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Garlic (high dose)</td><td>Warfarin, aspirin, clopidogrel</td><td>Additive antiplatelet/anticoagulant effect → increased bleeding risk</td><td>MODERATE. 1 raw clove/day = low risk. High-dose garlic supplements = risk. Inform physician if on anticoagulants.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Flaxseeds (omega-3)</td><td>Warfarin, aspirin</td><td>Additive antiplatelet effect, slightly prolongs bleeding time</td><td>LOW-MODERATE. 1–2 tbsp/day generally safe.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Turmeric/curcumin (high dose)</td><td>Warfarin, antiplatelet drugs, diabetes drugs</td><td>Antiplatelet + anticoagulant effect at high doses. Blood glucose lowering.</td><td>MODERATE at supplement doses. Dietary turmeric in cooking = safe. Avoid curcumin supplements if on anticoagulants.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Amla (high dose)</td><td>Anticoagulants, antidiabetic drugs</td><td>Antiplatelet, blood glucose lowering effects</td><td>LOW at 1–2 fruit/day. Monitor if on anticoagulants.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Grapefruit juice</td><td>Statins (simvastatin, atorvastatin), calcium channel blockers, some immunosuppressants</td><td>Inhibits CYP3A4 → dramatically increases drug levels → toxicity risk</td><td>HIGH ★★★. Avoid grapefruit entirely if on statins or calcium channel blockers.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>High fibre diet</td><td>Digoxin, levothyroxine, metformin</td><td>Reduces drug absorption if taken simultaneously</td><td>MODERATE. Take these drugs at least 1 hour before high-fibre meals or 2–4 hours after.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fasting (extended)</td><td>Antihypertensives, antidiabetics, diuretics</td><td>Fasting lowers BP and glucose — drugs may cause hypotension/hypoglycaemia during fast</td><td>HIGH ★★★. Always review and potentially reduce doses during therapeutic fasting. Inform treating physician.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The most dangerous drug-food interaction in BNYS practice: prescribing karela juice + methi to a diabetic patient on insulin or sulphonylureas without reducing their drug dose first. This can cause severe hypoglycaemia. ALWAYS coordinate with the prescribing physician when introducing potent food-based glucose-lowering interventions.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Fasting & Drug Interactions",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Drug class</th><th>Risk during fasting</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Insulin (all types)</td><td>Severe hypoglycaemia</td><td>DO NOT fast without endocrinologist supervision and dose reduction plan. Absolutely contraindicated for independent self-directed fasting.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sulphonylureas (glibenclamide, gliclazide)</td><td>Hypoglycaemia (stimulate insulin release regardless of food)</td><td>Must reduce/hold dose during fasting. Coordinate with prescriber. Monitor glucose 2-hourly during fast.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Metformin</td><td>Nausea/GI upset on empty stomach. Lactic acidosis risk if dehydrated + CKD</td><td>Can usually continue with juice/fruit fasting. Stop during water-only fast. Ensure adequate hydration.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Antihypertensives</td><td>Hypotension during fasting (natural BP-lowering effect of fasting)</td><td>Monitor BP BD. May need dose reduction. Patient should be able to check BP independently.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>NSAIDs (ibuprofen, diclofenac)</td><td>GI bleeding/ulceration on empty stomach</td><td>Do NOT take NSAIDs during fasting. Manage pain with acupressure, heat, yoga instead.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Anticonvulsants (phenytoin, carbamazepine)</td><td>Fasting can alter seizure threshold and drug levels</td><td>Extended fasting contraindicated in epilepsy without neurologist supervision.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Thyroid medications (levothyroxine)</td><td>Absorption altered with food — should already be taken on empty stomach</td><td>Continue as prescribed. No interaction with fasting itself. Take 30–60 min before breaking fast.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`}
],

cs:[
  {t:"Motivational Interviewing — Core Skills",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">What is MI?</div>Motivational Interviewing is a collaborative, goal-oriented conversation style that helps patients find their own motivation for change. It is directive but patient-centred. Evidence shows it doubles compliance rates compared to prescriptive advice-giving.</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="display:none"></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cs)">O</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Open questions</span> — "What concerns do you have about your health?" "What would your life look like if you made this change?" Avoid yes/no questions. Open questions = you learn, they reflect.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cs)">A</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Affirmations</span> — Acknowledge strengths, efforts, and past successes. "You've managed to quit smoking once before — that shows real determination." Builds self-efficacy.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cs)">R</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Reflective listening</span> — Reflect back what you hear: "So it sounds like you know what you should do, but finding the time feels impossible?" This feels deeply validating to patients.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:var(--cs)">S</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Summaries</span> — Periodically summarise what you've heard: "Let me see if I've understood correctly..." This helps patients hear their own situation more clearly.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Clinical Pearl</div><div class="pt">The "readiness ruler" technique: "On a scale of 0–10, how important is this change to you? And how confident are you that you could make it?" Low importance → explore values and consequences. Low confidence → explore barriers and small achievable steps. This one question set saves 20 minutes of ineffective advice-giving.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Stages of Change — Transtheoretical Model",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Patient says/thinks</th><th>Your role</th><th>Key phrase</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Precontemplation</td><td>"I don't have a problem" / "My diet is fine"</td><td>Raise awareness gently. Plant a seed. Don't confront — it increases resistance.</td><td>"What do you know about how diet affects your condition?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Contemplation</td><td>"I know I should change, but..."</td><td>Explore ambivalence. Tip the decisional balance. Highlight discrepancy between values and behaviour.</td><td>"What would be different in your life if you made this change?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Preparation</td><td>"I'm thinking about starting next month"</td><td>Help plan. Set specific, achievable SMART goals. Address anticipated barriers.</td><td>"What is the first small step you could take this week?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Action</td><td>Actively making changes</td><td>Provide support, practical tools, monitor progress. Celebrate small wins.</td><td>"How are you finding the changes so far? What's working well?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Maintenance</td><td>Change maintained &gt;6 months</td><td>Help identify triggers for relapse. Build self-efficacy. Prevent complacency.</td><td>"What situations make it hardest to maintain the changes?"</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Relapse</td><td>Returns to old behaviour</td><td>Normalise relapse — it's part of change. Re-engage with compassion, not judgement.</td><td>"Most people have some setbacks — what did you learn from this?"</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Matching your intervention to the patient's stage of change is the most important counselling skill. Giving detailed dietary advice to a precontemplation patient = wasted effort + patient feels judged and doesn't return. Checking readiness first saves time and builds the therapeutic relationship.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Lifestyle Prescription — SMART Goal Setting",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">SMART goals in naturopathic prescriptions</div>Vague advice ("eat better, exercise more") is never followed. SMART goals are: Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Poor advice</th><th>SMART prescription</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>"Eat more vegetables"</td><td>"Add one cup of raw vegetables (cucumber, carrot, tomato) to lunch every day for the next 2 weeks."</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"Exercise more"</td><td>"Walk briskly for 20 minutes after dinner, 5 days this week. Track it in a notebook."</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"Reduce stress"</td><td>"Practice Yoga Nidra recording (45 min) every day before sleep for 30 days. Note quality of sleep each morning."</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"Drink more water"</td><td>"Drink 2 glasses warm water immediately on waking each morning, and keep a 1L bottle visible at your desk. Target 2L by 3pm daily."</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"Do yoga"</td><td>"Practice the 6 asanas I taught you for 20 minutes every morning before breakfast, 6 days a week. Review in 4 weeks."</td></tr>
      <tr><td>"Reduce sugar"</td><td>"Replace your afternoon tea (2 tsp sugar) with green tea (no sugar) from Monday. One change at a time."</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">One change at a time. Patients who are given 10 lifestyle changes at once make zero. Agree on ONE priority change with the patient (not what you think is most important — what THEY are most ready to change). Master that first. Then add the next. This approach has much higher long-term compliance.</div></div>`}
],

rf:[
  {t:"ABSOLUTE CONTRAINDICATIONS — Do NOT Treat Naturopathically",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">⚠️ These are emergencies — refer immediately, do not attempt naturopathic treatment first</div></div>
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Acute myocardial infarction (Heart attack)</strong> — Chest pain + radiation + sweating + breathlessness = call 108/112. No yoga, massage, or any treatment. Immediate MONA + referral.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Acute stroke</strong> — Sudden face drooping, arm weakness, speech difficulty, severe headache, vision loss = FAST response. Immediate emergency referral. Time is brain (1.9 million neurons die per minute).</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA)</strong> — T1DM or T2DM with vomiting, abdominal pain, ketones, deep breathing (Kussmaul), altered consciousness. Medical emergency. IV insulin + fluids needed.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Hypertensive emergency</strong> — BP ≥180/120 with end-organ damage (headache, visual changes, chest pain, neurological deficit). Medical emergency — IV medication required. Do NOT attempt to lower BP with yoga/breathing alone.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Acute surgical abdomen</strong> — Peritonitis, appendicitis, bowel perforation, ectopic pregnancy. Board-like rigidity, rebound tenderness, absent bowel sounds. Surgical emergency.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Sepsis/Septic shock</strong> — Fever + hypotension + tachycardia + altered consciousness. Life-threatening. IV antibiotics within 1 hour. Not a naturopathic condition.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Active pulmonary tuberculosis (TB)</strong> — Confirm diagnosis first. Naturopathy can be COMPLEMENTARY to anti-TB drugs (RIPE protocol), never sole treatment. Highly contagious — use appropriate precautions.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Acute asthma attack (severe)</strong> — Cannot complete sentences, SpO₂ &lt;92%, RR &gt;30. Bronchodilators + O₂ required. Yoga/pranayama are for prevention, not acute attack management.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Psychiatric emergency</strong> — Active suicidal ideation, psychosis (hallucinations, delusions, disorganised behaviour), severe mania. Immediate psychiatric referral.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Suspected malignancy</strong> — Unexplained weight loss, night sweats, persistent lymphadenopathy, haemoptysis, rectal/vaginal bleeding, suspicious breast lump. Urgent referral for diagnosis first. Do NOT delay diagnosis with naturopathic treatment.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:#dc2626"></span><div><strong>Deep vein thrombosis (DVT) / Pulmonary embolism</strong> — Unilateral calf pain + swelling (DVT) or sudden breathlessness + pleuritic chest pain (PE). No massage. Immediate anticoagulation needed.</div></div>
    </div>`},

  {t:"Red Flag Symptoms — Always Investigate Before Treatment",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Red flags in BNYS practice — investigate or refer before treating naturopathically</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Red flag features</th><th>Possible serious cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Back pain</td><td>Age &lt;20 or &gt;55, bilateral leg weakness/numbness, saddle anaesthesia, bladder/bowel dysfunction, fever, unexplained weight loss, history of malignancy</td><td>Cauda equina syndrome (emergency), spinal cord compression, metastatic malignancy, spinal infection</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Headache</td><td>Thunderclap onset (worst headache of life), progressive, on waking, associated neurological signs, fever + neck stiffness, head injury</td><td>Subarachnoid haemorrhage, raised ICP, meningitis, intracranial tumour</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chest pain</td><td>Central, crushing, radiating to arm/jaw, associated breathlessness, sweating, nausea</td><td>Acute MI, PE, aortic dissection, unstable angina</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Weight loss</td><td>Unexplained, &gt;5% in 3 months, without dietary change</td><td>Malignancy, TB, hyperthyroidism, diabetes, HIV, malabsorption</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fever</td><td>&gt;39°C, prolonged (&gt;7 days), with night sweats, rigor, localised pain/redness</td><td>Serious infection (malaria, TB, typhoid, IE, abscess), lymphoma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Breathlessness</td><td>Sudden onset, at rest, rapidly progressive, associated chest pain or haemoptysis</td><td>PE, pneumothorax, acute pulmonary oedema, severe asthma</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GI symptoms</td><td>Rectal bleeding especially dark/melaena, dysphagia progressive, vomiting blood, change in bowel habit &gt;6 weeks in &gt;40 yrs</td><td>GI malignancy, peptic ulcer, GI bleed</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Jaundice</td><td>Any new jaundice</td><td>Hepatitis (infective, alcoholic), biliary obstruction, malignancy — requires liver function tests + imaging</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Critical Pearl</div><div class="pt">Your most important clinical skill as a BNYS physician is knowing what is BEYOND your scope. A doctor who refers appropriately and promptly saves lives. A doctor who tries to treat everything with naturopathy harms patients. The two most important questions before starting any naturopathic treatment: (1) Is this an emergency? (2) Do I need to rule out a serious underlying cause first?</div></div>`},

  {t:"Conditions Where Naturopathy is Complementary (Not Primary)",c:`
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Collaborative approach — naturopathy supports but does not replace allopathic treatment</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Allopathic primary treatment</th><th>BNYS complementary role</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Type 1 Diabetes</td><td>Insulin is life-saving and non-negotiable</td><td>Yoga + diet to improve glucose control, reduce insulin requirements. Never reduce insulin without endocrinologist involvement.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Epilepsy</td><td>Anticonvulsants</td><td>Yoga Nidra, stress management to reduce seizure frequency. Avoid fasting, avoid Kapalbhati/Bhastrika (may trigger seizure).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Schizophrenia / Bipolar</td><td>Antipsychotics/mood stabilisers</td><td>Yoga, pranayama as ADJUNCT under psychiatric supervision. Never advise stopping psychiatric medications.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Active TB</td><td>RIPE (Rifampicin, Isoniazid, Pyrazinamide, Ethambutol) regimen</td><td>Nutritional support, pranayama (breathing exercises), lifestyle support. COMPLEMENTARY ONLY.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>HIV/AIDS</td><td>ART (antiretroviral therapy)</td><td>Nutritional optimisation, yoga to improve quality of life and immunity. Never advise stopping ART.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Advanced heart failure</td><td>Medications + device therapy</td><td>Gentle yoga (modified), pranayama, dietary sodium restriction. No intensive yoga or hydrotherapy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Malignancy</td><td>Surgery, chemotherapy, radiotherapy</td><td>Nutritional support, Yoga Nidra for anxiety and pain, massage for comfort (not over tumour site). Integrative oncology consultation needed.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pregnancy complications</td><td>Obstetric care</td><td>Prenatal yoga (specific), Bhramari pranayama, dietary support. Avoid SP6, LI4, SP8 acupressure points. Refer any complication immediately.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The phrase to use with patients: "Naturopathy and modern medicine are not enemies — they are partners. My job is to support your body's healing while you also get the treatment you need from your specialist. I will coordinate with your other doctors." This builds trust, keeps patients safe, and positions BNYS as the professional discipline it is.</div></div>`}
]

};
const D_IMAGING = {

or:[
  {t:"How to Read Any Ortho X-Ray — ABCS Approach",c:`
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Always request TWO views at 90° to each other (AP + lateral) — NEVER report on a single view</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">A</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Alignment</span> — Are the bones aligned correctly? Joint congruity maintained? Any dislocation or subluxation? Check articular surfaces are parallel and joint spaces symmetric.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">B</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Bone density & texture</span> — Increased density (sclerosis = bone reaction, infection, avascular necrosis, metastasis). Decreased density (osteopenia, osteoporosis, lytic lesions from myeloma/metastasis). Trabecular pattern — interrupted = pathological fracture risk.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">C</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Cartilage / joint space</span> — Measure joint space width. Narrowing = cartilage loss (osteoarthritis, inflammatory arthritis). Uniform narrowing = inflammatory. Focal/asymmetric = OA. Widening = effusion or ligament laxity.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">S</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Soft tissues</span> — Swelling (joint effusion), calcification (CPPD, calcific tendinitis, myositis ossificans), gas (infection — surgical emergency), foreign bodies, fat pad signs.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Additionally assess for fractures — describe using these 6 features</div>
      <b>1. Location</b> (which bone, which third — proximal/mid/distal) · <b>2. Pattern</b> (transverse/oblique/spiral/comminuted/avulsion/stress) · <b>3. Displacement</b> (undisplaced/displaced — direction) · <b>4. Angulation</b> (apex direction, degrees) · <b>5. Rotation</b> · <b>6. Open vs closed</b> (soft tissue integrity)
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Absence of fracture on X-ray does NOT exclude fracture. Scaphoid fractures are X-ray negative in 20% initially — if snuffbox tenderness present, treat as scaphoid fracture and repeat X-ray at 10 days (or MRI immediately). Stress fractures are also often X-ray negative for 2–3 weeks — request bone scan or MRI.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Fracture Classification & Patterns",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Fracture type</th><th>X-ray appearance</th><th>Common cause</th><th>Key concern</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Transverse</td><td>Horizontal fracture line perpendicular to bone axis</td><td>Direct trauma (bending force)</td><td>Can have butterfly fragment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Oblique</td><td>Fracture line at angle to bone shaft</td><td>Angulation force</td><td>Tendency to displace</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spiral</td><td>Corkscrew fracture line encircling bone</td><td>Rotational/torsional force. Tibia in children = NAI (non-accidental injury)</td><td>Beware in children — report safeguarding concern</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Comminuted</td><td>3 or more fragments</td><td>High-energy trauma</td><td>Vascular and nerve injury, complex fixation needed</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Impacted</td><td>Fracture ends driven into each other (increased density at fracture site)</td><td>Axial loading (fall on outstretched hand, heel)</td><td>May appear subtle — look for cortical buckling</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Avulsion</td><td>Small bone fragment pulled away at ligament/tendon attachment</td><td>Sudden muscular contraction or ligament stress</td><td>Suggests significant soft tissue injury</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stress (fatigue)</td><td>Often invisible initially. Periosteal reaction ("grey cortex" sign) after 2–3 weeks</td><td>Repetitive loading (athletes, military recruits)</td><td>X-ray often negative — need MRI or bone scan</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pathological</td><td>Fracture through abnormal bone — look for lytic/sclerotic lesion at fracture site</td><td>Metastasis ★, myeloma, osteoporosis, Paget's, infection</td><td>Investigate underlying cause urgently</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Greenstick</td><td>One cortex broken, other bent — like green stick</td><td>Children only (bones more flexible)</td><td>May need manipulation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Torus (buckle)</td><td>Cortical buckling/puckering without complete break</td><td>Children — axial loading</td><td>Stable fracture — usually conservative management</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Spiral fracture of femur in a child under 3 years = non-accidental injury until proven otherwise. Document carefully, involve paediatrics and safeguarding team. Do NOT send the child home without a full assessment.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Common Orthopaedic X-Ray Findings — Upper Limb",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>X-ray findings</th><th>Clinical correlation</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Colles' fracture</td><td>Distal radius fracture (within 2.5cm of wrist joint). Dorsal displacement + angulation = "dinner fork" deformity. Often with ulnar styloid avulsion.</td><td>Fall on outstretched hand (FOOSH) in elderly osteoporotic women. Most common wrist fracture.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Smith's fracture</td><td>Distal radius fracture with VOLAR (forward) displacement — reverse Colles'</td><td>Fall on flexed wrist. "Garden spade" deformity.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Scaphoid fracture</td><td>Fracture line through scaphoid waist (most common). May be invisible acutely.</td><td>FOOSH in young adults. Snuffbox tenderness. Risk of avascular necrosis if missed (blood supply enters distally).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Monteggia fracture-dislocation</td><td>Ulna shaft fracture + radial head dislocation</td><td>"One bone fractures — the other dislocates." Always look at elbow when forearm fracture seen.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Galeazzi fracture-dislocation</td><td>Radius shaft fracture + distal radioulnar joint (DRUJ) dislocation</td><td>Converse of Monteggia. Check DRUJ when radial shaft fracture seen.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Supracondylar fracture (humerus)</td><td>Fracture through distal humerus above condyles. Posterior fat pad sign ★ (sail sign) even without visible fracture line.</td><td>Most common elbow fracture in children. Risk: anterior interosseous nerve (AIN) and brachial artery injury → urgent reduction.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Shoulder dislocation</td><td>Anterior (95%): humeral head displaced forward and inferior — overlaps glenoid on AP. Loss of normal "light bulb" shape. Hill-Sachs deformity (compression fracture of posterior humeral head).</td><td>Always check axillary nerve function (sensation lateral arm) before and after reduction.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acromioclavicular (AC) dislocation</td><td>Widening of AC joint space (&gt;5mm). Step deformity of clavicle. Grade I–VI (Rockwood).</td><td>Fall on tip of shoulder. Grade I–II conservative; Grade IV–VI surgical.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Calcific tendinitis (shoulder)</td><td>Amorphous calcium deposit in supraspinatus tendon (superior to greater tuberosity)</td><td>Severe acute shoulder pain. Calcium deposits may resorb spontaneously.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Common Orthopaedic X-Ray Findings — Lower Limb",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>X-ray findings</th><th>Clinical notes</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Neck of femur fracture</td><td>Disruption of Shenton's line (smooth curve from femoral neck to obturator foramen). Valgus/varus angulation. Garden classification I–IV.</td><td>Elderly osteoporotic. Garden I–II = undisplaced (internal fixation). Garden III–IV = displaced (hemiarthroplasty/THR). AVN risk increases with displacement.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Intertrochanteric fracture</td><td>Fracture line between greater and lesser trochanters. Extracapsular. Comminuted in 4-part.</td><td>Extracapsular = better blood supply = lower AVN risk. Dynamic hip screw (DHS) fixation.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tibial plateau fracture</td><td>Fracture/depression of tibial plateau. Measure depression depth (&gt;2mm = significant). Schatzker I–VI classification.</td><td>Axial loading + valgus force. Schatzker IV–VI = high energy = popliteal artery/peroneal nerve risk.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ankle fracture (Weber classification)</td><td>Weber A: below syndesmosis. Weber B: at level of syndesmosis. Weber C: above syndesmosis (syndesmosis likely disrupted).</td><td>Weber C = unstable = syndesmosis injury = surgery usually needed. Weber A usually stable.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Calcaneal fracture</td><td>Bohler's angle (&lt;20° = flattened = fracture) and Gissane's angle (&gt;130° = abnormal). Intra-articular subtalar involvement.</td><td>Axial loading (fall from height). Always check spine X-ray — 10% have associated spinal fracture.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lisfranc injury</td><td>Normally 2nd metatarsal base aligns with medial border of middle cuneiform. Any misalignment = Lisfranc. Fleck sign (small avulsion at base of 2nd MT) = pathognomonic.</td><td>Commonly missed! Weight-bearing X-rays show instability better. MRI for definitive assessment.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Slipped upper femoral epiphysis (SUFE)</td><td>Klein's line (drawn along superior femoral neck) should intersect femoral epiphysis. In SUFE it misses the epiphysis (medial slip).</td><td>Obese adolescent boys. Urgent ortho referral — avoid weight-bearing. Bilateral in 25%.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Perthes disease</td><td>Crescent sign (subchondral fracture), fragmentation, increased density of femoral head, widened joint space early</td><td>Boys 4–8 years. AVN of femoral head. Progresses over months to years.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Arthritis on X-Ray — Quick Comparison (All Types)",c:`
    <div class="alert a-amb"><div class="a-label">Master rule</div>5 features to check for every arthritis X-ray: Distribution · Joint space · Bone density · Erosions · Special features. The single fastest differentiator: <b>DIPJs involved?</b> → OA or Psoriatic. Spared? → RA.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Osteoarthritis</th><th>Rheumatoid Arthritis</th><th>Gout</th><th>Psoriatic Arthritis</th><th>Ankylosing Spondylitis</th><th>CPPD</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Distribution</td><td>Knee, hip, DIPJs, 1st CMC, 1st MTPJ, spine</td><td>Symmetric MCPJs, PIPJs, wrists — SPARES DIPJs ★</td><td>1st MTPJ ★, ankle, knee. Asymmetric.</td><td>DIPJs ★ (opposite RA), asymmetric, sausage digit</td><td>SI joints (bilateral symmetric) ★, spine, entheses</td><td>Wrist (TFCC), knee menisci, symphysis pubis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Joint space</td><td>Asymmetric focal narrowing</td><td>Uniform narrowing (pannus)</td><td>PRESERVED until late ★</td><td>Narrowing + erosions at DIPJs</td><td>SI joint: widened → narrowed → fused</td><td>Narrowing in affected joints</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bone density</td><td>Normal / subchondral sclerosis ↑</td><td>Juxta-articular osteopenia ★</td><td>Normal</td><td>Normal + periosteal new bone</td><td>Normal early</td><td>Normal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Erosions</td><td>ABSENT (osteophytes instead) ★</td><td>Marginal "rat bite" erosions at bare area</td><td>Punched-out with overhanging sclerotic edge (Martel sign) ★</td><td>Pencil-in-cup deformity ★</td><td>Shiny corners (Romanus lesion), enthesopathy</td><td>Absent / rare</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Osteophytes</td><td>Prominent ★ bony lipping</td><td>None</td><td>None</td><td>Fluffy periosteal reaction, enthesophytes</td><td>Syndesmophytes → bamboo spine</td><td>None / mild</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Key sign</td><td>LOSS mnemonic: Loss of space, Osteophytes, Sclerosis, Subchondral cysts</td><td>Soft tissue swelling + ulnar drift + subluxation</td><td>Normal density + preserved space + overhanging erosion</td><td>Ivory phalanx, sausage digit, asymmetric SI</td><td>Bamboo spine, trolley track sign, fused SI joints</td><td>Chondrocalcinosis ★ (calcium lines in cartilage)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 One-line differentiators</div><div class="pt">OA = DIPJ + osteophytes + no erosions. RA = MCPJ/PIPJ symmetric + osteopenia + marginal erosions + spares DIPJ. Gout = 1st MTPJ + preserved space + overhanging erosion + tophi. PsA = DIPJ + pencil-in-cup + periosteal new bone. AS = bilateral SI joints + bamboo spine. CPPD = chondrocalcinosis in cartilage.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Osteoarthritis (OA) — X-Ray in Detail",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">LOSS — the 4 hallmark X-ray signs of OA</div>
      <b>L</b>oss of joint space (asymmetric) · <b>O</b>steophytes (bony lipping) · <b>S</b>ubchondral sclerosis (↑ density) · <b>S</b>ubchondral cysts (geodes)
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Joint</th><th>Key X-ray features</th><th>Views required</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Knee OA ★</td><td>Medial compartment narrowing (most common), varus deformity, osteophytes at tibial spines and femoral condyles, subchondral sclerosis, patellofemoral OA (skyline view), loose bodies</td><td>Weight-bearing AP + lateral + skyline (patellofemoral). Standing films are MANDATORY.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hip OA</td><td>Superior joint space narrowing (most common), femoral head and acetabular osteophytes, subchondral cysts, varus/valgus deformity, leg length discrepancy</td><td>AP pelvis + lateral hip</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hand OA</td><td>Heberden's nodes (DIPJs — bony hard, non-tender), Bouchard's nodes (PIPJs), 1st CMC "squared thumb" appearance ★, asymmetric narrowing</td><td>PA and oblique views of hand</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spine (spondylosis)</td><td>Disc space narrowing, anterior/posterior osteophytes, facet joint OA, vacuum phenomenon (gas in disc = degenerative), Schmorl's nodes (disc herniation into endplate)</td><td>AP + lateral. C5/6, L4/5 most common levels.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">KL Grade I</div><div class="nv-val">Doubtful narrowing + possible osteophytes</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">KL Grade II</div><div class="nv-val">Definite osteophytes + possible narrowing</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">KL Grade III</div><div class="nv-val">Moderate narrowing + multiple osteophytes + sclerosis</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">KL Grade IV</div><div class="nv-val">Severe/bone-on-bone narrowing + large osteophytes + deformity</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always take STANDING (weight-bearing) films for knee OA. A supine film underestimates narrowing by up to 2mm — a Grade II on supine may be Grade IV on standing. Orthopaedic surgeons require weight-bearing films before listing for knee replacement. Skyline (sunrise) view for patellofemoral OA — often missed on AP + lateral alone.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) — X-Ray in Detail",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">RA X-ray progression — early signs appear within 6 months</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>X-ray findings</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Stage I (early)</td><td>Periarticular soft tissue swelling (fusiform), juxta-articular osteopenia ★ (FIRST sign), NO erosions yet, NO joint space loss</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage II (moderate)</td><td>Marginal erosions at bare area ★, uniform joint space narrowing, wrist involvement, early subluxation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage III (severe)</td><td>Large erosions, marked narrowing, joint subluxation (MCPJs — ulnar drift), swan neck, boutonnière deformity</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage IV (end-stage)</td><td>Bony ankylosis (joint fusion), gross deformity, secondary OA superimposed</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px"><thead><tr><th>Joint</th><th>Specific RA X-ray features</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Hands & wrists ★</td><td>Symmetric MCP + PIP erosions, SPARES DIPJs ★, ulnar styloid erosion (earliest wrist sign), carpal destruction, ulnar deviation MCPJs</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Feet</td><td>5th MTPJ erosion (earliest foot finding ★), hallux valgus, metatarsal subluxation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cervical spine ⚠️</td><td>Atlantoaxial subluxation (C1-C2 gap &gt;3mm = abnormal, &gt;9mm = cord risk). ALWAYS X-ray cervical spine before GA in RA patients.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Knee</td><td>Uniform narrowing ALL 3 compartments (vs OA = medial only), valgus deformity (vs OA = varus), periarticular osteopenia</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Atlantoaxial subluxation in RA is a surgical emergency if symptomatic. C1-C2 distance on lateral flexion view &gt;3mm = subluxation. RA patient with neck pain + hand tingling + leg weakness = urgent MRI cervical spine. NEVER manipulate the neck in RA without imaging. Inform anaesthetist before any GA.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Ankylosing Spondylitis (AS) — X-Ray in Detail",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">AS progression: SI joints → lumbar → thoracic → cervical spine (bottom-up)</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Structure</th><th>Early X-ray</th><th>Late X-ray</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Sacroiliac joints ★ (first)</td><td>Subchondral sclerosis (iliac side &gt; sacral), pseudo-widening (erosions), blurred margins</td><td>Complete bony fusion — SI joints disappear</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vertebral bodies</td><td>Shiny corners (Romanus lesion): erosion + sclerosis at anterior corners. Squaring of vertebral bodies (loss of normal anterior concavity).</td><td>Syndesmophytes (vertical fine bridges) → bamboo spine ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bamboo spine (late)</td><td>—</td><td>Continuous calcification of annulus fibrosus + longitudinal ligaments. "Trolley track" sign on AP (3 vertical lines). Completely fused, brittle spine.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hip joints</td><td>Bilateral symmetric narrowing (axial migration — different from OA which is superior)</td><td>Bony ankylosis, protrusio acetabuli</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Enthesopathy</td><td>Erosions + new bone at Achilles, plantar fascia, ischial tuberosities, iliac crests ("whiskering")</td><td>Large fluffy enthesophytes</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SI Grade 0</div><div class="nv-val">Normal</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SI Grade 1</div><div class="nv-val">Suspicious only</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SI Grade 2</div><div class="nv-val">Early erosions + sclerosis</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SI Grade 3</div><div class="nv-val">Sclerosis + partial fusion</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">SI Grade 4</div><div class="nv-val">Complete bony fusion</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">NY criteria</div><div class="nv-val">Grade ≥2 bilateral OR grade 3–4 unilateral</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Bamboo spine fractures are dangerous — the ankylosed spine behaves like a long bone. Even a minor fall can cause a complete unstable fracture through an ankylosed segment, frequently MISSED on plain X-ray. Always CT spine in AS patients after ANY trauma. The fracture pattern is typically through a disc level (3-column injury) — very unstable.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Gout, Psoriatic & Other Arthropathies — X-Ray",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Pathognomonic X-ray finding</th><th>Other features</th><th>Key differentiator</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Gout</td><td>Punched-out erosion with overhanging sclerotic edge ★ (Martel sign / "rat bite with hood")</td><td>1st MTPJ ★, preserved joint space (even with large erosions), calcified tophi, normal bone density, asymmetric</td><td>Joint space PRESERVED despite large erosions — unique to gout</td></tr>
      <tr><td>CPPD (Pseudogout)</td><td>Chondrocalcinosis ★ — calcium lines in cartilage (knee menisci, wrist TFCC, symphysis pubis)</td><td>Acute: looks like septic arthritis or gout. Chronic: OA at unusual sites (wrist, MCPJs, shoulder, elbow)</td><td>Calcium in CARTILAGE (not soft tissue). Causes: ageing ★, hyperparathyroidism, haemochromatosis, hypomagnesaemia</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Psoriatic Arthritis (PsA)</td><td>Pencil-in-cup deformity ★ (whittling of one bone end fitting into cup-shaped erosion)</td><td>DIPJs ★, asymmetric, ivory phalanx (sclerotic distal phalanx), periosteal new bone, asymmetric sacroiliitis (vs AS = symmetric)</td><td>Both erosive AND productive changes on same finger. DIPJ + skin plaques = PsA.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Septic arthritis (early)</td><td>Soft tissue swelling ★, joint space WIDENING (effusion)</td><td>Rapid progression to narrowing and destruction within days — faster than any other arthritis</td><td>Speed of destruction: septic = days. RA = months. OA = years.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Charcot joint (neuropathic)</td><td>5 Ds: Density ↑, Debris (loose bodies), Disorganisation, Distension, Dislocation ★</td><td>Grossly destructive X-ray with minimal clinical pain (disproportionate). DM (foot ★), tabes dorsalis (knee), syringomyelia (shoulder)</td><td>"Too much damage for too little pain" — gross X-ray destruction, unbothered patient</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Haemochromatosis</td><td>OA at unusual sites: 2nd and 3rd MCPJs ★ with hook-shaped osteophytes</td><td>Chondrocalcinosis of wrist TFCC and knee, osteoporosis</td><td>OA at MCPJs (unusual site) + chondrocalcinosis = haemochromatosis. Check ferritin + transferrin saturation.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reactive arthritis (Reiter's)</td><td>Asymmetric oligoarthritis, calcaneal spurs ★, Achilles enthesopathy, periosteal reaction</td><td>Asymmetric sacroiliitis (unilateral), lower limb predominant</td><td>Post-infectious (Chlamydia, Salmonella). Triad: urethritis + arthritis + conjunctivitis.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Chondrocalcinosis causes mnemonic — ABCDEFGH</div><div class="pt">Ageing ★ · Biochemical (hypoMg, hypoP) · Calcium excess · Diabetes · Endocrine (hyperPTH, hypothyroid) · Familial (CCAL2 gene) · Gout (associated) · Haemochromatosis. In a young patient with chondrocalcinosis — always check calcium, PTH, magnesium, phosphate, ferritin, and transferrin saturation.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Spine X-Ray Interpretation",c:`
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">1</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Alignment</span> — Check lateral view: normal cervical lordosis, thoracic kyphosis, lumbar lordosis. Loss of lordosis = muscle spasm. Spondylolisthesis: one vertebra slips forward on the one below — grade by percentage displacement (Meyerding I–IV).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">2</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Vertebral body height</span> — Compression fracture: anterior wedging of vertebral body. Height loss &gt;50% = significant. Multilevel = osteoporosis. Single level with posterior involvement = metastasis/myeloma.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">3</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Disc spaces</span> — Narrowed: degeneration, infection (discitis shows irregular endplates + narrowing + loss of definition). Widened: fracture-dislocation, infection early.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">4</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Posterior elements</span> — Pedicles: absent pedicle on AP view = metastatic destruction ★ ("winking owl" sign). Facet joints: narrowing = degeneration. Spondylolysis: break in pars interarticularis (scotty dog sign on oblique view).</div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Key X-ray finding</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Ankylosing spondylitis</td><td>Bamboo spine (syndesmophytes bridging vertebrae), squaring of vertebral bodies, sacroiliac joint fusion (bilateral, symmetric), "trolley track" sign on AP</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spondylolisthesis</td><td>Forward slip of one vertebra on the other. L4/5 and L5/S1 most common. Scotty dog with collar = spondylolysis (pars defect).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Osteoporotic compression fracture</td><td>Anterior wedge deformity, multiple levels, Schmorl's nodes (disc herniation into endplate)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Metastatic disease</td><td>Absent pedicle (winking owl), lytic or sclerotic lesion, vertebral collapse with posterior cortex involvement</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cervical spondylosis</td><td>Disc space narrowing (C5/6, C6/7 most common), osteophytes (foraminal narrowing), loss of cervical lordosis</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The "winking owl" sign: on AP lumbar X-ray, normal pedicles look like owl eyes. If one pedicle is absent or indistinct = metastatic destruction. This is often the earliest radiological sign of spinal metastasis. Always check pedicles systematically on every AP spine X-ray.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Bone Density & Metabolic Bone Disease",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Description</th><th>Cause</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Generalised osteopenia</td><td>Cortical thinning, loss of trabecular pattern, vertebral "cod-fish" deformity</td><td>Osteoporosis ★, osteomalacia, hyperparathyroidism, malnutrition</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Looser zones (pseudofractures)</td><td>Radiolucent lines perpendicular to cortex, often bilateral and symmetric. Partial stress fractures.</td><td>Osteomalacia ★ (vitamin D deficiency, renal disease). Classic sites: femoral neck, pubic rami, ribs, scapulae.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Subperiosteal resorption</td><td>Loss of cortical definition at radial aspect of middle phalanges, distal clavicle</td><td>Hyperparathyroidism ★. Check PTH, calcium, phosphate.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rugger-jersey spine</td><td>Alternating dense and lucent bands in vertebral bodies — like a striped rugby jersey</td><td>Renal osteodystrophy (secondary hyperparathyroidism in CKD)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Paget's disease</td><td>Bone enlargement, cortical thickening, coarse trabecular pattern ("cotton wool" skull, "blade of grass" advancing front in long bones), bowing</td><td>Paget's disease of bone. Elevated ALP ★★★ (sometimes &gt;1000 U/L)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sclerotic metastases</td><td>Increased bone density in patchy distribution, may be multiple</td><td>Prostate cancer ★, breast cancer (osteoblastic), lymphoma. Contrast: lytic = kidney, thyroid, myeloma, lung</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bone cysts / lytic lesions</td><td>Punched-out, well-defined lytic lesions. "Soap bubble" = giant cell tumour. "Rain-drop" pattern skull = myeloma ★</td><td>Myeloma (skull), GCT (epiphysis of long bone), ABC, enchondroma</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Knee X-Ray — Detailed Assessment",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal medial joint space</div><div class="nv-val">4–5 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal lateral joint space</div><div class="nv-val">4–5 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Significant narrowing</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;2 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Kellgren-Lawrence grade</div><div class="nv-val">0–4 (OA severity)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>What it means</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Kellgren-Lawrence Grade I</td><td>Doubtful narrowing + possible osteophytes. Mild OA.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kellgren-Lawrence Grade II</td><td>Definite osteophytes + possible joint space narrowing. Mild OA.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kellgren-Lawrence Grade III</td><td>Moderate joint space narrowing + multiple osteophytes + subchondral sclerosis. Moderate OA.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kellgren-Lawrence Grade IV</td><td>Severe narrowing (bone-on-bone) + large osteophytes + severe sclerosis + deformity. Severe OA = surgical candidate.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Patellofemoral OA</td><td>Skyline (sunrise) view: lateral patellofemoral joint space narrowing + osteophytes + patellar tilt</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Loose body</td><td>Dense fragment within joint space. OA, osteochondral injury, synovial osteochondromatosis.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fabella</td><td>Sesamoid bone in lateral gastrocnemius tendon. Seen in 10–30%. Normal variant — don't mistake for loose body or fracture.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Varus/Valgus deformity</td><td>Tibiofemoral angle on standing AP. Varus (bow-leg) = medial compartment OA. Valgus (knock-knee) = lateral compartment OA.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always take weight-bearing (standing) X-rays for knee OA assessment — non-weight-bearing films underestimate joint space narrowing by up to 2mm. A knee that looks grade II lying down may be grade IV on standing. Most orthopaedic surgeons require standing films before listing for knee replacement.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Hip X-Ray — Assessment & Measurements",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal joint space</div><div class="nv-val">4–5 mm (superior)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Significant narrowing</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;2 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">CE angle (center-edge)</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;25° (dysplasia if &lt;20°)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal neck-shaft angle</div><div class="nv-val">125–135°</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">1</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Shenton's line</span> — Smooth arc from inferior femoral neck to inferior border of superior pubic ramus. Broken line = hip fracture or dislocation.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">2</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Acetabular coverage</span> — Center-edge (CE) angle: angle between vertical line through femoral head centre and line to acetabular edge. &lt;20° = dysplasia → risk of early OA.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">3</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Joint space narrowing pattern</span> — Superior = classic OA. Medial = inflammatory (RA). Axial (all round) = avascular necrosis or inflammatory.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--or)">4</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Avascular necrosis (AVN) signs</span> — Crescent sign (subchondral fracture — pathognomonic), sclerosis, collapse and flattening of femoral head. Causes: steroids ★, alcohol, sickle cell, trauma, Perthes.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The crescent sign in AVN: a thin radiolucent line just beneath the articular surface of the femoral head, representing a subchondral fracture. It is pathognomonic of AVN. MRI is far more sensitive for early AVN (before X-ray changes) — if clinical suspicion is high and X-ray is normal, MRI hip is the investigation of choice.</div></div>`}
],

ec:[
  {t:"2D Echo — Standard Views & What You See",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Standard 4 probe positions (parasternal, apical, subcostal, suprasternal)</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>View</th><th>Probe position</th><th>What you see</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Parasternal long axis (PLAX)</td><td>3rd–4th ICS left sternal edge, probe marker toward right shoulder</td><td>LV, RV, aortic root, LA, mitral valve, aortic valve, posterior pericardium</td><td>LV dimensions, MV morphology, aortic root size, pericardial effusion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Parasternal short axis (PSAX) — base</td><td>Rotate 90° from PLAX</td><td>Aortic valve (tricuspid "Mercedes-Benz" shape), LA, RV, pulmonary valve, PA</td><td>Aortic valve morphology (bicuspid vs tricuspid), pulmonary hypertension</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PSAX — mid (papillary muscle level)</td><td>Angle slightly toward apex</td><td>Circular LV cross-section with 2 papillary muscles</td><td>Regional wall motion abnormalities ★, LV hypertrophy pattern</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apical 4-chamber (A4C)</td><td>Apex impulse position, probe marker toward left</td><td>All 4 chambers simultaneously, MV, TV, atrial and ventricular septum</td><td>LV function (EF), chamber sizes, valve regurgitation, ASD/VSD</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apical 2-chamber (A2C)</td><td>Rotate 60° counterclockwise from A4C</td><td>LV anterior and inferior walls, LA, MV</td><td>LV anterior/inferior wall motion, MV assessment</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Apical 5-chamber</td><td>Tilt slightly anterior from A4C</td><td>LVOT and aortic valve in addition to 4 chambers</td><td>LVOT obstruction (HOCM), aortic valve disease Doppler</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Subcostal (subxiphoid)</td><td>Below xiphoid, patient supine, knees bent</td><td>All 4 chambers, IVC, hepatic veins, pericardium</td><td>IVC size (volume status), tamponade assessment, subcostal 4-chamber view when other windows poor</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Suprasternal</td><td>Suprasternal notch, head extended</td><td>Aortic arch, descending aorta, pulmonary artery</td><td>Aortic coarctation, aortic arch pathology, patent ductus arteriosus (PDA)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Normal Echo Values — Must Know",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LV EF (ejection fraction)</div><div class="nv-val">≥55% (normal) 40–54% (mildly reduced) &lt;40% (reduced = HFrEF)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LV end-diastolic diameter (LVEDD)</div><div class="nv-val">M: 42–59 mm   F: 39–53 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LV end-systolic diameter (LVESD)</div><div class="nv-val">M: 25–40 mm   F: 22–35 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">IVS thickness (diastole)</div><div class="nv-val">6–10 mm (>12 mm = LVH)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Posterior wall thickness (diastole)</div><div class="nv-val">6–10 mm</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Aortic root diameter</div><div class="nv-val">20–37 mm (>40 mm = dilated)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LA diameter (PLAX)</div><div class="nv-val">25–40 mm (>40 mm = dilated)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LA volume index</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;34 mL/m² (>34 = dilated)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">RV diameter (A4C)</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;41 mm at base</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">TAPSE (RV systolic function)</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;17 mm (normal RV function)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">IVC diameter (subcostal)</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;21 mm (collapses &gt;50% = RA pressure ≤5 mmHg)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Estimated RVSP (TR jet)</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;35 mmHg (>50 = severe PH)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">EF is the most reported number but is the WORST measure of cardiac function in isolation. A patient with EF 60% can have severe diastolic dysfunction (HFpEF) and be very symptomatic. Always assess: EF + diastolic function (E/A ratio, E/e' ratio, LA volume) + wall motion + valve function together for a complete picture.</div></div>`},

  {t:"LV Systolic Function Assessment",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">How EF is calculated</div>Simpson's biplane method (most accurate): traces LV at end-diastole and end-systole in A4C and A2C views. EF = (EDV - ESV) / EDV × 100</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>EF category</th><th>Range</th><th>Name</th><th>Common causes</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Normal</td><td class="echo-val">≥55%</td><td>Preserved systolic function</td><td>Normal or HFpEF (diastolic dysfunction)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mildly reduced</td><td class="echo-val">45–54%</td><td>HFmrEF</td><td>Early cardiomyopathy, ischaemic heart disease</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Moderately reduced</td><td class="echo-val">35–44%</td><td>HFrEF</td><td>IHD, dilated cardiomyopathy (DCM), myocarditis, valvular</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Severely reduced</td><td class="abn-val">&lt;35%</td><td>Severe HFrEF</td><td>Advanced DCM, end-stage IHD, decompensated heart failure. Consider ICD/CRT.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>Regional wall motion abnormalities (RWMA)</strong> — Hypokinesia (reduced), akinesia (absent), dyskinesia (paradoxical outward motion in systole). RWMA in coronary artery territory = ischaemic heart disease ★.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>Global hypokinesia (all walls equally poor)</strong> — Dilated cardiomyopathy, myocarditis, tachycardiomyopathy, septic cardiomyopathy, toxins (alcohol, chemotherapy)</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>LV hypertrophy (LVH)</strong> — IVS and/or PW &gt;12mm. Causes: hypertension ★ (concentric LVH — IVS = PW), HOCM (asymmetric septal hypertrophy — IVS:PW ratio &gt;1.3), aortic stenosis (concentric), athlete's heart (eccentric, normal function)</div></div>
    </div>`},

  {t:"Diastolic Dysfunction — Grading",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Why diastolic function matters</div>50% of heart failure patients have preserved EF (HFpEF) — caused by diastolic dysfunction. Echo is the only non-invasive way to assess this. Always report diastolic parameters.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Grade</th><th>E/A ratio</th><th>E/e' ratio</th><th>TR velocity</th><th>LA volume index</th><th>Interpretation</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Normal diastolic function</td><td class="echo-val">0.8–2.0</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;14</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;2.8 m/s</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;34 mL/m²</td><td>Normal filling pressures</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Grade I — Impaired relaxation</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;0.8</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;14</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;2.8 m/s</td><td class="echo-val">&lt;34 mL/m²</td><td>Early — normal filling pressures. Often asymptomatic.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Grade II — Pseudonormal</td><td class="echo-val">0.8–2.0</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;14</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;2.8 m/s</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;34 mL/m²</td><td>Elevated filling pressures. Symptomatic on exertion.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Grade III — Restrictive</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;2.0</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;14</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;2.8 m/s</td><td class="abn-val">&gt;34 mL/m²</td><td>Severely elevated pressures. Severe HFpEF. Poor prognosis.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>E wave</strong> = early passive filling (from LA to LV when MV opens). <strong>A wave</strong> = late active filling (atrial contraction). Measured by PW Doppler at mitral valve tips.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>e' (tissue Doppler)</strong> = myocardial relaxation velocity at mitral annulus. Reduced e' (&lt;7cm/s medial, &lt;10 lateral) = impaired relaxation.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>E/e' ratio</strong> = estimate of LV filling pressure. E/e' &gt;14 = elevated LV filling pressure → likely HFpEF.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Pseudonormalisation (Grade II): E/A looks normal (0.8–2.0) but filling pressures are elevated. To unmask: Valsalva manoeuvre causes E/A &lt;0.8 in Grade II (reveals impaired relaxation). Always check E/e' and LA volume — they don't pseudonormalise.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Valve Assessment on 2D Echo",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Valve/Finding</th><th>2D appearance</th><th>Doppler finding</th><th>Severity marker</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Aortic stenosis (AS)</td><td>Thickened, calcified, restricted leaflets. Reduced aortic valve opening area. Post-stenotic aortic dilatation.</td><td>High-velocity CW jet across AV. Increased peak gradient.</td><td>Severe: Vmax &gt;4 m/s, mean gradient &gt;40 mmHg, AVA &lt;1.0 cm²</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Aortic regurgitation (AR)</td><td>Regurgitant jet from AV into LVOT on colour Doppler. Fluttering of MV anterior leaflet (severe AR — diastolic flutter).</td><td>Holodiastolic flow reversal in descending aorta (severe). Vena contracta &gt;6mm = severe.</td><td>Severe: vena contracta &gt;6mm, PHT &lt;200ms, holodiastolic reversal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mitral stenosis (MS)</td><td>Thickened, calcified MV leaflets. Hockey stick / doming deformity of anterior leaflet. Restricted leaflet separation. Enlarged LA.</td><td>Prolonged pressure half-time (PHT). Increased peak gradient.</td><td>Severe: MVA &lt;1.0 cm² (PHT method: MVA = 220/PHT)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mitral regurgitation (MR)</td><td>MR jet into LA on colour Doppler. Prolapse: posterior displacement of leaflet beyond annular plane. Flail: ruptured chordae → leaflet tip into LA.</td><td>CW density of MR jet, pulmonary venous flow reversal (severe).</td><td>Severe: vena contracta &gt;7mm, EROA &gt;0.4 cm², regurgitant volume &gt;60mL</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bicuspid aortic valve</td><td>2 leaflets on PSAX short axis view ("fish mouth" opening). Raphe (fused commissure) may be visible.</td><td>Variable — may have stenosis or regurgitation</td><td>Associated with aortic root dilatation and coarctation — check aortic dimensions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mitral valve prolapse (MVP)</td><td>Posterior displacement of MV leaflet(s) &gt;2mm beyond the mitral annular plane into the LA in PLAX view. Billowing appearance.</td><td>MR (mild to severe). Mid-systolic click on auscultation.</td><td>Billowing leaflet &gt;2mm displacement. Barlow's disease if both leaflets thick and prolapsing.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tricuspid regurgitation (TR)</td><td>TR jet into RA on colour Doppler (usually functional — RV dilatation). TR jet velocity used to estimate RVSP.</td><td>TR Vmax used: RVSP = 4(Vmax²) + RA pressure</td><td>RVSP &gt;50 mmHg = severe pulmonary hypertension</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Pericardial Disease on Echo",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Echo findings</th><th>Clinical significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Pericardial effusion — sizing</td><td>Anechoic (black) space around heart. Small: &lt;10mm posterior. Moderate: 10–20mm. Large: &gt;20mm. Circumferential vs loculated.</td><td>Causes: viral ★, malignancy, uraemia, hypothyroidism, TB, post-cardiac surgery, autoimmune</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cardiac tamponade</td><td>Large effusion + right atrial collapse (earliest, end-diastole) + RV diastolic collapse ★ + IVC plethora (&gt;21mm, &lt;50% collapse) + exaggerated respiratory variation in valve flows (&gt;25% mitral, &gt;40% tricuspid)</td><td>Clinical + echo diagnosis. Urgent pericardiocentesis needed. Beck's triad: hypotension + raised JVP + muffled heart sounds.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Constrictive pericarditis</td><td>Thickened, bright pericardium (&gt;4mm). Septal bounce (interventricular septal shift with respiration — "septal knock"). Dilated IVC. Normal or mildly reduced EF. Respiratory variation in E wave.</td><td>Post-viral, TB ★ (developing world), post-cardiac surgery. Treat surgically (pericardiectomy). Confused with restrictive cardiomyopathy — differentiate by hepatic vein flow reversal pattern and tissue Doppler e'.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Tamponade is a CLINICAL diagnosis — don't wait for echo confirmation if the patient is haemodynamically unstable (Beck's triad). The echo confirms and guides drainage. The earliest echo sign of tamponade is right atrial collapse (seen in systole), before RV collapse and before clinical deterioration. If you see it — the patient needs urgent intervention.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Pulmonary Hypertension on Echo",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal RVSP</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;35 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Mild PH</div><div class="nv-val">36–50 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Severe PH</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;50 mmHg</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">TR velocity (severe PH)</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;3.4 m/s</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>RVSP estimation:</strong> 4 × (TR Vmax)² + estimated RA pressure (RA pressure: IVC &lt;21mm + &gt;50% collapse = 5 mmHg; IVC &gt;21mm + &lt;50% collapse = 15 mmHg)</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>RV dilatation</strong> (RV:LV ratio &gt;1 in A4C view — normally RV is smaller than LV)</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>RV hypertrophy</strong> (RV free wall &gt;5mm)</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>Flattened/paradoxical septal motion</strong> — D-shaped LV on PSAX — RV overload causing septal flattening</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>TAPSE &lt;17mm</strong> — Reduced RV longitudinal systolic function (measure M-mode at TV annulus)</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--ec)"></span><div><strong>Reduced PA acceleration time</strong> (&lt;100ms) — "flying W" sign on PA PW Doppler in severe PH</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">D-shaped LV (interventricular septum flattens making LV look like a D instead of O on short axis) = RV pressure overload. Causes: pulmonary hypertension, massive PE, acute RV infarction. In PE: "60/60 sign" = RVSP 60mmHg + PA acceleration time &lt;60ms = acute PH from PE (not chronic). Useful when CTPA not immediately available.</div></div>`}
],

us:[
  {t:"USG Abdomen — Systematic Approach",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">Report structure — always describe all organs systematically</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">1</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Preparation</span> — Fasting 4–6 hours (reduces bowel gas). Full bladder for pelvic assessment. Patient supine, arms by sides. Use intercostal and subcostal windows.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">2</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Probe selection</span> — Curvilinear (3.5–5 MHz): adults, abdominal organs. Linear (7–15 MHz): superficial structures, thyroid, testes. Phased array: cardiac, narrow windows.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">3</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Echogenicity terminology</span> — Hyperechoic (brighter than reference — fat, calculi, gas). Hypoechoic (darker — fluid, most solid tumours). Anechoic (completely black — pure fluid, bile, urine). Isoechoic (same as reference — normal parenchyma).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">4</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Scan sequence</span> — Liver → Gallbladder → Common bile duct → Pancreas → Spleen → Kidneys (both) → Aorta → IVC → Bladder → (Pelvis in women) → Free fluid (Morrison's pouch, splenorenal, pelvis)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always use BOTH longitudinal and transverse scanning planes for every organ. A lesion visible in only one plane may be artefact. Posterior acoustic shadowing (black shadow behind structure) = calcification/stone/gas. Posterior acoustic enhancement (bright area behind) = fluid-filled structure (cyst, gallbladder).</div></div>`},

  {t:"Liver — Normal Values & Pathology",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal liver span (MCL)</div><div class="nv-val">12–15 cm (adults)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal echogenicity</div><div class="nv-val">Slightly hyperechoic to renal cortex</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Portal vein diameter</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;13 mm (&gt;13 = portal HTN)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal surface</div><div class="nv-val">Smooth, well-defined</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>USG appearance</th><th>Diagnosis</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Fatty liver (NAFLD/NASH)</td><td>Increased echogenicity (brighter than kidney and spleen), posterior attenuation (deep structures poorly seen), loss of vessel clarity. Graded I–III.</td><td>Grade I: mild. Grade II: moderate. Grade III: severe (posterior structures poorly seen, bright liver). Correlate with LFTs, metabolic syndrome.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cirrhosis</td><td>Coarse, heterogeneous echotexture, nodular surface ★, shrunken right lobe + hypertrophied caudate lobe, splenomegaly, ascites, portal hypertension signs</td><td>Advanced chronic liver disease. Check for complications: portal HTN, ascites, HCC screening (6-monthly AFP + USS).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Simple hepatic cyst</td><td>Anechoic, thin walls, posterior acoustic enhancement, no internal echoes. Round/oval.</td><td>Benign. No follow-up needed if &lt;3cm with typical features.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Haemangioma</td><td>Well-defined, hyperechoic (bright), homogeneous, usually &lt;3cm. Posterior acoustic enhancement may be present.</td><td>Most common benign liver lesion. Confirm with MRI if &gt;3cm or atypical features.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC)</td><td>Variable echogenicity. Hypoechoic (common), heterogeneous in large tumours. Halo sign (hypoechoic rim). Portal vein invasion (tumour thrombus).</td><td>Elevated AFP. Confirm with multiphasic CT or MRI (arterial enhancement + washout = LI-RADS 5). Refer hepatology.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Metastases</td><td>Multiple lesions, variable echogenicity. Bull's eye / target lesion (hyperechoic centre + hypoechoic halo) = classic. Often from GI, breast, lung primary.</td><td>Multiple hepatic lesions = metastases until proven otherwise. CT chest/abdomen/pelvis for staging.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Liver abscess</td><td>Focal hypoechoic/complex lesion with internal echoes and debris. Thick irregular walls. May have through-transmission.</td><td>Amoebic (single, right lobe, travel history) vs pyogenic (multiple). Fever, raised WBC, liver tenderness. Drainage ± antibiotics.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Portal hypertension</td><td>Portal vein &gt;13mm, spleno-portal axis dilatation, splenomegaly, ascites, collateral vessels (para-umbilical, perisplenic, oesophageal), reversal of portal flow (hepatofugal)</td><td>Cirrhosis ★, portal vein thrombosis. Check liver echotexture.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Gallbladder & Bile Ducts",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal GB wall thickness</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;3 mm (fasting)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal CBD diameter</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;6 mm (&lt;8mm post-cholecystectomy)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">CBD upper limit with age</div><div class="nv-val">1mm per decade after 60 yrs</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal GB size</div><div class="nv-val">Length &lt;9cm, width &lt;4cm</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>USG findings</th><th>Key features</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Gallstones (cholelithiasis)</td><td>Hyperechoic foci within GB lumen + posterior acoustic shadowing ★ + mobile (move with position change)</td><td>Sensitivity of USS for gallstones: ~95%. Shadowing is the key — a stone without shadowing = artefact. WES triad: Wall-Echo-Shadow.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Acute cholecystitis</td><td>Thickened GB wall &gt;3mm ★, pericholecystic fluid, sonographic Murphy's sign (probe pressure over GB causes pain) ★, distended GB, gallstone often present</td><td>Sonographic Murphy's sign: 90% sensitive + specific for acute cholecystitis. Fever + RUQ pain + USS findings = urgent surgical referral.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cholecystitis — empyema</td><td>Distended GB, internal echoes (pus), thickened wall, no acoustic shadowing within</td><td>Surgical emergency. Perforation risk.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GB polyp</td><td>Echogenic focus attached to GB wall, NON-mobile (fixed), NO shadowing</td><td>&lt;1cm: benign polyp, reassure. &gt;1cm or growing: refer for cholecystectomy (malignancy risk).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GB carcinoma</td><td>Irregular thickening of GB wall, soft tissue mass replacing GB, loss of plane between GB and liver, invasion of adjacent structures</td><td>Poor prognosis. Often found incidentally or late. Associated with gallstones, porcelain GB.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Biliary obstruction (CBD dilation)</td><td>CBD &gt;6mm (dilated). Intrahepatic biliary radicle (IHBR) dilatation (parallel channels — "double barrel shotgun" sign). May see cause: stone, mass at head of pancreas.</td><td>CBD dilation + jaundice = ERCP / MRCP urgently. Look for cause at head of pancreas (Ca head of pancreas) or CBD stone.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Choledocholithiasis</td><td>CBD &gt;6mm + echogenic focus with shadowing in CBD. Often difficult to visualise (bowel gas).</td><td>MRCP is more sensitive (95%). ERCP for treatment (stone extraction).</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The WES triad for gallstones: Wall of GB → Echo (hyperechoic stone) → Shadow (acoustic shadow). All three together = 100% specific for gallstone. Acoustic shadowing is essential — a hyperechoic focus without shadowing = polyp, sludge, or artefact (not stone). Always confirm mobility by repositioning the patient.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Kidneys — Normal Values & Pathology",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal kidney size</div><div class="nv-val">9–12 cm (length)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Cortical thickness</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;7 mm (normal)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal echogenicity</div><div class="nv-val">Less echogenic than liver/spleen</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Corticomedullary diff.</div><div class="nv-val">Clearly visible (lost in CKD)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>USG appearance</th><th>Diagnosis</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>CKD (chronic kidney disease)</td><td>Bilateral small kidneys (&lt;9cm), increased echogenicity (bright cortex = fibrosis), loss of corticomedullary differentiation, thinned cortex</td><td>Small echogenic kidneys = CKD until proven otherwise. Bilateral finding = systemic cause (diabetes, hypertension).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>AKI (acute kidney injury)</td><td>Normal or enlarged kidneys, normal or mildly increased echogenicity, preserved CMD. IVC may be flat (hypovolaemia) or distended (fluid overload).</td><td>Clinical correlation essential. USS helps exclude obstruction (post-renal AKI) — look for hydronephrosis.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hydronephrosis</td><td>Anechoic fluid in renal pelvis and calyces. Graded: mild (pelvis only), moderate (pelvis + major calyces), severe (cortical thinning).</td><td>Obstruction: stones ★ (look in ureter/VUJ/PUJ), BPH, malignancy, retroperitoneal fibrosis. Always look for cause.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Renal calculi</td><td>Hyperechoic foci with posterior acoustic shadowing within renal parenchyma, pelvis, or collecting system. Twinkling artefact on colour Doppler.</td><td>Sensitivity 70% (lower than CT KUB). Small stones (&lt;3mm) may be missed. Twinkling artefact on colour Doppler increases sensitivity.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Simple renal cyst</td><td>Anechoic, smooth thin walls, posterior acoustic enhancement, no internal echoes.</td><td>Bosniak I–II: benign. Bosniak III–IV: complex, septations, calcification = refer urology (malignancy risk).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Renal cell carcinoma (RCC)</td><td>Heterogeneous solid mass, often isoechoic or slightly hyperechoic, distorts renal contour. May have calcification.</td><td>Haematuria + flank mass + flank pain = classic triad. Contrast CT for staging. IVC invasion possible.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pyelonephritis</td><td>Enlarged kidney, loss of CMD, focal hypoechoic areas (oedema/abscess). May appear normal in early disease.</td><td>Clinical diagnosis. USS useful to detect complications (abscess, obstruction) and exclude differential diagnoses.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD)</td><td>Bilaterally enlarged kidneys with multiple cysts of varying sizes replacing normal parenchyma. Cysts also in liver.</td><td>Positive family history. Screen for berry aneurysm. Refer nephrology.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"Pancreas, Spleen & Aorta",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal pancreatic duct</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;3 mm (body)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal spleen size</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;13 cm (length)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal aorta (infrarenal)</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;3 cm (AAA if ≥3 cm)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Splenomegaly</div><div class="nv-val">&gt;13 cm = mild, &gt;16 cm = massive</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Organ / finding</th><th>USG appearance</th><th>Clinical significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Acute pancreatitis</td><td>Enlarged oedematous pancreas (hypoechoic, poorly defined borders), peripancreatic fluid, loss of surrounding fat planes. Often poor visualisation due to bowel gas.</td><td>CT abdomen (contrast enhanced) is gold standard for assessment and Balthazar grading. USS: check gallstones as cause.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chronic pancreatitis</td><td>Atrophic pancreas, heterogeneous echotexture, calcifications ★ (bright foci with shadowing), dilated pancreatic duct (&gt;3mm)</td><td>Alcohol ★ cause. Pancreatic duct dilation on USS = investigate with MRCP/ERCP. Risk of pancreatic cancer.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pancreatic carcinoma</td><td>Hypoechoic mass in head of pancreas ★ (most common), dilated CBD + pancreatic duct (double duct sign), vascular invasion</td><td>Double duct sign = dilated CBD + dilated pancreatic duct = carcinoma until proven otherwise. Urgent CECT + CA19-9.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Splenomegaly</td><td>&gt;13cm. Note: uniform (portal hypertension ★, haematological) vs heterogeneous (metastases, lymphoma, abscess, infarct)</td><td>Always report splenomegaly and suggest cause based on associated findings (portal hypertension signs, lymphadenopathy)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA)</td><td>Infrarenal aorta &gt;3cm (aneurysm), &gt;5.5cm = surgical threshold. Intraluminal thrombus (echogenic crescentic material). Measure at widest point.</td><td>Pulsatile abdominal mass. Rupture risk increases sharply &gt;5.5cm. USS screening for men &gt;65 who have smoked. Surveillance intervals: 3.0–4.4cm = annual, 4.5–5.4cm = 3-monthly, ≥5.5cm = vascular surgical referral.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Always scan the aorta in any patient with unexplained back/abdominal pain, hypotension, or pulsatile abdominal mass — ruptured AAA is rapidly fatal if missed. USS can confirm AAA in &lt;2 minutes at the bedside. Measure the OUTER WALL to OUTER WALL diameter in transverse plane — do not include thrombus in the measurement of the true lumen only.</div></div>`},

  {t:"Free Fluid & FAST Scan",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">FAST scan (Focused Assessment with Sonography in Trauma) — 4 windows in &lt;2 minutes</div></div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">1</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Morrison's pouch (RUQ)</span> — Space between liver and right kidney. FIRST and most sensitive site for intraabdominal free fluid in trauma. Any anechoic fluid = positive.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">2</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Splenorenal recess (LUQ)</span> — Space between spleen and left kidney. Also check splenodiaphragmatic space (fluid above spleen).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">3</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Pelvic (pouch of Douglas / rectovesical)</span> — Probe suprapubic transverse and longitudinal. Most dependent area — small volumes collect here first in upright position.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="sn" style="background:var(--us)">4</div>
      <div class="st"><span class="sh">Pericardial (subxiphoid)</span> — Subcostal 4-chamber view. Anechoic fluid around heart = haemopericardium / tamponade. Extended FAST (eFAST) adds bilateral lung sliding assessment for pneumothorax.</div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px"><thead><tr><th>Fluid appearance</th><th>Likely content</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Anechoic (completely black)</td><td>Transudate (ascites from portal hypertension, cardiac failure, nephrotic syndrome)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Low-level echoes (grey)</td><td>Exudate, blood, pus, chyle</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Complex (septations, debris)</td><td>Abscess, haemoperitoneum (clotted blood), complex exudate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Echogenic clot</td><td>Acute haemoperitoneum (fresh blood is anechoic, clotted blood is echogenic)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">FAST scan sensitivity for haemoperitoneum in trauma: ~80% (limited by operator skill, body habitus, bowel gas). A NEGATIVE FAST does NOT exclude intraabdominal injury — CT is required if clinical suspicion remains. In haemodynamically UNSTABLE patients with positive FAST → emergency surgery without CT.</div></div>`},

  {t:"USG Pelvis — Uterus, Ovaries & Bladder",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal uterus (reproductive)</div><div class="nv-val">7–9 cm (length), 4–5 cm (AP)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal ovary</div><div class="nv-val">3×2×2 cm (volume &lt;10 mL)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Normal endometrium (follicular)</div><div class="nv-val">4–8 mm (premenopausal)</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Post-menopausal endometrium</div><div class="nv-val">&lt;5 mm (bleeding if &gt;5 mm = investigate)</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>USG appearance</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Uterine fibroids (leiomyomata)</td><td>Well-defined, hypoechoic, solid masses arising from myometrium. May be submucosal (distort endometrium), intramural, subserosal. Calcification in old fibroids.</td><td>Most common pelvic tumour in women. Submucous = heavy bleeding. Subserous = pressure symptoms. Refer if symptomatic.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Endometrial thickening</td><td>Endometrial thickness &gt;5mm in postmenopausal woman (especially with bleeding)</td><td>Endometrial cancer until proven otherwise. Hysteroscopy + biopsy. In premenopausal: thickness varies with cycle — correlate with LMP.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ovarian cyst — simple</td><td>Anechoic, thin-walled, unilocular, posterior acoustic enhancement</td><td>&lt;5cm in reproductive age = physiological / follicular cyst. &gt;5cm or persisting: follow up. Post-menopausal: any cyst needs investigation.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Polycystic ovaries (PCO)</td><td>Enlarged ovaries (&gt;10mL volume), &gt;12 follicles 2–9mm per ovary (necklace sign), increased stromal echogenicity</td><td>PCOS = PCO morphology + oligo/anovulation + hyperandrogenism (2 of 3 criteria — Rotterdam). USS alone insufficient for diagnosis.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ectopic pregnancy</td><td>Empty uterine cavity + adnexal mass (ring of fire on Doppler = trophoblastic flow) + free fluid in POD</td><td>Surgical emergency. Beta-hCG positive + empty uterus = ectopic until proven otherwise. Immediate gynaecology referral.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dermoid cyst (teratoma)</td><td>Hyperechoic fat component, calcification (tooth), "tip of iceberg" sign, Rokitansky nodule</td><td>Most common ovarian tumour in young women. Risk of torsion. Laparoscopic cystectomy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ovarian torsion</td><td>Enlarged ovary (&gt;5cm), peripheral cysts, absent or reduced Doppler flow, free fluid. Whirlpool sign (twisted pedicle) on Doppler.</td><td>Surgical emergency. Absent flow is late sign — torsion can occur with normal flow. Clinical diagnosis + urgent gynaecology referral.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`}
],

sp:[
  {t:"MRI Spine — Reading the Report",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">MRI sequences — what each shows</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Sequence</th><th>Fluid signal</th><th>Fat signal</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>T1 weighted</td><td>Dark (hypointense)</td><td>Bright (hyperintense)</td><td>Anatomy, bone marrow (fat = bright), haemorrhage (subacute), disc herniation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T2 weighted</td><td>Bright (hyperintense)</td><td>Intermediate</td><td>Spinal cord pathology ★, CSF (bright), disc (bright if normal hydration), nerve root compression, oedema</td></tr>
      <tr><td>STIR (fat suppressed T2)</td><td>Bright</td><td>Dark (suppressed)</td><td>Bone marrow oedema ★ (stress fractures, metastases, discitis — bright signal in bone)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>T1 + Gadolinium</td><td>Variable</td><td>Bright</td><td>Tumours, infection (abscess ring enhances), post-op scarring vs recurrent disc (enhances = scar, doesn't = disc)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px"><thead><tr><th>MRI finding</th><th>Description</th><th>Diagnosis</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Disc prolapse (herniation)</td><td>Posterior disc material beyond disc space margins. Graded: bulge → protrusion → extrusion → sequestration.</td><td>Correlate with clinical symptoms. Not all MRI disc herniations cause symptoms. Clinical + imaging together decide management.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Canal stenosis</td><td>Reduced AP diameter of spinal canal. &lt;10mm (cervical) = severe stenosis. Trefoil configuration in lumbar stenosis.</td><td>Neurogenic claudication (lumbar): bilateral leg pain on walking, relieved by sitting/bending forward. Correlate with history.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Modic changes</td><td>Type I: T1 dark/T2 bright (bone marrow oedema — acute inflammation). Type II: T1 bright/T2 bright (fatty replacement — chronic). Type III: T1 dark/T2 dark (sclerosis)</td><td>Adjacent to degenerate disc. Modic I = active inflammation = may respond to treatment. Modic II = chronic/end-stage.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cord compression / myelopathy</td><td>T2 signal change (bright) within spinal cord at level of compression = cord oedema/myelomalacia</td><td>Neurological emergency if acute. Surgical decompression needed. Do NOT manipulate spine if cord signal change present.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Discitis / osteomyelitis</td><td>T2 bright + STIR bright at disc and adjacent endplates + loss of endplate definition + enhancing disc on T1+Gd</td><td>Spinal infection. Fever + back pain + elevated CRP/ESR. Blood cultures before antibiotics. Refer spinal team.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">The most important MRI finding to never miss: T2 signal change WITHIN the spinal cord (not just compression — but cord signal change). This means myelopathy — the cord is being damaged. If this is present alongside clinical signs (upper motor neuron signs below lesion), urgent neurosurgical referral is required. Do NOT physiotherapy or manipulate until this is assessed.</div></div>`},

  {t:"MRI Knee — Key Findings",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Structure</th><th>Normal appearance</th><th>Abnormal findings</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Menisci (medial and lateral)</td><td>Homogeneously dark (black) on all sequences. Bow-tie appearance on sagittal view (peripheral meniscus), triangle on coronal.</td><td>Grade I: round T2 signal (doesn't reach surface — normal in young). Grade II: linear signal doesn't reach surface (degeneration). Grade III: signal reaches articular surface = TEAR ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>ACL (anterior cruciate ligament)</td><td>Dark, taut band coursing from posterior lateral femoral condyle to anterior tibial plateau. Steep Blumensaat's line angle.</td><td>Complete tear: discontinuity, T2 bright signal, lax/absent ligament. Partial: thinned, high signal. Secondary signs: lateral compartment bone bruise (pivot shift injury).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>PCL</td><td>Dark, thick, arched band posterior to ACL. Normally has homogeneous low signal.</td><td>Tear: high signal, discontinuity. PCL injuries: dashboard injury (posterior knee impact).</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Articular cartilage</td><td>T2 bright, smooth, uniform thickness over femoral condyles and tibial plateau.</td><td>Focal thinning, fissuring, subchondral bone exposed = OA. ICRS grading I–IV for cartilage defects.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bone marrow oedema</td><td>Dark on T1, bright on STIR/T2 fat-sat</td><td>Bone bruise (trauma), AVN, stress fracture, subchondral insufficiency fracture (elderly women)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Baker's cyst</td><td>Fluid-filled cystic structure posterior to knee joint, in gastrocnemius-semimembranosus bursa</td><td>Secondary to intra-articular pathology (OA, meniscal tear). Treat the underlying cause.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">O'Donoghue's unhappy triad: ACL tear + MCL tear + medial meniscus tear from valgus + rotational force (tackled from outside in football). If you see a lateral femoral condyle bone bruise + ACL tear on MRI, always look carefully at the medial meniscus — the pivot shift mechanism commonly catches the posterior horn of the medial meniscus.</div></div>`},

  {t:"CT Abdomen — Tissue Windows",c:`
    <div class="alert a-blu"><div class="a-label">Different window settings reveal different structures on the same CT scan</div></div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Window</th><th>W/L settings</th><th>What's visible</th><th>Use for</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Soft tissue window</td><td>W: 350–400 / L: 20–60</td><td>Abdominal organs, vessels, lymph nodes, soft tissue masses</td><td>Default window. Organ pathology, masses, collections.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lung window</td><td>W: 1500 / L: –600</td><td>Air-filled structures, lung parenchyma, pneumothorax</td><td>Pulmonary lesions, free air under diaphragm, pneumoperitoneum</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Bone window</td><td>W: 1800–2000 / L: 400–500</td><td>Cortical bone, trabecular pattern, fractures, sclerotic/lytic lesions</td><td>Spine fractures, bony metastases, pelvic fractures</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Liver window</td><td>W: 150 / L: 50–75</td><td>Subtle liver lesions (small haemangiomas, early metastases)</td><td>Hepatic lesion characterisation. Subtle hypodense lesions better seen.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Vascular/CTA window</td><td>W: 600–700 / L: 200–300</td><td>Contrast-enhanced vessels, aneurysms, dissection flap</td><td>Aortic aneurysm measurement, PE (pulmonary window + mediastinal), mesenteric ischaemia</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <table class="tbl" style="margin-top:10px"><thead><tr><th>CT phase</th><th>Timing post-contrast</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Pre-contrast (plain)</td><td>No contrast</td><td>Calcification (stones, calcified nodes), baseline density, haemorrhage (bright on plain)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Arterial phase</td><td>~25–35 seconds</td><td>HCC (arterial enhancement), aortic aneurysm/dissection, active haemorrhage</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Portal venous phase</td><td>~60–80 seconds</td><td>Most abdominal pathology ★ (metastases appear as hypodense filling defects), liver parenchyma, bowel wall enhancement</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Delayed / Excretory phase</td><td>~5–10 minutes</td><td>Urinary tract (IVU-phase for renal collecting system, ureter opacification, bladder lesions)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>`},

  {t:"DEXA Scan — Bone Mineral Density",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">T-score normal</div><div class="nv-val">≥ −1.0</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Osteopenia</div><div class="nv-val">−1.0 to −2.5</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Osteoporosis</div><div class="nv-val">≤ −2.5</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">Severe osteoporosis</div><div class="nv-val">≤ −2.5 + fragility fracture</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="plist">
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--sp)"></span><div><strong>T-score</strong> = comparison to YOUNG HEALTHY ADULT peak bone mass. Used for post-menopausal women and men &gt;50 years. One SD below peak = 10× increase in fracture risk.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--sp)"></span><div><strong>Z-score</strong> = comparison to AGE-MATCHED peers. Use in premenopausal women, men &lt;50, children. Z-score &lt;−2.0 = "below expected for age" → look for secondary cause.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--sp)"></span><div><strong>Sites measured</strong> — Lumbar spine (L1–L4) + proximal femur (femoral neck + total hip). Use the LOWEST T-score of any site for diagnosis. Forearm (radius) used if hip/spine not measurable.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--sp)"></span><div><strong>FRAX tool</strong> — Integrates T-score + clinical risk factors (age, sex, BMI, previous fracture, steroid use, family history, smoking, alcohol, RA, secondary osteoporosis) to calculate 10-year fracture probability. Use FRAX to decide whether to treat.</div></div>
      <div class="pi"><span class="pd" style="background:var(--sp)"></span><div><strong>Treatment threshold</strong> — FRAX 10-year major osteoporotic fracture risk ≥20% OR hip fracture risk ≥3% = treat with bisphosphonate (alendronate first line). Always add calcium 1000mg/day + Vitamin D 800 IU/day.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pearl</div><div class="pt">Artefacts that falsely ELEVATE DEXA T-score: aortic calcification (overlying spine), vertebral compression fractures (collapsed vertebra has higher density), osteophytes (spondylosis adds apparent density). A T-score of −1.5 in a 75-year-old with severe spondylosis may actually represent severe osteoporosis — lateral DEXA or forearm scan avoids this. Always read the DEXA report alongside the plain X-ray findings.</div></div>`}
],

ecg:[
  {t:"ECG Interpretation — Systematic 8-Step Approach",badge:"Foundation",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">Always use the same systematic approach — never skip steps</div>A systematic method prevents missing life-threatening findings hidden behind a seemingly obvious diagnosis.</div>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Rate</span> — Regular rhythm: 300 ÷ large squares between R-R. Quick method: 300→150→100→75→60→50. Normal = 60–100 bpm.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Rhythm</span> — Regular or irregular? Irregularly irregular = AF ★. Is every P followed by QRS?</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">3</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">P wave</span> — Present? Upright in I and II (sinus rhythm). Peaked = P pulmonale. Bifid = P mitrale (LAE). PR interval: 0.12–0.20 sec.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">4</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">PR interval</span> — Normal 0.12–0.20 sec. Short (&lt;0.12) = WPW/accessory pathway. Long (&gt;0.20) = 1st degree HB. Progressive lengthening = Mobitz I (Wenckebach).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">5</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">QRS complex</span> — Normal &lt;0.12 sec. Wide QRS = BBB, VT, hyperkalaemia, paced rhythm. Axis: Normal −30° to +90°. LAD = −30° to −90°. RAD = +90° to +180°.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">6</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">ST segment ★</span> — ST elevation ≥1mm limb leads / ≥2mm chest leads in ≥2 contiguous leads = STEMI until proven otherwise. ST depression = ischaemia, posterior MI, digoxin. Saddle-back vs coved = Brugada.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">7</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">T wave</span> — Normally upright in I, II, V3–V6. Inverted = ischaemia, PE, RVH. Peaked = hyperkalaemia ★. Flat = hypokalaemia, hypothyroidism.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#c0392b">8</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">QT interval</span> — QTc = QT ÷ √(R-R in seconds). Normal QTc &lt;440ms (men), &lt;460ms (women). Prolonged QTc = Torsades risk.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Complete all 8 steps every time</div><div class="pt">A patient with AF can also have ST elevation. A patient with LBBB may also have hyperkalaemia. "Spot diagnosis" ECG reading without a systematic approach misses 20–30% of significant findings. Complete all steps before concluding.</div></div>`},
  {t:"STEMI — Territory, Culprit Artery & Localisation",badge:"Emergency ★",c:`
    <div class="alert a-red"><div class="a-label">STEMI = ST elevation ≥1mm limb leads / ≥2mm chest leads in ≥2 contiguous leads. New LBBB with chest pain = treat as STEMI.</div>Door-to-balloon target ≤90 min. Every 30 min delay = 8% ↑ in 1-year mortality.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Territory</th><th>ST elevation leads</th><th>Reciprocal changes</th><th>Culprit artery</th><th>Key complications</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Anterior ★</td><td>V1–V4</td><td>None typically</td><td>LAD (left anterior descending)</td><td>LV failure, cardiogenic shock, LBBB, VT/VF</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Anterolateral</td><td>I, aVL, V4–V6</td><td>III, aVF</td><td>LAD or LCx (diagonal branch)</td><td>LV dysfunction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Inferior ★</td><td>II, III, aVF</td><td>I, aVL</td><td>RCA (right coronary) 80%</td><td>Heart block 2nd/3rd degree, RV infarction</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Right ventricular</td><td>V1, V4R ★</td><td>V5, V6 depression</td><td>RCA proximal</td><td>Hypotension with inferior MI — AVOID nitrates ★</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Posterior</td><td>ST depression + tall R/T in V1–V3 ★</td><td>V1–V3 depression IS the reciprocal</td><td>RCA or LCx</td><td>Often missed — do posterior leads V7–V9</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lateral</td><td>I, aVL, V5–V6</td><td>III, aVF</td><td>LCx (left circumflex)</td><td>Often silent, late presentation</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Inferior MI + hypotension = RV infarction until proven otherwise</div><div class="pt">RV infarct occurs in 40% of inferior STEMIs. Triad: hypotension + clear lungs + raised JVP (Kussmaul's sign). ECG: ST elevation in V4R (right-sided lead). CRITICAL: NO nitrates — preload-dependent RV, nitrates cause catastrophic BP drop. Treatment: IV fluids 1L, primary PCI urgently.</div></div>`},
  {t:"Arrhythmia Recognition — Quick Reference",badge:"Essential",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Arrhythmia</th><th>Rate</th><th>Rhythm</th><th>P wave</th><th>QRS</th><th>Key ECG feature</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Sinus tachycardia</td><td>100–150</td><td>Regular</td><td>Upright 1:1</td><td>Normal</td><td>Normal P before every QRS — find the cause (pain, fever, PE, anaemia)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>AF ★</td><td>Varies 100–160</td><td>Irregularly irregular ★</td><td>Absent — fibrillatory baseline</td><td>Normal or wide</td><td>No P waves, chaotic baseline, variable R-R</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Atrial flutter</td><td>Atrial 300, ventricular 150</td><td>Regular (2:1 or 4:1)</td><td>Sawtooth ★ in II, III, aVF</td><td>Normal</td><td>Sawtooth flutter waves at 300/min. 2:1 block = ventricular 150.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SVT (AVNRT)</td><td>150–250</td><td>Regular</td><td>Buried or retrograde</td><td>Narrow</td><td>Sudden onset/offset. P buried in QRS or pseudo-R in V1.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VT ★</td><td>100–250</td><td>Regular</td><td>AV dissociation</td><td>Wide &gt;0.12s bizarre</td><td>Wide complex tachycardia = VT until proven otherwise. Fusion/capture beats = VT.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>VF ★★</td><td>Chaotic</td><td>Chaotic</td><td>None</td><td>Chaotic</td><td>No cardiac output → immediate defibrillation + CPR</td></tr>
      <tr><td>1° Heart block</td><td>Normal</td><td>Regular</td><td>Normal</td><td>Normal</td><td>PR &gt;0.20 sec, every P conducts</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2° Mobitz I (Wenckebach)</td><td>Slow</td><td>Regularly irregular</td><td>Progressive PR lengthening → dropped QRS</td><td>Normal</td><td>Progressive PR prolongation → dropped beat. Benign, AV nodal level.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2° Mobitz II ★</td><td>Slow</td><td>Regularly irregular</td><td>Constant PR → sudden drop</td><td>Often wide</td><td>Sudden dropped QRS without PR change. Infranodal, high risk → pacemaker.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Complete (3°) HB ★</td><td>Ventricular 20–40</td><td>Independent P and QRS</td><td>Present at own rate, no relation to QRS</td><td>Wide escape</td><td>AV dissociation — P and QRS march independently → pacemaker urgently</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Wide complex tachycardia — assume VT first</div><div class="pt">VT accounts for 80% of wide complex tachycardias. NEVER give verapamil to presumed SVT that is actually VT — can cause haemodynamic collapse and death. Haemodynamically unstable → synchronised DC cardioversion regardless of diagnosis. Brugada criteria help differentiate in stable patients.</div></div>`},
  {t:"BBB (Bundle Branch Block) — LBBB vs RBBB",badge:"Diagnosis",c:`
    <div class="nv-grid">
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">RBBB criteria</div><div class="nv-val">QRS &gt;0.12s · RSR' "rabbit ears" in V1 ★ · Wide S wave in I, V6</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LBBB criteria</div><div class="nv-val">QRS &gt;0.12s · Broad notched R in I, V5, V6 ★ · Absent septal Q in I, V5, V6</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">RBBB significance</div><div class="nv-val">May be normal variant. New RBBB + anterior chest pain = septal STEMI.</div></div>
      <div class="nv-card"><div class="nv-label">LBBB significance ★</div><div class="nv-val">Always pathological. New LBBB + chest pain = treat as STEMI. Masks ST changes.</div></div>
    </div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>RBBB</th><th>LBBB</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>V1 morphology</td><td>RSR' (rabbit ears) ★</td><td>Deep broad QS or rS (W pattern)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>V6 morphology</td><td>Wide S wave (W pattern)</td><td>Broad tall R, no Q (M pattern)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lead I</td><td>Wide S wave</td><td>Broad notched R (M pattern)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sgarbossa criteria (LBBB + MI)</td><td>N/A</td><td>Concordant ST ≥1mm · Concordant ST depression V1–V3 · Discordant ST ≥5mm → STEMI in LBBB</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 WiLLiaM MaRRoW — fastest BBB mnemonic</div><div class="pt"><b>WiLLiaM:</b> W in V1, M in V6 = LBBB. <b>MaRRoW:</b> M in V1 (RSR'), W in V6 = RBBB. LBBB: look for M pattern in V5–V6 (tall broad R). RBBB: look for rabbit ears (RSR') in V1.</div></div>`},
  {t:"ECG in Electrolyte Abnormalities",badge:"Critical",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Electrolyte</th><th>Change</th><th>ECG findings (sequence)</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Potassium</td><td>Hyperkalaemia ★</td><td>Peaked T waves → PR prolongation → P wave flattening → wide QRS → sine wave → VF. K⁺ &gt;6.5 = cardiac emergency.</td><td>IV calcium gluconate FIRST (membrane stabilisation) → insulin+dextrose → salbutamol neb → dialysis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Potassium</td><td>Hypokalaemia</td><td>Flat/inverted T → U waves ★ (after T in V2–V3) → ST depression → prolonged QU → VT/TdP risk</td><td>IV/oral KCl. If prominent U waves → replenish Mg first (Mg required for K retention)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Calcium</td><td>Hypocalcaemia</td><td>Prolonged QT (long ST segment) → TdP risk</td><td>IV calcium gluconate 10ml 10% slowly. Check Mg and K.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Calcium</td><td>Hypercalcaemia</td><td>Short QT interval ★ · Short ST segment · Bradycardia · Osborn J waves (severe)</td><td>IV saline + furosemide. Bisphosphonates if malignancy-related.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Magnesium</td><td>Hypomagnesaemia</td><td>Flat T, U waves, prolonged QT — causes refractory hypokalaemia</td><td>IV MgSO4 2g over 10 min. Must correct Mg before K replacement is effective.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 U wave = hypokalaemia hallmark</div><div class="pt">The U wave is a small deflection AFTER the T wave, best seen in V2–V3. Prominent U waves (taller than T wave) = significant hypokalaemia. Critical: the QU interval is prolonged in hypokalaemia — automated QTc calculations may incorrectly measure QU as QT. Always interpret QT manually in hypokalaemia.</div></div>`},
  {t:"ECG Patterns — Cardiac Conditions Quick Reference",badge:"Reference",c:`
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Condition</th><th>Key ECG findings</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>LVH</td><td>Sokolow-Lyon: SV1 + RV5 ≥35mm ★. ST depression + T inversion V5–V6 (strain pattern).</td><td>Hypertension, aortic stenosis, HCM</td></tr>
      <tr><td>RVH</td><td>R &gt; S in V1, RAD (&gt;+90°), P pulmonale, ST depression V1–V3</td><td>PE, pulmonary hypertension, cor pulmonale, mitral stenosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Pericarditis ★</td><td>Saddle-shaped ST elevation ALL leads (global) ★ · PR depression in II ★ · No reciprocal changes · Elevated PR in aVR</td><td>Viral, post-cardiac surgery. Treat: NSAIDs + colchicine.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Massive PE</td><td>S1Q3T3 ★ · Sinus tachycardia (most common) · New RBBB · T inversion V1–V4</td><td>S1Q3T3 present in only 20% — sinus tachycardia is the most common ECG finding in PE</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cardiac tamponade</td><td>Low voltage ALL leads ★ · Electrical alternans (QRS axis alternates beat-to-beat) ★ · Sinus tachycardia</td><td>Beck's triad: ↓BP + ↑JVP + muffled heart sounds. Pulsus paradoxus &gt;10mmHg.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Brugada syndrome</td><td>Type 1 (diagnostic): Coved ST ≥2mm in V1–V2 + RBBB morphology ★. Type 2 (saddle-back) = not diagnostic alone.</td><td>Hereditary channelopathy. Risk of VF/SCD in young patients. ICD for symptomatic cases.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Long QT (LQTS)</td><td>QTc &gt;440ms men, &gt;460ms women ★. QTc &gt;500ms = high TdP risk.</td><td>Congenital or acquired (drugs: amiodarone, haloperidol, macrolides). TdP = polymorphic VT.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>WPW</td><td>Short PR (&lt;0.12s) ★ · Delta wave (slurred QRS upstroke) ★ · Wide QRS</td><td>NEVER give AV nodal blockers (adenosine, verapamil, digoxin) in pre-excited AF → VF risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hypothermia</td><td>Osborn (J) waves ★ at QRS-ST junction in V4–V6 · Bradycardia · AF · Shivering artefact</td><td>J waves at &lt;32°C. Rewarm slowly — risk of VF during rewarming.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Pericarditis vs STEMI — the critical distinction</div><div class="pt">Both cause ST elevation. Key: (1) Pericarditis = global ST in ALL leads, no reciprocal changes + PR depression in II. (2) STEMI = regional ST with reciprocal depression elsewhere. (3) Spodick's ratio: ST:T amplitude in V6 &gt;0.25 = pericarditis. (4) PR depression in lead II is pathognomonic of pericarditis. When in doubt → treat as STEMI until troponin and echo confirm.</div></div>`}
]

};
