  {t:"Alcohol Reduction — Clinical Protocol",badge:"Lifestyle Medicine",c:`
    <div class="alert a-grn"><div class="a-label">AUDIT — Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test</div>Score 0-7: Low risk. Score 8-15: Harmful use — brief intervention. Score 16-19: High risk — counselling. Score 20+: Possible dependence — refer specialist.</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Standard drink</th><th>Units</th><th>Low-risk limits</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Beer 330ml (5%)</td><td>1.65 units</td><td>Men and women: under 14 units/week</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wine 175ml (12%)</td><td>2.1 units</td><td>Max 4 units per occasion (men), 3 units (women)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spirits 25ml (40%)</td><td>1 unit</td><td>At least 2 alcohol-free days per week</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">1</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Brief Intervention — FRAMES</span> Feedback (personalised risk). Responsibility (change is their choice). Advice (clear recommendation). Menu (options for reduction). Empathy (non-judgemental). Self-efficacy (express confidence they can do it). 5 minutes — reduces drinking 15-30% at 12 months.</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">2</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Naturopathic Support</span> NAC 600mg BD — replenishes glutathione depleted by alcohol. Milk thistle 200mg TDS — hepatoprotective. B vitamins especially B1 thiamine — depleted by alcohol (causes Wernicke's). Magnesium 400mg — heavily depleted. Kudzu root 750-1500mg/day — reduces alcohol craving (RCT evidence).</div></div>
      <div class="step"><div class="sn" style="background:#0e7490">W</div><div class="st"><span class="sh">Warning — Dependent Drinkers</span> Alcohol withdrawal in physically dependent drinkers can be FATAL (seizures, delirium tremens). Identify dependence with CAGE questionnaire. Morning drinking or tremors on abstinence = refer for medically supervised detoxification. Never advise sudden cessation in suspected dependence without medical supervision.</div></div>
    </div>`},
  {t:"Nature Therapy & Social Connection — Evidence Guide",badge:"Lifestyle Medicine",c:`
    <div style="font-weight:700;color:var(--em-dk);margin-bottom:6px">NATURE THERAPY (SHINRIN-YOKU)</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Intervention</th><th>Dose</th><th>Effect</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Forest bathing (Shinrin-yoku)</td><td>2 hours in forested area 2x/week</td><td>Cortisol down 12%, NK cell activity up 40%, BP down 7/4 mmHg, anxiety down</td><td>Strong — multiple Japanese RCTs. Effect lasts 7-30 days post-exposure.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Green exercise (any outdoor activity)</td><td>5 minutes in green environment</td><td>Self-esteem and mood improve within 5 minutes — not proportional to duration</td><td>Strong — UK meta-analysis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Blue space (coast, rivers, lakes)</td><td>120 minutes/week total</td><td>Better health, lower psychological distress. 120 min/week is the threshold.</td><td>Good — White et al. 2019, 20,000 participants</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Gardening / Horticultural therapy</td><td>30 min active gardening</td><td>Cortisol recovery faster than reading. Depression and anxiety reduction in elderly. Mycobacterium vaccae in soil — natural antidepressant.</td><td>Good</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div style="font-weight:700;color:var(--em-dk);margin:10px 0 6px">SOCIAL CONNECTION — THE FORGOTTEN VITAL SIGN</div>
    <table class="tbl"><thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Loneliness increases mortality by 26% — equivalent to smoking 15 cigarettes/day</td><td>Holt-Lunstad meta-analysis, 3.4 million participants</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Social isolation raises dementia risk 60%, depression risk 50%</td><td>Multiple large cohort studies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Strong social connections associated with 50% lower mortality over follow-up</td><td>Berkman and Syme, Oakland study</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    <div class="pearl"><div class="pl">🟡 Social Prescribing</div><div class="pt">Now mainstream in UK NHS — GPs refer to community activities, volunteer groups, arts programmes. As a BNYS practitioner: screen for loneliness (UCLA Loneliness Scale). Prescribe: group yoga or meditation classes, community gardens, volunteer work, faith communities, pet ownership (reduces BP and loneliness), regular face-to-face contact. Video calls are better than nothing but inferior to in-person contact — oxytocin (bonding hormone) requires physical presence for maximum release.</div></div>`}
